<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vanuatu     12-20 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vanuatu,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Arrested, Charged With Inciting Mutiny</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT VILA, Vanuatu (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President George Sokomanu was arrested
on Wednesday and charged with inciting mutiny in a deepening
political crisis in this South Pacific state, the Australian
Associated Press news agency reported.
   Sokomanu faces a maximum sentence of life imprisonment, and the
agency quoted Public Prosecutor John Baxter-Wright as saying
additional charges would be levied against him.
   On Tuesday, Parliament acted to remove Sokomanu from office for
his failed attempt two days earlier to form an interim government
pending national elections in February. Legislators accused him of
treason, gross misconduct and other major offenses.
   Sokomanu tried last Friday to dissolve Parliament and to dismiss
elected Prime Minister Walter Lini and replace with Sokomanu's
nephew, flamboyant, Australian-educated politician Barak Sope. Lini
has been in power since Vanuatu, formerly known as the New Hebrides
and under Anglo-French rule, became independent in 1980.
   The AAP said the president was charged during a five-minute
appearance at Port Vila Magistrate's Court.
   It said Senior Magistrate Dawn Barcinski asked the president if
he had anything to say, and he replied: ``Your Honor, I would like
to see my lawyer first.''
   The president, clad in a sport shirt and shorts, waved to
spectators as he walked from the court and was led away to a police
vehicle, guarded by about 12 uniformed officers, the AAP said.
   Four members of the abortive interim government, including Sope,
already have been charged with sedition.
   All five men are scheduled to apply for bail later Wednesday
before the Supreme Court.
   The crisis culminates a yearlong power struggle between Lini and
Sope, whose foes blamed him for recent outbreaks of violence in his
bid for leadership.
   This island nation of 130,000 people lies 1,200 miles northeast
of Brisbane, Australia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
