<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0728 12-20 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0728,0695</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Ouimet and Fritz; Separates moved for AMs as a0640 on
Robinson and a0743 on Ouimet. Ouimet also moved on the business
wire. McCallum also moved on the sports wire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Max Robinson</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Max Robinson, who became the first black news
anchorman on American network television but soon saw his life beset
by personal and professional problems, died Tuesday from
complications of AIDS. He was 49.
   Robinson started his broadcasting career as a disc jockey in
Richmond, Va. He moved to Washington in 1965.
   In 1978, Robinson left Washington television station WTOP, where
he had won top ratings as an anchorman for a decade, to join ABC as
the first black to anchor a network news show. He co-anchored the
ABC Evening News from Chicago with Peter Jennings in London and
Frank Reynolds in Washington.
   Robinson's tenure at ABC was troubled as he zealously waged a
battle against racism at the network. He charged the network with
racism in a speech at Smith College in 1981.
   After Reynolds' death in 1983, Jennings was made sole anchor of
the newscasts, and Robinson was relegated to weekend anchor stints
and news briefs. In 1984, he joined Chicago television station WMAQ.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John McCallum</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John D. McCallum, a former syndicated sports
columnist and author of 35 books, died Saturday of cardiac arrest at
age 64.
   McCallum wrote for Tacoma newspapers for a number of years and
then moved to New York. He wrote a sports column for the Newspaper
Enterprise Association, a national news service.
   McCallum was best known for works on sports figures, including
``The Tiger Wore Spikes,'' about baseball great Ty Cobb, and ``Dumb
Dan Morgan,'' about a boxer in the Jack Dempsey era.
   He also wrote books on figures such as the late Dwight
Eisenhower, actress Grace Kelly and former Teamsters president Dave
Beck.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Joseph Nixon</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WABASH, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph H. Nixon, a chairman emeritus of Nixon
newspaper chain, died Tuesday after a short illness. He was 75.
   Nixon began his career as a newspaperman in 1934 at the Michigan
City Dispatch, owned by his father, Don Nixon.
   He later managed the Elizabethton, Tenn., Star, the Wabash
Plain-Dealer and Peru Daily Tribune for the Nixon chain. He returned
to Wabash in 1954, where he was president and publisher of four
Indiana newspapers.
   Nixon became chairman of Nixon Enterprises, Inc., the parent
company of Nixon Newspapers Inc., in 1980. He was later named
chairman emeritus and continued working until two months ago.
   The Nixon chain, based in Peru, Ind., publishes 11 newspapers in
Indiana, Illinois and Louisiana with a combined circulation of more
than 85,000.
   Nixon Enterprises also owns a commercial printing division, a
cable television franchise in Frankfort and other publications.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Alphonse Ouimet</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alphonse Ouimet, a former president of the
Canadian Broadcasting Corp. who helped introduce television to
Canada 40 years ago, died Tuesday. He was 80.
   Ouimet went to work for the CBC as an engineer when it was
founded 52 years ago. In 1958, he became president and held that
post for nine years. In the 1940s, he studied the operation of
television in the United States and Europe, and played a major role
in introducing it to Canadian audiences.
   After leaving the CBC, Ouimet headed a UNESCO conference on
satellite technology in broadcasting and served as president of
Telesat Canada from 1969 to 1980.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Emanuel Fritz</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emanuel Fritz, a forestry and
conservation authority who was known as ``Mr. Redwood'' because of
his expertise, died Thursday at age 102.
   Fritz helped create California's state forest program and was
co-founder of the Regional Parks Association, the forerunner of the
East Bay Regional Park system near the San Francisco Bay.
   He was a professor of forestry emeritus at the University of
California at Berkeley. He joined the faculty in 1919, retiring in
1954. Frtiz lived the longest of any present or former professor at
Berkeley, the university announced Thursday.
</TEXT>
