<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Quake-DonorWarning     12-20 0144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quake-Donor Warning,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armenian Group Vows Background Checks of Fund Raisers After Warning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national Armenian relief group said Tuesday it
will conduct background checks of all its fund raisers after
learning that a Boston volunteer had a criminal record.
   The Armenian Assembly of America, a group with 300 members and
offices in Washington and Los Angeles, said that in the hectic days
following the Dec. 7 quake, ``background checks were not conducted
on those who had volunteered to assist.''
   One of the volunteers at the Northeast Relief Center in Boston, a
group affiliated with the Armenian Assembly, was a man convicted of
violating state drug laws, authorities said.
   When the man appeared on a WBZ-TV newscast to appeal for
donations and medical supplies, Woburn police spotted him. The man
later was ordered out of the relief office, officials said.
</TEXT>
