<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 2350EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nielsens     12-20 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brady Bunch Reunion Pulls CBS Out Of Ratings' Cellar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``A Very Brady Christmas,'' CBS' reunion of the
1970s sitcom family that lived on ABC, was this season's top-rated
made-for-TV movie and gave CBS a Christmas gift _ a break from third
place in the ratings.
   It was the first time this season that CBS finished out of last
place.
   NBC won the week, and ``The Cosby Show'' was the No. 1, the A.C.
Nielsen Co. said.
   But ``A Very Brady Christmas,'' broadcast Sunday, was last week's
No. 2 prime-time show, with a 25.1 rating and a 39 share, lifting
CBS to second place over ABC, where ``The Brady Bunch'' ran from
1969-1974.
   Each rating point represents 904,000 homes with television. The
share is a percentage of sets in use.
   The rest of the top 10 were: ``A Different World,'' NBC;
``Cheers,'' NBC; ``Roseanne,'' ABC; ``Who's the Boss?'' ABC;
``Golden Girls,'' NBC; ``L.A. Law,'' NBC; ``Murder, She Wrote,''
CBS; and ``Dear John,'' NBC, tied with ``60 Minutes,'' CBS.
   NBC's average prime-time rating last week was 15.4. CBS had 13.1
and ABC 11.8.
   ``ABC World News Tonight'' won the close news race with an
average rating of 11.0 and a 20 share. ``NBC Nightly News'' got out
of third, possibly due to anchorman Tom Brokaw's travels to Armenia
and Geneva, and had a 10.9 and 20, edging the ``CBS Evening News,''
with a 10.7 and 19.
   NBC's ``Midnight Caller'' episode that drew fire from homosexual
rights groups because of its storyline about a man with AIDS
purposely engaging in high-risk sex, ranked 33rd, about what it has
been ranking this season.
   Jerry Lewis began a guest-star stint on CBS' ``Wiseguy,''
boosting the crime drama to 32nd place.
   The lowest-rated network shows last week were: ``Davy Crockett,''
``Mission Impossible,'' ``Moscow Circus,'' ``Annie McGuire,'' ``West
57th,'' ``Simon & Simon,'' ``TV 101,'' ``Murphy's Law,''
``Knightwatch'' and ``Burning Issues.''
</TEXT>
