<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Korea 1stLd-Writethru a0630 12-20 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0630,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roh Frees 281 Political Prisoners; 1,581 Others Rehabilitated</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with new material and editing, UPDATING with
prisoners freed. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo's government
freed 281 political prisoners throughout South Korea on Wednesday
and restored the civil rights of 1,581 others in a sweeping amnesty
to restore political peace.
   Justice Ministry officials said prison terms of 92 other
political prisoners were reduced and 61 radical students were
removed from police wanted lists.
   The government ordered the amnesty involving 2,015 of what it
called ``politically motivated offenders'' as part of efforts to
defuse a nationwide furor over demands that former President Chun
Doo-hwan be punished for human rights abuses and corruption under
his authoritarian regime.
   Roh appealed to the nation last month to forgive Chun and
promised to free political prisoners as part of a series of measures
to wipe out vestiges of Chun's government. Roh, a former general and
ally of Chun, has pledged to introduce full democracy.
   Dissident groups accused Roh of betraying his promise to free all
political prisoners and claimed about 300 remained in jail.
   Justice officials said 224 ``anti-state criminals'' still were
behind bars, but said nearly all were Communist North Korean spies
or dissidents convicted of violent crimes.
   The main political opposition parties welcomed the amnesty. They
had frequently demanded such action as a way toward national
reconciliation and democracy, but said they would still press for
action against Chun.
   Among those released Wednesday were Kim Hyun-jang and Moon
Boo-shik. Each was serving a 20-year term for leading a raid on the
U.S. cultural center in Pusan. One person died and three were hurt
when the center was set afire in the protest over U.S. support for
the Chun government.
   Kim Tae-kun, a leading dissident who won the Robert Kennedy Human
Rights Award this year, had his civil rights restored. Kim, who was
released last June, drew five years in 1986 on charges of
overthrowing the government and spreading pro-North Korean
propaganda.
   Kim claims he was forced to make a false confession under torture.
   Justice Ministry officials said the amnesty was the second since
Roh succeeded Chun last Feb. 25 and involved the largest number of
political offenders in a single amnesty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
