<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 2349EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-VisaFraud     12-20 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Visa Fraud,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former U.S. Diplomat Sentenced In Iranian Visa Fraud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL PUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior diplomat who served as anti-fraud officer
at the U.S. Embassy in Spain was sentenced Tuesday to five years in
federal prison after pleading guilty in a scheme to illegally sell
visas to Iranian nationals.
   Bernard J. Fennell, former first secretary and consul in Madrid,
was sentenced by U.S. District Judge Lenore C. Nesbitt on conspiracy
and fraud charges.
   Fennell, other American citizens and Iranian nationals were
accused of conspiring to unlawfully sell visas to Iranians wanting
to emigrate to the United States. Many of the Iranians had already
been rejected for visas, or were otherwise ineligible to obtain them.
   As much as $5,000 was paid for a single visa, and $15,000 bought
visas for a family of five, according to the indictment.
   Fennell's alleged co-conspirators, visa broker Harry Arjad and
his associate Mary Rosales, traveled to West Germany, Turkey and
Israel collecting passports and money from Iranian nationals, said
Dexter Lehtinen, U.S. Attorney for the Southern District of Florida.
   Those passports were then taken to Fennell at the embassy, who
would issue non-immigrant visas to the Iranians without the required
documentation and personal interviews, Lehtinen said.
   Fennell, who was the embassy's anti-fraud officer and supervised
visa operations, also falsified information on the visa applications
and on confidential outgoing cables to other U.S. embassies to
justify the illegal visas, Lehtinen said.
   The indictment listed 12 sales that took place in Frankfurt, Tel
Aviv and Istanbul between July and December 1986.
   Some of the Iranian aliens who tried to enter the United Sates
have pleaded guilty in the case. Fennell has since resigned from the
State Department.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
