<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 0109EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChildAbuse 1stLd-Writethru a0585 12-20 0871</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Abuse, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0585,0887</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Public Aware _ But Five Kids Still Die Daily</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 7th graf, `One day...', to UPDATE with
published report that city agency had failed to tell judge about
woman's history of child neglect. Picks up 8th graf, `Ninety-five
percent...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The public has glimpsed the nightmarish world of
domestic violence through Hedda Nussbaum's testimony in the Lisa
Steinberg case. But experts say more than increased awareness is
needed to save the lives of children like 6-year-old Lisa and, now,
5-year-old Jessica Cortez.
   ``We were seeing five deaths a day (nationally) before Lisa died,
and five deaths per day since then,'' said Dr. Richard Krugman of
the Kempe National Center for the Prevention of Child Abuse and
Neglect in Denver.
   ``I can't blame the public. I don't think the public knows what
to do,'' said Krugman.
   Lisa Steinberg made headlines when she died in November 1987 _ a
symbol of a system gone wrong. She made front-page news again last
week, at the trial of Joel Steinberg _ the man she knew as Daddy,
the man accused of murdering her.
   But last Wednesday _ when the brutal beating death in Brooklyn of
5-year-old Jessica Cortez grabbed the headlines away _ it was the
same old story; only the name had changed.
   Jessica Cortez's mother, Abigail, and the mother's boyfriend,
Adrian Lopez, were unemployed. They lived in a city-owned housing
project in Brooklyn. On the surface, they had nothing in common with
the Steinberg family _ except that children in their home also were
battered.
   One day after police found Lopez standing over Jessica's limp
body, they returned to the apartment and found Jessica's 9-year-old
half-brother, Nicky Lebron Alvarez, quivering in a closet, badly
beaten with 10 bones broken.
   Family Court authorities charged Monday that welfare officials
knew that Ms. Cortez had a history of child neglect but failed to
tell a judge about it, according to a published report. The New York
Times said in Tuesday's editions that during a 1986 custody hearing,
welfare officials called the woman a good mother even though the
city's Special Services for Children department had filed a neglect
petition against her three years earlier.
   ``Ninety-five percent of the American public knows child abuse
exists _ that's not the issue anymore,'' said Krugman. ``My
impression is people make some cosmetic changes (after rekindled
awareness of child abuse); it's like firing a football coach when
you've got bigger problem than just the coach.''
   ``Now, we need a new kind of public awareness _ that physical
abuse of children, the Lisa Steinberg type cases, are preventable if
people want to do something.''
   The National Committee for the Prevention of Child Abuse
estimated there were 1,132 child-abuse fatalities in the United
States last year; Krugman puts the figure at 2,000 to 5,000.
   There were 2.25 million official reports of abused children
nationally in 1987, including 25 percent who were physically abused
and 14 percent who were sexually abused, the committee's report
said. Jessica Cortez fit into both those categories, police said.
   She also fit into a third category: at least 103 children died of
abuse last year in New York City.
   Authorities say those numbers aren't likely to decline despite
widespread publicity about child abuse and the Steinberg case _ live
national television coverage on Cable News Network, a cover story in
Newsweek, hours of local TV coverage of Ms. Nussbaum's testimony.
   But it will have some positive effect, they believe.
   ``The Steinberg case puts the spotlight on the topic,'' said
Detective Joseph Ryan, coordinator of domestic violence programs for
the New York City police. ``This case is very important because it
is that much more detailed, and serves to show the dynamics of
violence in a family situation.''
   Agreed Carol Digirolamo, executive director of the Governor's
Commission on Domestic Violence: ``There clearly is some increase in
awareness.''
   The deaths of Steinberg and Jessica also illustrated one of the
more frightening aspects of child abuse: it crosses all lines of
race, economics and geography. And domestic violence is rarely
limited to just one family member, experts in the field say.
   Steinberg was a lawyer. Ms. Nussbaum, his live-in lover, was a
children's book editor. They lived a comfortable existence in a
historic building in Manhattan's upscale Greenwich Village. And,
authorities said, their two illegally adopted children were
ill-treated.
   When Lisa was found in a coma Nov. 2, 1987, the other child,
Mitchell, was sitting in a dirty diaper, tethered to a chair and
drinking spoiled milk. Ms. Nussbaum also had been badly battered.
   In both the Steinberg and Cortez cases, drugs were apparently
involved _ another disturbing trend which has contributed to the
rising number of child abuse cases.
   Ms. Nussbaum has detailed how she and Steinberg freebased cocaine
while Lisa lay unconscious in another room. Neighbors of Lopez and
Ms. Cortez said they were also drug users, smoking marijuana and
crack.
   From July 1, 1987, to June 30, 1988, the city Human Resources
Administration estimated 14 percent of its 55,286 reported abuse
cases were tied to drugs _ a 67 percent jump from the previous 12
months.
</TEXT>
