<1ST_LINE>r w Ex-CongressmanReadiesRunForTopDemocraticPartyJob     12-20
0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Ex-Congressman Readies Run For Top Democratic Party Job</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: News conference scheduled for noon EST; may be topped</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Rep. James Stanton of Ohio is entering
the race for chairman of the national Democratic Party with support
from Ohio's two U.S. senators but without the backing of his state's
top two Democratic Party officials.
   Stanton scheduled a news conference today to make his bid
official.
   He has won the support of Sens. John Glenn and Howard Metzenbaum,
but Ohio Democratic Chairman James Ruvulo and Vice Chair Thea Boyd
on Monday lined up behind another candidate, Michigan Democratic
Chairman Richard Wiener.
   Wiener was among the first to announce his candidacy for the job
being vacated by Paul Kirk.
   Wiener on Monday announced the support of 13 other state party
leaders from the Midwest. They include the state party chairs from
North Dakota, Minnesota, Kansas, South Dakota, Illinois, Wisconsin,
Nebraska and Indiana as well as vice chairs from several states.
   Stanton said he's confident Democratic National Committee members
who examine his background will be convinced he's right for the job.
   ``I've built a ward organization; I've run a city council; I've
run an $800 million business,'' Stanton said Monday. ``I have the
communications skills to talk to the people who are going to
financially energize any political party in this country.''
   ``I believe I have a very viable chance to win,'' Stanton said.
   Stanton's decision followed a lengthy testing-the-waters period.
   ``I've been very much encouraged by people I respect deeply,
people like (former DNC Chairman) Bob Strauss and others,'' Stanton
said, adding that he's also lined up the backing of several members
of Congress from Ohio as well as the Rev. Jesse Jackson's 1984
campaign manager, Gerald Austin, and Jackson's 1988 campaign
manager, Arnold Pinkney.
   That's significant because one of the contenders for the post is
Ronald H. Brown, a longtime party activist most recently associated
with Jackson.
   Stanton is a former congressman and Cleveland City Council
president who dropped out of public life after a 1976 Democratic
Primary loss to Metzenbaum.
   Metzenbaum, Glenn, Ohio Reps. Mary Rose Oakar and Louis Stoes and
former House Speaker Tip O'Neill of Massachusetts last week signed a
mailgram urging union leaders to back Stanton.
   The party's new leader is to be chosen at a meeting in Washington
Feb. 9 and 10.
</TEXT>
