<1ST_LINE>r a BC-People-Sills     12-20 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-People-Sills,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beverly Sills Given Farewell Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York City Opera gave departing general
director Beverly Sills a farewell party Monday night, and the grand
ballroom of the Plaza Hotel resounded with celebrity toasts.
   ``She is so warm, effervescent and fun, you immediately forget
her incredible voice. When you do, she gets really annoyed,'' teased
actress Mary Tyler Moore.
   Miss Moore concluded, ``You have garnered as much love as you
have praise for your work as an artist and business woman, and I
toast you.''
   Sills noted that she has had a ``meaningful relationship'' with
the opera company for 33 years and two months. She was its
coloratura superstar and for the past 10 years its general director.
Following her resignation the opera announced she would be succeeded
in March by Christopher Keene.
   ``I have reached the age of 59, and 50 years of my life have been
spent in opera,'' she said. ``Interesting things are being offered
to me. I feel a third career is somewhere out there right around the
corner.''
   Mike Wallace of the CBS News program ``60 Minutes'' suggested in
his toast that Sills become mayor of New York, or as he put it,
``her honor, the prima donna.''
   New York Mayor Edward I. Koch, who spoke at a reception before
the dinner, suggested that Sills become a TV interviewer.
   The master of ceremonies, TV interviewer Barbara Walters, sang
original lyrics spelling ``Beverly,'' beginning with ``B is for the
beauty of your soul, dear.'' Then she invited the audience to sing a
second time through.
   Songwriters Betty Comden and Adolph Green sang, very fast, words
they'd written to the finale of Tchaikovsky's ``Fourth Symphony,''
ending with Miss Sills' nickname, ``Bubbles, Bubbles, Bubbles.''
   Actress Helen Hayes praised Miss Sills' acting in opera and said,
``Let me make you our national city treasure.''
   Actress Barbara Feldon said about the honoree, ``There is this
possibility for human radiance that can transcend all kinds of
troubles and make life really worthwhile.''
   Actor Len Cariou called Miss Sills ``an artist of life.''
</TEXT>
