<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Court Says Federal Union Presidents Legally Supported Mondale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court has reversed the last of the
disciplinary suspensions against the presidents of federal employee
unions for actively supporting Democrat Walter Mondale in the 1984
presidential campaign.
   The ruling by the Second Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals in New
York vacates charges brought in 1985 by the Merit Systems Protection
Board against Vincent R. Sombrotto, president of the National
Association of Letter Carriers, and Moe Biller, president of the
American Postal Workers Union.
   After a series of hearings, the board in 1987 ordered Sombrotto,
Biller and Kenneth Blaylock, former president of the American
Federation of Government Employees, suspended from their government
jobs for 60 days under the 1939 Hatch Act.
   The 1939 law forbids government workers from taking ``an active
part in political management or political campaigns.''
</TEXT>
