<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 0221EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PrisonPackages     12-20 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison Packages,0703</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmates Do Their Holiday Shopping By Mail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY TRUDY TYNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mail-order catalog firm that has
begun catering to the captive audience of prisoners reports
Christmas sales are on the rise.
   ``They are very good customers and it's developed into a
substantial segment of our business. Where else are they going to
go?'' said Mortimer Polep, chairman of the Holyoke-based Paysaver
Catalog Showrooms Inc.
   ``We even got a thank-you letter from one inmate who said, `After
all, our money is as good as the guy that hasn't been caught yet,'''
he said.
   Paul Hahn of the 2,000-member National Mail Order Association,
based in Los Angeles, said it's impossible to tell how many inmates
order from catalogs, but sales seem to be up everywhere.
   ``We don't keep any special statistics on sales to prison
inmates, but my sense is that they have been increasing as prisons
have eased the regulations on what kinds of packages prisoners can
receive,'' he said.
   Polep said his company's Christmas sales to prisoners are up 25
percent this year, but he won't divulge exactly how big his business
is behind bars.
   At the 1,100-inmate state prison at Norfolk, Sgt. Christopher
Cameron said he inspects about 30 packages a day that inmates have
ordered from catalogs. ``We don't allow them anything like hacksaws
or shotguns,'' he said.
   For the three weeks before Christmas, however, the prison
suspends its rules against mailed food and allows inmates to receive
packages up to 25 pounds holding mail-order and homemade delicacies.
   To inspect the food packages, the prison must hold up inspections
of other packages, which wait until after Christmas to reach inmates.
   ``The food is more important and meaningful to them anyway,''
Cameron said. ``They can get clothes all year.''
   The largest purveyors to the Norfolk prisoners are Cook Brothers,
an Illinois-based catalog firm specializing in low-cost items,
followed by Service Merchandise of Nashville, Tenn., and
merchandising giants J.C. Penney Co. and Sears, Roebuck and Co.,
Cameron said.
   Clothing is the big sales item at the medium-security prison,
followed by towels, television sets, radios and fans, he said.
   ``We've put together a little booklet on what they can order, but
essentially it's any basic necessity,'' Cameron said. ``They know by
word of mouth that if there were any problems with anyone trying to
bring in weapons or drugs, we would cut back on the orders and we
can trace it right back to who is responsible.''
   Payments are made by the prison against inmate accounts, he said.
They build up accounts by working in prison, or by getting money
from their families.
   Regulations on what prisoners can order vary widely from state to
state and prison to prison, according to state and federal
officials, with federal prisoners allowed only limited
catalog-ordering privileges.
   ``They have to have special prior permission, but half the time
the issue is not so much the regulations but the fact that our
inmates just don't have the money,'' said Kathryn Johnson, a
spokeswoman for the federal bureau of prisons.
   Sears treats its prison customers ``just like any others,'' said
spokeswoman Kathy Gucfa, except that it delivers packages directly
to the prisons rather than to its retail stores. ``Obviously they
can't get out to pick up their packages,'' she said.
   But Paysaver has employees assigned just to its prison business,
and Christmas is a particularly busy time.
   The woman in charge of the company's prison sales, who asked that
her name not be used, said some of her dealings with inmates ``have
helped restore my faith in human nature.
   ``Sometimes they don't figure the shipping charges right and if
it's just a couple of dollars, I send it out and just tuck a note
inside as to what is owed and almost always I get a check back,''
she said.
   ``I got a letter from a man at Attica (in New York) who said he
was sending Christmas presents to his kids in Florida and asked if I
could put a note inside the package saying, `With love, from
Daddy.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881220-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 0236EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Shell-Arsenal     12-20 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shell-Arsenal,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Decides Against Shell In $2 Billion Arsenal Cleanup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN BRUNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Insurance companies claimed a major
victory after a jury decided Shell Oil Co. would have to spend up to
$2 billion to clean up three decades of pesticide pollution at the
Rocky Mountain Arsenal in Colorado.
   ``The verdict was a clean, straight win for the insurers,'' said
Barry Bunshoft, an attorney for Lloyd's of London, the British
insurance market that had faced the biggest share of possible
liability. ``To say that this is an exciting win and a gratifying
win is an understatement.''
   The 250 insurance companies involved convinced a jury they should
not be held responsible for the contamination because Shell knew of
the pollution for 30 years. They claimed Shell was not covered by
its 800 different policies any more than a homeowner who set fire to
his own home.
   ``Naturally, we're extremely disappointed with the outcome of
this lengthy trial,'' said Betty Lynn McHam, a Shell spokeswoman in
Houston. ``We believe there are sound legal grounds for appealing to
a higher court and we will appeal.''
   In 1983, the Justice Department ordered the oil company to pay
the cleanup bill, then estimated at $1.8 billion. Shell subsequently
began trying to collect the money from its insurers.
   Dozens of insurance company attorneys whooped for joy Monday when
the verdict was read in San Mateo County Superior Court. The lengthy
trial was held in a makeshift courtroom at Crestmoor High School to
make room for all the lawyers.
   Eleven jurors voted for the insurance companies for the period
from 1952-59, with one juror against. For the period 1960-82, the
vote was 11 for the insurers and one undecided. A jury in a civil
suit does not have to reach a unanimous verdict.
   The jurors declined to comment on their decision.
   During those years, Shell leased the U.S. Army land at the
arsenal north of Denver's Stapleton International Airport for a
pesticide production plant. The soil and groundwater at the plant
was polluted by Shell and Army operations, and the pollution seeped
into nearby drinking water wells.
   Shell attorneys also argued before Judge William Lanam that the
liability should be mainly with the Army because it provided the
leaking pipes and ponds used by the oil company.
   ``Regardless of the outcome of this litigation, the citizens of
Colorado can be confident that Shell has and will continue to meet
its share of responsibilities at the Rocky Mountain arsenal. We are
hopeful that the remaining issues between the state of Colorado, the
U.S. Army and Shell can be resolved, thereby allowing the arsenal
cleanup to proceed expeditiously,'' Ms. McHam said.
   The trial, which began in October 1987, was held in San Mateo
County because of the county's record of completing cases promptly.
It included more than 4,000 exhibits and hundreds of hours of
testimony.
   Ms. McHam said she could not estimate the cost of the cleanup.
Insurance industry sources put it at $2 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
