<1ST_LINE>r i PM-DonaPaz     12-20 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dona Paz,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Relatives of Victims Curse Government On Anniversary Of Ferry
Disaster</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of people wailed and called
down a curse on the government and a shipping line today in
emotional ceremonies marking the first anniversary of history's
worst peacetime disaster at sea.
   The 300 protesters were marking the Dec. 20, 1987, sinking of the
ferry Dona Paz and the oil tanker Vector, which collided and
exploded off Mindoro island, leaving more than 3,000 people dead.
   ``In the name of all our loved ones, wherever they are, we swear
that all those responsible shall be made to pay for the deaths and
injustices they caused,'' the crowd chanted in unison. ``We will not
lose hope until all those responsible are punished.''
   A presidential commission said at least 3,563 people were aboard
the two ships, but only 26 survived. Survivors and relatives claim
the government and the Dona Paz's owners, Sulpicio Shipping Lines,
have not provided adequate compensation nor taken steps to prevent
other maritime disasters.
   The protesters, including at least four survivors and relatives
of Dona Paz victims, assembled at a Manila's church for a Mass, then
marched toward President Corazon Aquino's office at Malacanang
Palace.
   About 20 police officers and vehicles blocked the marchers at a
bridge about 600 feet from the palace but permitted the marchers to
hold a rally.
   After speeches, the protesters lit candles and set fire to
papier-mache models of the two ships. Two men slit the throats of
two chickens and spattered the models with the blood.
   As the flames triggered firecrackers inside the models, hundreds
wailed and began reciting the curse, traditional among people of the
central Visayas islands from where most of the victims came.
   During the rally, survivor Arnel Galang told the crowd that the
Sulpicio Lines had offered him money to testify that the oil tanker
was at fault but he refused.
   ``They think they can buy lives with their money,'' he said. He
said the survivors were being victimized by owners ``and this
uncaring government.''
   Speaker Ildefonso Aresala, who said he lost his entire family in
the disaster, said his claims for compensation had been bogged down
by paperwork.
   ``I thought the president would be able to help, but I was
mistaken,'' he said. ``There's no clear solution. This is very
painful for us. I don't know what kind of law we have.''
   Other relatives of victims claimed the government was simply
pressuring them into accepting inadequate compensation offered by
the ship owners.
   ``For as long as the government adopts a system that favors the
interests of greedy capitalists, corruption will continue endlessly
and sea travelers will never be safe,'' said one leaflet distributed
in the crowd.
   Nazzer Cajolo, who claimed he lost five brothers in the disaster,
said Sulpicio offered a $7,500 settlement but his family rejected it.
   ``Now they say my brothers are alive,'' he added. ``We want this
government to listen to us and not avoid us.''
   Cajolo is one of about 300 people who have filed a class suit
against Sulpicio Lines, the largest Philippine domestic shipping
company. The suit was rejected by a lower court but an appeal is
pending.
   In October, another Sulpicio passenger ship, the Dona Marilyn,
sank during Typhoon Ruby with about 500 people aboard. About half
those aboard died or are missing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
