<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     12-20 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Up In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained against the Japanese yen today,
while share prices rebounded moderately on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 124.70 yen, up 0.68 yen from Monday's close
of 124.02 yen. After opening at 124.45 yen, the currency moved in a
range of 124.30 to 124.80 yen.
   The U.S. currency's higher opening in Tokyo followed its rise on
the Sydney market, which opened earlier, dealers said.
   Daiwa Bank's Mitsuhiko Kinugasa said the dollar-yen rate hardly
moved in the morning session, but increased dollar-buying by
speculative investors and trading companies in the afternoon pushed
the dollar up.
   ``There was no economic factor in Tokyo that raised the dollar
today, but its firmness on overseas markets encouraged investors'
buying,'' Kinugasa added.
   On the stock market, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, a
66.63-point loser Monday, climbed 97.86 points, or 0.3 percent,
closing at 29,567.94.
   Dealers attributed the index's quick rise in the morning to an
overnight gain in the Dow Jones industrial average in New York. The
Nikkei gained 151 points in the morning session, but eased somewhat
in the afternoon as buying interest fell, dealers said.
   Most institutional investors were sitting on the sidelines in the
afternoon due to uncertainties over the U.S. discount rate, said a
dealer at one major securities firm, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Trading was thin with volume on the first section estimated at
650 million shares.
</TEXT>
