<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OfficerDies     12-20 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Officer Dies,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top Officer Collapses, Dies While Jogging</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police officer who survived a gunshot
blast to the chest in 1986 and saved a man from an ax-wielding
assailant in 1985 collapsed and died while jogging.
   Ramiro Olvera Jr., 27, who received 19 commendations in less than
five years in uniform, collapsed as he jogged Monday morning.
   ``It's a terrible loss to the city and everyone who knew him,''
said Police Chief Jim Everett. ``We have lost a very fine young
officer who will be difficult to replace.''
   Dr. Robert Bayardo, Travis County medical examiner, said an
aneurysm in the right side of the officer's brain burst. An aneurysm
is a balloon-type swelling of a blood vessel, Bayardo said.
   In December 1985, Olvera and another officer were forced to shoot
a man who was attacking another man with an ax at a housing project.
The attacker died and the officers were credited with saving the
life of the intended victim.
   Only two months later, Olvera stopped a burglary suspect who had
been fleeing from officers by ramming his patrol car into the
suspect's car.
   In 1986, a man whom Olvera was frisking pulled out a gun and
fired at Olvera's chest. The bullet was deflected by a bulletproof
vest.
   Olvera's work earned him the title of 1986 Officer of the Year
from a local club and 1986 Central Texas Law Officer of the Year
from a law enforcement group.
   Olvera in 1987 joined the Hispanic Crimes Unit, a team of
investigators who gained a reputation for solving tough crimes.
</TEXT>
