<2ND_LINE>PM-Ministers' Trial,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Selection Begins In Trial Of Five Ministers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection is underway in the trial of
five of the 13 civil rights leaders arrested for trying to block a
City Council meeting in June.
   More than 20 jurors were interviewed Monday as city prosecutors
and defense lawyers tried to seat an eight-member panel in Municipal
Court.
   The five ministers on trial are each charged with one count of
obstructing official business. The charge is a second-degree
misdemeanor, with a maximum sentence of three months in jail and a
$750 fine.
   The five defendants are among 13 ministers and civil rights
leaders who were arrested after they refused to leave City Council
chambers during the protest of the city's handling of problems in
its Community Development Department. One black Community
Development Department official was fired, another resigned, one
retired and one was reassigned because of alleged mismanagment of
the city's housing programs.
   The civil rights leaders wanted to know why the men were
reprimanded without being consulted about problems in the
department. They also asked for a public hearing into the
allegations.
   Their requests were rejected by city officials and that sparked
months of protest by civil rights leaders, who claim there is a
conspiracy against black officials in Toledo.
   The other eight defendants are scheduled for trial next month.
</TEXT>
