<1ST_LINE>r i PM-EmptyJet     12-20 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Empty Jet,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jumpbo Jet Flies Empty After Six-Hour Delay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air-India Boeing 747 flew to London
without a single passenger after a six-hour delay prompted ticket
holders to switch to another flight, an airline spokesman said today.
   ``We have no control on the passengers. When the plane was
delayed, they opted for another flight,'' said K.S. Mahatre, chief
public relations officer of the state-run airline.
   There was no reason given for the delay. The 60 to 70 passengers
booked on Monday's flight from Bombay switched to another Air-India
plane that stopped in London and continued on to New York, Mahatre
said.
   ``We had no option but to fly the aircraft empty because we are a
scheduled airline and can't just cancel because there is no
passenger,'' Mahatre said when contacted by telephone at the
airline's headquarters in Bombay.
   The jumbo jet, capable of carrying 264 passengers, carried a
14-member crew and 34 tons of cargo. It cost the airline $54,000 to
make the one-way flight to London, Mahatre said. He didn't know how
much of that was offset by the cargo.
   ``The plane's return flight is fully booked, so we do not look
that bad,'' he said.
</TEXT>
