<HEAD>Mormon Church's Temple Square Gets 4-Millionth Visitor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four million people have visited the Mormon
Church's historic Temple Square this year, the most visitors the
center has recorded in a single year, an official said.
   Teresa Hughes of Kingsport, Tenn., was singled out as the
4-millionth visitor Monday as she and her husband, Stephen, strolled
through the gates of the 10-acre, walled-in city block, said Temple
Square director Joseph F. Horne.
   The couple was treated to a special tour of the grounds and
accepted gifts from local merchants, state and county officials and
the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.
   Home of the Mormon Temple, Mormon Tabernacle and visitors
centers, the downtown square is the state's most popular tourist
attraction.
   ``We've never reached the 4-million mark in any previous year,''
Horne said. ``In fact, last year was the previous record year for
visitors, and the 3-million milestone was reached on Dec. 3, so
we're way ahead of any previous year.''
