<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea     12-20 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Announces Amnesty For Political Offenders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today announced an
amnesty for more than 2,000 ``politically motivated offenders,''
including two who were serving 20-year sentences for burning a U.S.
government building.
   The Justice Ministry said the clemency was approved at a special
Cabinet session.
   Ministry officials said 281 prisoners would be released
Wednesday, including Kim Hyun-jang and Moon Boo-shik, who were
serving 20-year sentences for leading a raid on the U.S. Cultural
Center in the southern city of Pusan in early 1982.
   Protesters set fire to the building to protest U.S. support for
the government of then-President Chun Doo-hwan. One person was
killed and three were wounded.
   Another 1,581 people already freed on parole will have their
civil rights restored Wednesday, 92 prisoners will have their
sentences reduced, and 61 people who were sought by police will be
taken off the wanted list, authorities said..
   Among those who will be granted restoration of civil rights is
prominent dissident Kim Kun-tae, who was freed from prison in June,
He received the Robert F. Kennedy Award for Human Rights in April.
   Kim was sentenced to five years in prison in 1986 for inciting
unrest, but supporters alleged he was forced to confess by police
torture.
   Prime Minister Kang Young-hoon said in a statement that the
leniency was a ``bold step intended to heal the depressing wounds of
the past era and thus to promote democratization.''
   He said the action was taken through consultations with all major
political parties, as had been promised by President Roh Tae-woo.
Roh pledged on Nov. 26 to release many political prisoners and
institute other reforms to dissociate himself from Chun, his
predecessor.
   The main opposition Party for Peace and Democracy said the
government amnesty was an important step toward democratization, but
party officials said there were still 60 more political prisoners to
be freed.
   The Reunification Democratic Party, another opposition group,
welcomed the measure, but dissident groups charged that Roh betrayed
his promise for a total release of political prisoners by excluding
about 300 political prisoners, mostly involved in movements for
workers and depressed people.
   Government officials disagreed and claimed the figure was about
200 who were involved mostly in communist spy cases and other
anti-state activities.
</TEXT>
