<DOCNO> AP881220-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 0525EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     12-20 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Howl Over Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow, freezing rain or rain fell over much of the West and
Midwest today after thunderstorms packing damaging gusts up to 67
mph boomed over Kansas, Missouri, Iowa and Wyoming.
   Gusts were clocked at almost 65 mph in Kansas City, Mo., and
Stanley, Kan., Monday night, and minor damage was reported in
Richards, Mo., and near Centerville, Iowa.
   High wind warnings were posted for much of Missouri today, and
warnings of gale-force winds were issued for Lake Huron and the
lower Great Lakes.
   Winds were also strong in Wyoming. Gusts of 67 mph were recorded
Monday evening in Vedauwoo.
   Scattered freezing rain fell in Upper Michigan and northeast
Minnesota today, and snow fell from western North Dakota to Wyoming,
Montana, Idaho, Utah and the mountains of Washington state.
   Rain dampened California's central coast, and rain and occasional
thunderstorms fell over Nebraska, eastern Kansas, western Missouri,
Iowa, southern Minnesota and central Wisconsin.
   Advisories for snow and blowing snow were posted for the central
Colorado mountains, and an avalanche warning was up in the Monarch
Pass area.
   Snow advisories were also up in northern Utah, Idaho's west
central mountains and Washington state's south central region and
Cascade Mountains.
   Winter storm watches were in effect in Oregon's Cascade and
Siskiyou mountains, as well as the northern and northeast California
mountains and higher elevations of the Lake Tahoe area.
   In the Midwest, advisories for snow, rain and snow, freezing rain
or a combination of the three were up in sections of Minnesota,
Wisconsin and Michigan.
   High-temperature records for Dec. 19 were snapped or tied Monday
in five Midwestern cities, including Peoria, Ill., where the reading
of 61 degrees surpassed the 1957 mark by 5 degrees, and Cedar
Rapids, Iowa, where the 70-year-old record of 53 degrees was
exceeded by 2 degrees.
   Today's forecast called for snow from eastern sections of South
Dakota and Nebraska to the upper Mississippi Valley and northern
Michigan, and over northern Maine, much of Idaho and eastern
portions of Washington and Oregon; scattered snow showers over Utah
and western Colorado; rain showers from eastern Iowa to southern
Wisconsin, northern Illinois and northern Indiana; scattered rain
showers from eastern Texas to Arkansas, the Ohio Valley, northern
New York state and northern New England; and rain along the northern
and central Pacific Coast.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 20s and 30s in the
northern and central Rockies, the northern half of the Great Plains,
the upper Mississippi Valley to northern Michigan and in northern
Maine; the 60s and 70s from southern Virginia and the south Atlantic
Coast states to Tennessee, lower Ohio and lower Mississippi valleys
and much of Texas; the 60s in southwest Arizona and Southern
California; and in the 40s and 50s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 8
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 72 degrees at
Brownsville, Texas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 39 fair; Boston 28 fair; Buffalo 49 windy;
Charleston, S.C. 34 fair; Cincinnati 50 windy; Cleveland 50 windy;
Detroit 48 windy; Miami 68 fair; New York 40 fair; Philadelphia 32
fair; Pittsburgh 52 cloudy; Portland, Maine 22 fair; Washington 42
partly cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 26 snow; Chicago 51 rain; Dallas-Fort Worth 64
windy; Denver 29 fair; Des Moines 46 fair; Indianapolis 53 windy;
Kansas City 53 windy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 34 rain; Nashville 51
partly cloudy; New Orleans 61 partly cloudy; St. Louis 54 windy.
   _West: Albuquerque 31 partly cloudy; Anchorage 31 cloudy; Las
Vegas 35 fair; Phoenix 46 fair; Salt Lake City 32 foggy; San Diego
54 cloudy; San Francisco 48 cloudy; Seattle 40 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 27 cloudy; Toronto 43 showers.
</TEXT>
