<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WrongDuckling     12-20 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wrong Duckling,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Purloined Duckling Mystery Deepens: Two Quacks Now But No Mack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There are two Quacks now but no Mack.
   The mystery of the purloined duckling deepened on Monday when a
bronze duck stolen from a children's sculpture in the Boston Public
Garden more than a year ago was left at the Statehouse for police to
find.
   But it was the wrong duck.
   To restore the sculpture, thieves must return a different
duckling that was swiped on Dec. 10th.
   ``We're delighted to have Quack back but Mack is still missing,''
said the sculptor, Nancy Schon of suburban Newton.
   She pleaded with the culprit to return Mack the duck before
Christmas.
   Mack and Quack are two of eight bronze ducklings shown waddling
after their mother in a sculpture dramatizing Robert McCloskey's
well-known children's story, ``Make Way for Ducklings.'' In the
story, a family of ducks wanders around the Beacon Hill neighborhood
before a friendly policeman helps them find a home in the Public
Garden.
   Quack, the eighth duckling in the line, was stolen from the
Garden while the cement was still setting on the sculpture in
September 1987, Schon said.
   She replaced it and the ducklings remained untouched for more
than a year. But this Dec. 10, while walking in the Garden, Schon
noticed that Mack, the fourth duck in the line, had disappeared.
   It had been cut off at the feet, apparenty with a blow torch,
leaving only a telltale trace of bronze on the cobblestone.
   The ducklings each weigh about 30 pounds and are worth about
$3,000.
   On Monday morning, Schon got a call from a friend saying the
duckling had been found. A caller led police to the duck, which was
in a cardboard box.
   ``I was joyous,'' she said. ``But when I went down to the police
station I discovered it was not Mack but Quack.''
</TEXT>
