<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     12-20 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in thin early European trading
today. Gold prices fell slightly.
   Foreign currency dealers said the continuing possibility of an
increase in the U.S. discount rate was providing support for the
dollar.
   ``No one wants to be caught without dollars if the Fed (U.S.
Federal Reserve) moves,'' said one dealer with a major Italian
commercial bank in Milan.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.68 yen to a closing 124.70. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 125.05 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday:
   _1.7745 West German marks, up from 1.7625
   _1.5000 Swiss francs, up from 1.4870
   _6.0635 French francs, up from 6.0235
   _1.9985 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9895
   _1,302.50 Italian lire, up from 1,296.00
   _1.2005 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1995
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8110, cheaper for buyers
than late Monday's $1.8230.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $413.90 a troy ounce,
down from $414.25 bid late Monday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $413.20.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $412.20, down from $412.25 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 5 cents to close at a bid
$415.67.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.10 a troy ounce,
up from Monday's $6.08.
</TEXT>
