<DOCNO> AP881220-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 0718EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Palme     12-20 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Palme,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Palme's Widow Identified Suspect From Videotape</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of Prime Minister Olof Palme,
the only witness to her husband's assassination, identified the
killer from a videotape last week, a newspaper reported today.
   The account by Lisbet Palme was the main evidence that persuaded
a Stockholm district court to order that Christer Pettersson, 41, be
held in custody Friday, said the report by the Aftonbladet newspaper.
   Prosecutors, police and Pettersson's defense attorney refused
comment on the report. Prosecutor Jorgen Almblad complained that
publicity about the case could put Mrs. Palme's life in danger.
   Swedish television also reported Monday that Mrs. Palme had
identified the gunman, but it gave no details.
   Palme, who was prime minister for 11 years, was gunned down on a
downtown Stockholm street while walking home from a movie with his
wife the night of Feb. 28, 1986. Mrs. Palme was grazed by a second
bullet.
   Aftonbladet said two other witnesses identified Pettersson as the
man seen loitering outside the Grand Theater before the killing.
   Pettersson pleaded innocent at his arraignment, but the court
found the prosecution had shown ``reasonable grounds for suspicion''
he committed the murder.
   Defense attorney Arne Liljeros has indicated he will argue
against the reliability of eyewitness accounts after a nearly
three-year time lapse. Failure to find the murder weapon, a .357
magnum revolver, also could complicate the prosecution, news reports
said.
   Pettersson, who has a long record of violent crimes and a history
of drug and alcohol abuse, was picked up Wednesday after nearly a
three-year manhunt.
   Aftonbladet said Mrs. Palme was reluctant to go through with the
identification and relive the shooting but was persuaded ``by people
outside the investigation'' to see a videotape.
   Mrs. Palme has persistently refused to publicly discuss the hunt
for her husband's killer.
</TEXT>
