<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 0803EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Fire     12-20 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Fire,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Seek Possible Links Between Department Store Fires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLYMOUTH, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire destroyed a large downtown
department store, and officials said today they were investigating
possible links with arson attacks at four other department stores.
   No injuries were reported in any of the incidents, which occurred
late Monday and early today in London, the Welsh city of Cardiff and
the southwestern town of Plymouth, about 200 miles from London.
   No group claimed responsibility in any of the incidents, but the
domestic news agency Press Association noted that animal rights
activists opposed to the sale of furs have planted incendiary
devices in the past at some of the targeted stores.
   The fire at Dingles department store in the center of Plymouth
gutted the 150-foot-high building. A total of 140 firemen battled
for six hours to put out the flames.
   The blaze broke out late Monday after the 450 employees had gone
home, fire officials said. Walls of the building collapsed, piling
tons of rubble on fire engines at the scene.
   ``We have no indication as to how it started yet. It is one of
the worst fires I have ever seen in the city center,'' said the
police department's chief investigator, Roger Mechan.
   Scotland Yard said incendiary devices started small fires at
Harrods department store in London's Knightsbridge district and at
Selfridges, another large London department store, shortly after
midnight.
   In each case, the device had been hidden down the side of a sofa
in the furniture department, investigators said. They said damage
was limited to the sofas.
   Similar incidents occurred at both stores in April.
   Scotland Yard bomb squad officers also defused an incendiary
device found at the House of Fraser store on Oxford Street before it
went off.
   In Cardiff in Wales late Monday, a fire broke out in the menswear
department at the Howells department store, police said. The fire
was quickly put out, according to a police statement.
   ``There is no indication as to the cause, but obviously it is
being treated as suspicious,'' the statement said.
   It said South Wales police would be talking with police in London
and Plymouth to see if there was a link between the fires and
discovery of incendiary devices.
</TEXT>
