<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HappyBirthday     12-20 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Happy Birthday,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company That Owns Song `Happy Birthday To You' Sold For $25 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The company that owns the song ``Happy Birthday
to You'' is being sold for $25 million to the largest music
publisher in the world, according to a report published today.
   Birchtree Ltd., which owns the birthday song, will soon be
acquired by Warner Chappell, which owns the rights to songs by
George and Ira Gershwin, Michael Jackson, Cole Porter, and Gilbert
and Sullivan, according to The New York Times.
   Warner Chappell is a division of Warner Communications Inc.
   Birchtree, of Princeton, N.J., was put up for sale in October, in
part because the company said it did not have the resources to
monitor and protect its copyrights as larger companies do, the Times
said.
   Technically, a royalty should be paid every time the birthday
song is sung in public, but the company has never monitored that
kind of use.
   ``Happy Birthday'' generates about $1 million a year in royalty
fees.
   Royalties were paid, for example, when the song was used in the
films ``10,''``The Great Santini,''``Oh God'' and ``Fame.''
   ``Happy Birthday to You'' was based on a melody composed in the
1890s by two kindergarten teachers in Louisville, Ky. The song's
lyrics were written later and the song was not copyrighted until
1935. When the copyright expires in 2010, Warner will no longer be
entitled to royalties.
   Birchtree owns 50,000 titles, of which about 1,700 are actively
collecting royalty fees, the Times said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
