<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Cobb     12-20 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Cobb,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radio Announcer Who Coined Nashville Nickname Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Cobb, the former radio announcer
credited with coining Nashville's nickname _ ``Music City, U.S.A.''
_ died following heart surgery. He was 76.
   The veteran announcer died Saturday in Park View Medical Center;
he underwent surgery Wednesday.
   Cobb was affiliated with WSM Inc. from 1937 to 1972, and, with
Louie Buck and Judd Collins, was one of the first three announcers
at the Grand Ole Opry.
   An account in the Nov. 5, 1964, edition of The Nashville
Tennessean said Cobb ad-libbed an announcement during a 1960 program
that ``the sounds listeners were hearing on WSM radio were coming
from `Music City, USA.'''
   ``He had a vast store of classical knowledge and, for years,
hosted every music show on the station,'' including a Sunday night
show on classical music, WSM production manager Tom Bryant said.
   He is survived by his wife, one son and three grandchildren.
</TEXT>
