<DOCNO> AP881220-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 0912EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Ruble     12-20 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Ruble ,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Says Ruble Exchange Rate Won't Go Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top trade official in the Soviet government
today denied the ruble will be devalued by 50 percent in 1990, as
had been widely assumed in the West from Soviet media reports in the
past two weeks.
   The newspaper articles, starting with one in Sovietskaya
Industria, or Soviet Industry, had said the ruble exchange rate
would fall by 50 percent ``on trade deals'' starting Jan. 1, 1990.
Western economists and businessmen assumed this meant a drop from
the current government-decreed exchange rate of $1.60 per ruble to
80 cents per ruble.
   But that applies only to the ruble's value in domestic deals
among Soviet enterprises, not to its value in trade with foreigners,
Vladimir Kamentsev, Deputy Chairman of the Council of Ministers and
head of the State Foreign Economic Commission, told a press briefing.
   ``This should not be taken as a change in the ruble standard
versus foreign currency,'' Kamentsev said.
   He said the 50 percent change applies only to exchanges of
foreign currency between various Soviet businesses, government-owned
and cooperative.
   A Western diplomat, who declined to be named, noted at the time
of the original report that it did not say which exchange rate would
drop, a critical distinction as the Soviet Union reputedly has 3,000
different exchange rates for different products and different
trading partners. Kamentsev refused to clarify that question.
   Kamentsev said, however, that the current change is one step in
the direction of a ruble that someday will be freely convertible to
foreign currency. He declined to name a date for convertibility, but
said it would come after a major price reform.
   Rubles now are virtually worthless outside the Soviet Union. The
Soviet government sells rubles to tourists and businessmen at a rate
of $1.60 per ruble, but the black market rate is 25 to 30 cents per
ruble.
   Kamentsev also said that starting next year, Soviet enterprises
will be allowed to trade their foreign currency with other Soviet
businesses in a thrice-yearly currency auction. However, he did not
explain how the apparently open prices of an auction would co-exist
with a set rate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
