<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EmployeeThievery     12-20 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Employee Thievery,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transit Authority Proposes No-Pockets Approach To Fighting Theft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City transit officials have come up with a
simple solution they say will make it harder for employees to pocket
bus fares _ eliminate employees' pockets.
   ``Opportunity makes the thief,'' Gordana Swanson, president of
the Southern California Rapid Transit District board, said Monday as
she endorsed a plan to distribute pocketless uniforms to all workers
who handle bus fares.
   Many workers who handle the money already wear such uniforms. For
those who don't, Ms. Swanson suggested sewing shut the pockets on
their clothes until new uniforms can be provided.
   The workers who still have pockets remove fare boxes from buses
with special keys and put the money in carts. The carts are then
delivered to armored trucks, which take the cash to the transit
authority's counting rooms.
   The new uniforms were one of several recommendations Transit
Authority General Manager Alan Pegg made in response to an audit
warning of ``casual pilferage and organized theft'' of fare-box
revenue. Estimates of annual losses range from thousands to millions
of dollars.
   Auditors said most of the losses occurred in the counting rooms,
where they said they saw money lying loose on the floors. In
addition, workers who count fares were allowed to leave the building
without being checked by security guards, auditors said.
</TEXT>
