<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NIreland-Inquest     12-20 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NIreland-Inquest,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Orders New Inquest Into IRA Shootings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northern Ireland's highest court
today ordered a new inquest into the deaths of three unarmed Irish
Republican Army members shot by police six years ago.
   The Northern Ireland Court of Appeal ruled that the three police
officers who fired the shots can be forced to testify at the new
hearing. No date has been set.
   But Sir Brian Hutton, the chief justice, made it clear that the
police officers _ who have been acquitted of murdering one of the
IRA members _ can refuse to testify on grounds of possible
self-incrimination.
   The original inquest was adjourned in late November.
   The three members of the Royal Ulster Constabulary, the
province's police force, were among five police officers involved in
the ambush on IRA members Gervase McKerr, Eugene Toman and Sean
Burns. The three men allegedly failed to stop their car at a police
checkpoint in County Armagh in November 1982.
   Eleanor McKerr, the widow of one of the victims, fought to have
the courts order the police officers to testify and be
cross-examined rather than submit written statements.
   Coroner James Elliott had ruled he had no power to compel the
police officers to appear in person. However, his original inquest
has been scrapped and the jury discharged.
   Inquests also are to be held into the deaths of three other
unarmed Roman Catholics _ two of them guerrillas and the third a
teen-age civilian _ who died in two separate police ambushes in 1982.
   Police said all the deaths occurred in the normal course of
anti-terrorist activity, but subsequent evidence suggested the
killings might have been avoided and that police were operating
under a ``shoot-to-kill'' policy.
   The mainly Catholic IRA is trying to oust Britain from Northern
Ireland and unite the majority Protestant province with the Irish
Republic.
</TEXT>
