<1ST_LINE>r i PM-RevengeKilling     12-20 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Revenge Killing,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Father Of Slaying Victim Shoots Killer During Court Hearing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PIRAEUS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted murderer was shot to death
today by the father of his victim during an appeal court hearing to
reduce his sentence, police said.
   Ioannis Venierakis, 36, serving a life sentence, was shot with a
pistol by Ioannis Papadosifos, 62, who was arrested by court police,
a police official said.
   ``I did it for the memory and honor of my son,'' Papadosifos was
quoted as saying later at a Piraeus police station.
   Venierakis was convicted of the 1983 slaying of 27-year-old
Manolis Papadosifos. Venierakis had suspected that the victim was
having an affair with his wife, said the police official, who was
unidentified according to Greek practice.
   The father had denied Venierakis' allegation.
   Both men come from the island of Crete. The court hearing was
scheduled to take place there but was moved to Piraeus, a port city
near Athens, for fear that violence would break out, the official
said.
   There are instances in Crete where families seek revenge and
carry on vendettas that last for generations.
