<1ST_LINE>u i PM-PLO-Dissent 1stLd-Writethru a0474 12-20 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PLO-Dissent, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0474,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede NICOSIA</HEAD>
<HEAD>Palestinian Factions Say They Seek to Oust Arafat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Palestinian hardliners saying they
will continue to fight Israel, seek to oust Arafat. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS FARES</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian hardliners said today they
will continue the armed struggle against Israel to torpedo Yasser
Arafat's peace efforts and will seek to oust Arafat from the PLO
leadership, a Palestinian source said.
   The senior Palestinian source, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said that Syrian-backed radical factions were meeting in
Damascus to discuss ``practical steps and measures to counter
Arafat's surrenderist moves.''
   The radicals have denounced the PLO chief's explicit recognition
of Israel and renunciation of terrorism. Arafat's statements, made
in Geneva last week, led the United States to open an official
dialogue with the Palestine Liberation Organization for the first
time since the U.S. banned PLO contacts 13 years ago.
   Arafat was in Yugoslavia today as part of his bid to gain
international support for his peace initiative.
   Opposition to Arafat's campaign, which is aimed at securing an
independent Palestinian state in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip, appeared to be gathering momentum among Palestinians who
believe he has made too many concessions.
   The United States has stressed it will break off talks if the PLO
carries out terrorist attacks. While attacks by non-PLO factions may
fall outside that condition, they could seriously undermine Arafat's
initiative.
   The factions meeting in Damascus included the Popular Front for
the Liberation of Palestine-General Command, led by former Syrian
Army Capt. Ahmed Jibril, the Fatah-Uprising of Col. Saeed Mousa and
the small Saiqa group, the source said.
   He said the radicals had formed a committee to discuss ways of
ousting Arafat and his allies to install a militant leadership
``which will adhere firmly to the PLO charter and sponsor the armed
struggle against Israel as the only way to liberate the occupied
territories.''
   The committee, he claimed, includes some leaders of the yearlong
Palestinian uprising in the West Bank and Gaza and ``various
Palestinian personalities, most of whom held senior posts in the
PLO.'' He did not identify them further.
   On Monday, a member of the PLO's governing body reflected a
possible serious split in the organization's top ranks by calling
Arafat's recognition of Israel and renunciation of terrorism
``Arafat's personal opinion.''
   Mustafa Zibri, a member of the PLO executive committee, said the
PLO chairman's statements last week were ``incompatible with the
resolutions of the latest Palestine National Council meeting.''
   The council, the PLO's parliament-in-exile, met in Algeria last
month to declare an independent Palestinian state. It indirectly
recognized Israel's existence and condemned terrorism, but did not
go far enough to gain U.S. recognition.
   The PLO is an umbrella organization of eight different
Palestinian guerrilla factions dominated by Arafat's mainstream
Fatah group. Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of Israel claims it is
bent on Israel's destruction.
   Zibri's statement could represent serious dissent because of his
seat on the PLO's 15-member executive commitee, which includes
representatives of six Palestinian guerrilla groups as well as
independents. Fatah has three seats.
   Zibri is the sole committee representative of the Popular Front
for the Liberation of Palestine, a Syrian-backed Marxist group
headed by George Habash, who told Arafat at the Algiers meeting that
his faction does not believe in moderation.
   It was not immediately known whether Habash endorsed Zibri's
statement, which was signed with Zibri's guerrilla name, Abu Ali
Mustafa. The statement was delivered from Damascus, to The
Associated Press in Nicosia. The office of the Popular Front in
Damascus confirmed the statement.
</TEXT>
