<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SriLanka 5thLd-Writethru a0511 12-20 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0511,0745</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Wins Presidential Race; Violence Continues</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 5th pvs, ``Premadasa said ...'' to UPDATE
with opposition reax. PICKS up 6th pvs, ``As promised ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Ranasinghe Premadasa,
vowing to halt ethnic violence on this Indian Ocean island, was
elected president with slightly more than half the votes, the
government said today.
   Earlier today, Sinhalese extremists hacked and shot to death nine
supporters of Premadasa's governing United National Party in a town
east of Colombo, police said.
   ``The politics of terror has no place in the temple of
democracy,'' Premadasa said in a televised address immediately after
the announcement. ``I will eradicate fear and suppresion. I will
restore law and order.''
   Premadasa received 50.4 percent of the vote in Monday's election,
edging former Prime Minister Sirimavo Bandaranaike of the opposition
Sri Lanka Freedom Party, according to Commissioner of Elections
Chandrananda de Silva.
   Premadasa has vowed to remove controversial Indian peacekeeping
troops when he takes over Sri Lanka's most powerful government post
Jan. 2 for a six-year term.
   Ms. Bandaranaike had no immediate comment on the balloting, and a
man who answered the phone at her home said she was ill. But one of
her close allies said she had described the results as ``unjust''
and would not accept them. The associate spoke on condition of
anonymity and would not elaborate.
   As promised, outgoing President Junius R. Jayewardene today
dissolved Parliament and called new legislative elections for Feb.
15. He ordered an islandwide curfew to take effect after the
official election results were announced.
   ``I particularly wish to ask, to appeal, to those who belong to
the winning side, to treat your opponents who have lost with
friendship, affection and love,'' he said.
   With all 182 polling districts counted, Premadasa had 2,569,199
votes, or 50.4 percent, compared with 2,299,770, or 45 percent for
Mrs. Bandaranaike, the election commissioner said.
   The remaining votes went to a leftist coalition candidate, Ossie
Abeygoonesekera. The turnout was 55 percent, well below the
nationwide rate of 80 percent in the 1982 presidential election as a
campaign of imitidation by extremists apparently kept many people at
home.
   Officials have blamed Sinhalese extremists of the People's
Liberation Front for the recent campaign of terror. The extremists
had threatened to kill anyone who voted on Monday.
   The military reported five Indian troops were killed in an ambush
by Tamil ethnic minority rebels Monday, bringing the reported
election day death toll to at least 20.
   Today's attacks occurred in Bandarawela, about 75 miles east of
Colombo, local authorities said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
They did not elaborate.
   The threats kept thousands from the polls. In the north, where
militants of the Tamil minority are fighting for an independent
state, many voting districts reported less than 10 percent turnout.
   And in the south, where Sinhalese extremists oppose government
concessions to the Tamils, turnout ranged from 20 percent to 70
percent.
   Premadasa was the standard-bearer for the party of Jayewardene,
who was barred by the constitution from seeking a third term.
   Under Jayewardene's rule, Sri Lanka neared the brink of ruin
because of ethnic violence that has killed nearly 10,000 people
since 1983, when Tamils began an uprising against the Sinhalese.
   With the help of neighboring India _ the subcontinent's
superpower and home to 60 million Tamils _ Jayewardene signed a
peace accord in July 1987 aimed at ending the Tamil insurgency.
   The pact guaranteed some autonomy to the Tamils, who make up 18
percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people _ and invited India to help
end the uprising by sending troops, which now number about 47,000.
   The People's Liberation Front vehemently opposed the pact and
vowed to kill anyone who supported the government after it was
signed. The front has been blamed for hundreds of slayings since.
   Both Premadasa and Mrs. Bandaranaike, who was prime minister in
1960-66 and 1970-77, opposed the Tamil accord.
   Premadasa has called for the phased or immediate withdrawal of
Indian troops.
   But Indian High Commissioner J.N. Dixit has indicated his country
will not accept unilateral action.
   Premadasa also campaigned as a champion of the poor and has
promised a monthly $75 to the country's most impoverished families.
He did not explain where the money would come from.
</TEXT>
