<1ST_LINE>r a PM-InaugurationBand     12-20 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Inauguration Band,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Disputes Selection Of Band For Bush's Inaugural Parade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FARMINGTON, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Organizers of George Bush's inaugural
parade passed over what was judged one of Maine's best high school
bands in favor of the school that serves Bush's summer home.
   It's ``a rotten, stinking deal,'' said William L. Reid, the head
of the boosters' club for the Mount Blue High School band.
   The 77-member band, located in this western Maine town, submitted
video and audio tapes of its performances to the inaugural committee.
   The committee had said selections would be based on merit,
including past achievements, and the Mount Blue band believed its
victory last month in the annual Maine Band Directors Association
competition would give it the edge.
   But Reid learned Monday that the Mount Blue band was rejected.
Instead, the only Maine band picked to play in the parade was the
one from Kennebunk High School, which serves students from Bush's
home in Kennebunkport.
   Reid and other supporters of the Mount Blue band complained to
members of Maine's congressional delegation that political
considerations outweighed other factors in the band's selection.
   ``People are enraged,'' said Rosemary Poulson, editor of the
Franklin County Journal in Farmington.
   The leader of the Kennebunk band made no apologies.
   ``I can't help it if our band is from Kennebunk,'' Bruce Lewia
said. ``I'm sure there were political connections. That's just the
way the ball bounces.''
   Lewia's band has not competed in the state competition, but he
said it has participated in regional competitions outside Maine.
   ``We're not some scrub band,'' he said. ``We're a good band.''
</TEXT>
