<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ChemicalWeapons     12-20 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chemical Weapons,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Making Diplomatic Efforts To Stop Libyan Chemical Weapons
Production</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is making diplomatic efforts
to dissuade other nations and private companies from selling Libya
materials needed to start up its huge chemical weapons plant, the
State Department's top counter-terrorism official said today.
   Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said Monday that the Libyan
plant was ``on the verge of full-scale production,'' and L. Paul
Bremer, head of the department's counter-terrorism office, said
official are concerned its products might get into the hands of
terrorist groups around the world.
   Bremer, interviewed today on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America,''
said there have been discussions with several countries in what he
described as ``a major diplomatic effort to try to persuade
companies and countries around the world not to sell the kind of
precursors that are necessary for chemical weapons production to
Libya.''
   Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi has denied his country has
developed the capability for chemical warfare.
   Bremer said in an Associated Press interview on Monday that Lybia
has a ``long-standing, close relationship with some of the world's
most murderous terrorist groups'' and has been willing to provide
destructive weapons to those groups.
   He said, however, there was no evidence the north African nation
had distributed any chemical weapons to others.
   U.S. officials previously had acknowledged U.S. concern about a
large chemical facility reportedly based in a mountain chain 35
miles from Libya's Mediterranean coast.
   ``We've been following the developments of this plant now for
some time. It goes back even earlier than the first press reports
about it in the fall,'' said Bremer on ABC.
   ``I think our objective now is to try to see if we can't persuade
other people to stop providing the kind of chemical agents which are
used in this kind of plant. That's the major objective now of our
diplomacy,'' Bremer said.
   Asked whether the United States would use military action to
prevent chemical weapons production in Libya, Bremer said, ``I'm not
going to comment on what kind of military measures might be used.''
   The United States has previously used military action against
Libya, bombing Tripoli in April 1986 in retaliation for the
country's alleged role in terrorist acts.
   Bremer also urged progress toward a worldwide ban on chemical
weapons at an international conference on disarmament scheduled to
reconvene in February.
</TEXT>
