<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RishSentencing     12-20 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rish Sentencing,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Life Sentence For Woman Involved In Burying Kidnap Victim Alive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANKAKEE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman convicted in the kidnap-murder of
businessman Stephen Small, who suffocated when buried alive, was
sentenced to life in prison without possibility of parole.
   ``I just want to say I am not guilty of those charges, never
was,'' Nancy Rish told Judge John Michela. ``I am very sorry for
what happened, for what I was associated with.''
   The woman cried and hugged her mother after hearing the sentence.
   Small, a member of a prominent media family and great-grandson of
a former Illinois governor, was kidnapped Sept. 2, 1987. His body
was unearthed two days later after his wife received a muffled
telephone call seeking $1 million in ransom.
   Nancy Small was unable to understand the tape of her husband
reading the ransom delivery instructions, and the money never was
paid.
   ``There was not one grain of remorse, not one grain of salt in
the tears of this woman for Stephen Small and his family,''
prosecutor Michael Ficaro told Michela before Ms. Rish was sentenced
Monday. ``The crocodile tears we saw at the trial and those we see
now are for Nancy Rish, not for Stephen Small.''
   Prosecutors said Ms. Rish, 26, joined with her boyfriend, Daniel
Edwards, in the plot. They said Ms. Rish lured Small from his home
with a telephone call so he could be abducted by Edwards.
   Small, 40, was taken to a remote area between Kankakee and the
Indiana line, placed in a homemade wooden box with a breathing tube
and buried. The ventilation system in the box failed and Small
suffocated.
   Edwards was convicted of murder and kidnapping in May and
sentenced to die, but prosecutors said Ms. Rish was not eligible for
the death penalty.
   Before her conviction Nov. 2, Ms. Rish claimed that witnesses
against her had lied, and that she was the victim of mistaken
identity.
   Small's late father was head of Mid-America Media Group, whose
properties included 11 radio stations, and his uncle was head of
Small Newspapers Inc., and editor and publisher of the The Daily
Journal in Kankakee.
</TEXT>
