<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LaRoucheTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0502 12-20 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LaRouche Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0502,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Deciding Whether To Hold Second Trial For LaRouche</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 7th graf, `The 66-year-old ...,' to CORRECT date of
sentencing from Jan. 23 to Jan. 27. Picks up 8th graf, `LaRouche,
who ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After the conviction of Lyndon H. LaRouche Jr. in a
case involving $30 million in defaulted loans, the government is
reviewing whether to proceed with a new trial of the political
maverick on related charges here.
   The move marks a change in course, since federal prosecutors had
vowed to pursue the Boston case regardless of the verdict in U.S.
District Court in Alexandria, Va.
   The complex Boston case, which ended in a mistrial in May,
included allegations of government infiltration of LaRouche groups.
A retrial is scheduled to begin Feb. 22.
   A Virginia jury on Friday found LaRouche and six associates
guilty on all 13 counts of tax and mail fraud conspiracy for failing
to repay $30 million in loans from supporters, including one woman
who testified she lost $112,800 in life savings.
   ``The Boston case is different,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney
John Markham, who also prosecuted the Virginia case.
   ``It charges different offenses and there is therefore no logical
reason why it should not go forward. But an office-wide decision
will have to be made after all appropriate people are consulted,''
he said Monday.
   The 66-year-old LaRouche faces up to 65 years in prison and $3.25
million in fines; sentencing in Virginia is set for Jan. 27.
   LaRouche, who has run for president four times, is known for his
unconventional views, including supporting an AIDS quarantine and
charging that former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger and the
Queen of England have ties to drug trafficking.
   In Boston, LaRouche, six aides and five political organizations
are charged with conspiring to obstruct a federal grand jury
investigation into allegations that LaRouche's 1984 presidential
campaign raised more than $2 million through credit card and loan
fraud.
   LaRouche is charged with one count of conspiracy for allegedly
ordering supporters to destroy records and refuse to cooperate with
investigators. All the aides and organizations also are charged with
conspiracy, and four of the groups are charged with fraud. Three
more defendants are fugitives.
   U.S. District Judge Robert E. Keeton called a mistrial after four
jurors complained about the length and conduct of the case, which
was repeatedly delayed by defense motions. The trial began a year
ago.
   The new court date hinges on a federal appeals court ruling on
whether the trial would violate defendants' protection against being
tried twice on the same charges. Attorneys for both sides expect the
1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals to support a new trial.
   Defense lawyers maintain the Virginia convictions make the Boston
case moot and that a retrial would waste government money. They long
have charged that the case is politically motivated, an accusation
prosecutors deny.
</TEXT>
