<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Gorbachev     12-20 0172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Gorbachev,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan, Gorbachev To Exchange Televised New Year's Greetings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has taped a greeting for
broadcast on Soviet television on New Year's Day and Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev is expected to respond in kind, the
White House said today.
   It would be the third time the two leaders have exchanged
televised New Year's greetings.
   They began the practice in 1986 after their first summit meeting
in Geneva.
   In 1987, the Soviets declined to take part in such an exchange,
saying U.S.-Soviet relations were not good enough to justify it.
Reagan taped a radio message that was broadcast over the Voice of
America, but was jammed in the Soviet Union.
   The exchange was resumed in 1988.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the president
videotaped his message last week. He said the brief message
``doesn't deal with policy issues.''
   He said details are now being worked out with the Soviets and he
anticipated that U.S. television networks would be receiving a
Gorbachev tape for their consideration.
</TEXT>
