<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-DrugConference     12-20 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Drug Conference,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Conference Adopts Convention Against Illicit Drug Trafficking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. conference today an adopted an
international convention against illicit drug trafficking and drug
abuse that it hopes will deal an efficient blow to those who sell
and use drugs.
   ``It's significant because it represents a commitment by over a
hundred other nations to cooperate in fighting the problems of drug
trafficking and drug abuse,'' U.S. Attorney General Richard
Thornburgh said at a news conference.
   ``It's apparent that no one nation alone or within its own
borders can deal with the multinational operations of the drug
cartels,'' Thornburgh said.
   The convention for the first time gives all signatory countries
the right of extradition of suspected drug traffickers and the right
to confiscate all their assets.
   The document, first conceived four years ago, was signed by 43
countries, including the United States, at the close of the
monthlong U.N. conference.
   Sixty-three other nations participating in the closed-door
gathering adopted the convention by consensus, according to Axel
Wuestenhage of the U.N. Information office.
   It may take several years for the new convention to become
legally binding. To have legal force, it must be ratified by
parliaments or other national bodies in the signatory countries,
then given to the U.N. secretary-general for notification.
   Many conference delegates were optimistic.
   Asked how the new convention matched recent anti-drug legislation
in the United States, Thornburgh said, ``It's a very good fit.'
   The provisions on money laundering, confiscation of drug dealers'
assets and cooperation in pursuing the traffickers are similar to
U.S. legislation signed last month, Thornburgh said.
   The United States would need only ``a minor adjustment'' to
comply with Article 3 of the Convention, he added. That article
deals with the identification, tracing, freezing and forfeiture of
proceeds derived from drug trafficking.
   The article is seen as a major way to toughen two earlier
international accords by cracking down on modern drug traffickers
whose networks straddle the world and involve billions of dollars.
   The new document, known formally as the Convention Against
Illicit Trafic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances,
complements the 1961 Convention on Narcotic Drugs signed by 121
contries and the 1971 Convention on Psychotropic Substances so far
ratified by 88 countries.
   Besides providing for asset forfeiture and extradition, the new
document foresees mutual legal assistance and cooperation in
training police and customs officers fighting drugs.
   It also stipulates how to monitor substances frequently used in
the illicit manufacture of drugs, to eradicate illicit plant
cultivation and suppress traffic by sea, in free-trade zones and
free ports.
   Thornburgh said the United States would have preferred stronger
language on extradition, with those engaged in crimes linked to drug
trafficking eligible for extradition ``irrespective of their
nationality whenever they may be found.''
   A special international commission will be charged with
monitoring implementation, Thornburgh said.
   Asked about the cooperation of Switzerland, with its strict laws
on banking secrecy, Thornburgh said Washington had experience with
Switzerland which proved ``very positive ... with regard to waiving
bank secrecy laws when criminal conduct is involved.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
