<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SafetyStandard     12-20 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Safety Standard,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OMB Trying To Stop Safety Standards Duplication</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Office of Management and Budget is seeking
to prevent two federal agencies from duplicating each other's work
in setting safety standards for cleanup of hazardous materials, the
White House said today.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said a meeting is
scheduled on the issue this week and a decision ``should be
forthcoming fairly soo.''
   Fitzwater said the problem of duplication arose as OMB considered
proposed regulations by the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration governing safety of state and local emergency workers
involved in cleanup operations.
   A similar standard is being developed by the Environmental
Protection Agency to cover state and local goverment workers who are
not under the jurisdication of OSHA. Fitzwater said this rule is not
expected to be ready for about 90 days.
   Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, said in a letter to OMB on Monday
that he had ``grave concerns'' about reports that the budget agency
was intervening in the matter and that ``excluding state and local
employees from the final standard would deny coverage to the very
people Congress intended to protect.''
   ``The OSHA regulation is before OMB,'' said Fitzwater. ``It is
going through normal processing. We don't feel there is any abnormal
delay. There is no real opposition to the regulations.''
   ``There is a meeting scheduled for the next few days to consider
the two regulations and try to eliminate duplication wherever
possible,'' he said. ``It should be forthcoming fairly soon.''
</TEXT>
