<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PolygamistTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0521 12-20 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polygamist Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0521,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polygamist Clan Murder Trial Goes To Jury</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 1 graf to UPDATE with deliberations resuming; Addam
is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COALVILLE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury today deliberated for the second
day charges against three polygamist clan members in the slaying of
a law-enforcement officer, who was killed after a 13-day siege at
the clan's rural compound.
   The second-degree murder case went to the jury Monday night after
more than six hours of instructions and closing arguments and nine
days of testimony. Jurors deliberated three hours, then were sent
home for the night.
   In closing arguments, prosecutor Creighton Horton said clan
patriarch Addam Swapp, 27, his brother Jonathan Swapp, 21, and
brother-in-law John Timothy Singer, 22, deliberately chose a course
of confrontation that led to bloodshed.
   The three are charged in the Jan. 28 death of Utah Corrections
Lt. Fred House. House was killed and Addam Swapp seriously wounded
when a shootout ended the standoff at the clan's Marion farm that
began Jan. 16, when Addam Swapp bombed a Mormon chapel.
   Under Utah law, the maximum penalty for second-degree murder is
life in prison.
   The three defendants and Vickie Singer, wife of the late clan
patriarch John Singer, who was killed by authorities in 1979, have
been sentenced to prison terms for federal violations in the bombing
and standoff. Vickie Singer is the mother of Addam Swapp's two wives.
   Addam Swapp was sentenced to 15 years, John Timothy Singer and
Jonathan Swapp to 10 years and Vickie Singer to five years.
   Horton told jurors that Addam Swapp ``basically declared war on
the church, state and nation'' when he bombed the chapel. Swapp
contended he was divinely inspired to commit the act on the ninth
anniversary of John Singer's death, but Horton dismissed the clan
leader's claims.
   ``God didn't place those weapons in their hands,'' Horton said.
   Addam Swapp's co-counsel, John Bucher, countered that just
because clan members were well-armed did not mean they intended to
use their weapons.
   Bucher told jurors Horton was trying to ``divert your attention
from the real issue _ it's about what (Addam Swapp) did with the
guns. He didn't use them offensively.''
   Singer has acknowleged firing the fatal bullet from his bedroom
window, but maintained he was aiming at police dogs.
   Attorney Fred Metos, representing Singer, called House's death a
``tragic accident'' born of his client's panicked attempt to protect
the Swapp brothers from the dogs. Metos urged the jury to find
Singer guilty of the lesser charge of negligent homicide.
   Jonathan Swapp's attorney, Earl Spafford, said his client only
fired his rifle to try to keep an FBI team from shooting his wounded
brother again.
   But prosecutor Dave Schwendiman said Singer and the Swapp
brothers had willfully and knowingly prolonged the confrontation and
could have accepted a peaceful compromise at any time during the
siege.
</TEXT>
