<1ST_LINE>u i PM-RedCross-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0545 12-20 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Red Cross-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0545,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Red Cross Suspends All Operations In Lebanon Following New Threats</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with details. CORRECTS number foreign
hostages held to 15. No pickup. ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Committee of the Red Cross said
today it was suspending its operations in Lebanon after receiving
new threats against the lives of its staffers.
   The decision came four days after the release of Peter Winkler,
the chief Red Cross delegate in south Lebanon who was held hostage
for a month.
   A brief news release said the committee made its decision after
hearing Monday of ``serious threats against its delegates on mission
in Lebanon, placing their lives in acute danger.'' It said the
relief operations would be resumed as soon as the threats are
``clearly and unequivocally withdrawn.''
   The Red Cross now has a staff of 17 in Lebanon. Ten others were
withdrawn after Winkler was kidnapped Nov. 16.
   A Red Cross spokesman, Carlos Bauverd, declined to elaborate on
the nature of the threats or say what groups were believed behind
them. He also would not say how the committee learned of the threats.
   There was also no word on when the staffers would be pulled out
of Lebanon.
   Winkler was taken while working at a refugee camp in the southern
port of Sidon. Swiss Foreign Minister Rene Felber said that in
indirect contacts, the kidnappers identified themselves as members
of a dissident Palestinian group called ``Organization of Socialist
Revolution.''
   Felber said the kidnappers were demanding a lenient sentence for
a Lebanese Shiite hijacker, Hussein Hariri, who is to go on trial
before the Swiss Supreme Court Feb. 20.
   Hariri hijacked an Air Afrique jetliner July 14, 1987 and killed
a French passenger before he was subdued during a stop at Geneva
airport.
   Fifteen other foreigners, including nine Americans, are missing
and presumed kidnapped in Lebanon. The longest held is Terry
Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The Associated Press,
who was abducted March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
