<DOCNO> AP881220-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 1132EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KlansmanGuilty     12-20 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Klansman Guilty,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Klan Leader Pleads Guilty In Clash With Black Marchers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Ku Klux Klan leader pleaded
guilty to a misdemeanor conspiracy charge stemming from a 1979
gunfight and brawl between Klansmen and black marchers.
   Terry Joe Tucker, who was ``exalted cyclops'' of the Cullman
Klavern in 1979, admitted conspiring with other Klansmen to disrupt
the march in Decatur by blacks, who were protesting the arrest of a
black man in the rapes of three white women.
   Tucker entered his guilty plea Monday in federal court in
Birmingham. Prosecutors have not recommended a sentence; U.S.
District Judge James H. Hancock delayed sentencing until at least
late January.
   Tucker faces up to one year in prison and a $1,000 fine.
   Tucker is the third former Klansman to plead guilty in the case.
A federal jury convicted a fourth man; five others are scheduled to
stand trial Jan. 9 in Birmingham.
   The clash came during one of several protests blacks staged after
the arrest of Tommy Lee Hines, who was charged with raping the three
white women in 1978. One march ended in a gunfight and brawl with
Klansmen in downtown Decatur in which several marchers and policemen
were injured.
   Hines was convicted of one of the rape counts and sent to prison.
The Alabama Court of Criminal Appeals later ruled that he was
mentally incompetent, and he was moved to a mental hospital.
   Tommy Spina, an attorney for Tucker, said the former Klansman
pleaded guilty in part because Hancock ruled last month that the
conspiracy charge was a misdemeanor rather than a felony.
   Also, the U.S. Supreme Court refused last week to review several
legal challenges to court rulings the Klan defendants had pursued,
clearing the way for the January trial, Spina said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
