<2ND_LINE>PM-Myerson Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0451,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Deliberates Second Day In Bess Myerson Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with jury resuming deliberations,
editing pvs to conform; Picks up 8th graf pvs, `Miss Myerson ...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal jury deliberating charges against
former Miss America Bess Myerson asked today to rehear some of the
testimony from the prosecution's star witness.
   Miss Myerson and two others are charged with a divorce-fixing
conspiracy. After 12 weeks of testimony, the jury began deliberating
Monday and resumed today.
   In late morning the panel asked to re-hear testimony by Sukhreet
Gabel as well as the judge's instructions about direct and
circumstantial evidence.
   Miss Myerson, who was Miss America in 1945; her lover, one-time
city contractor Carl ``Andy'' Capasso, 43; and former state Supreme
Court Justice Hortense Gabel, 76, are charged with plotting to cut
Capasso's temporary support payments to his estranged wife.
   All three are charged with conspiracy, mail fraud and aiding the
violation of state bribery laws.
   ``The gist of conspiracy is agreement,'' U.S. District Judge John
F. Keenan explained to jurors Monday during nearly three hours of
instructions.
   It wasn't necessary to find any illegal activity ``actually had
been carried out'' for a conspiracy conviction, he said, adding that
they simply ``must find there was a meeting of the minds of at least
two of the defendants.''
   Prosecutors contended that Miss Myerson, 64, the city's former
cultural affairs commissioner, bribed Mrs. Gabel by giving a
$19,000-a-year city job to the judge's emotionally troubled and
chronically unemployed daughter, Sukhreet, 39.
   Miss Myerson also faces an obstruction of justice count for an
alleged attempt to influence the grand jury testimony of Ms. Gabel.
   The key witness on that count was Ms. Gabel, who conceded in her
testimony that her version of the facts had changed in the past and
might change again. She also said that electroshock treatment she
underwent for clinical depression left her memory, at times, ``like
Swiss cheese.''
   None of the defendants testified in their own behalf and Keenan
told jurors it would be ``unfair, improper and indeed un-American''
to hold that against them.
   The prosecution's case consisted mainly of circumstantial
evidence because there were no witnesses to the alleged bribe
scheme. There were, however, two undisputed, facts: Sukhreet Gabel
was hired as Miss Myerson's personal assistant in late August 1983,
and the judge slashed Capasso's interim support payments from $1,850
a week to $850 a week on Sept. 14, 1983.
   The defense contended that Ms. Gabel's hiring may have been
unwise but was not illegal. The defense also offered legal and
financial explanations for the lowering of Capasso's support
payments.
   Miss Myerson faces a maximum of 30 years in prison and $513,000
in fines if convicted on all counts. Her two co-defendants face up
to 25 years and $263,000 in fines.
   Capasso, once a multimillionaire city sewage contractor, is
serving a three-year prison term for income tax evasion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
