<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Peru     12-20 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peru,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governing Party Names Garcia Rival to Key Post</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing Aprista Party today named
President Alan Garcia's chief rival to its top administrative post,
effectively giving the rival control over the party.
   Former Prime Minister Luis Alva Castro was elected
secretary-general of the center-left party by a majority of
delegates at its 16th National Congress, the party said in a
statement.
   On Saturday, Garcia offered his resignation as party president
after he recieved a bitter reception at the convention. Over the
weekend, party leaders indicated they would reject the offer. But no
rejection has been issued, and it appeared today that the post of
party president would go vacant.
   Today's vote gives Alva Castro, who is also the nation's current
second vice president, control of the governing party.
   Analysts said Alva Castro will likely use the power provided by
his new post to force Garcia to form a new Cabinet composed of
mainstream party members.
   Garcia has been Peru's president since July 1985. His resignation
from the party role did not affect his position as head of the
country, but indicated a serious eroding of his supoport.
   His party opponents frequently accused him of ignoring the wishes
of large sectors of the party in running the country, and his
reputation has plummeted in the face of the worst financial crisis
to hit Peru this century.
   Alva Castro served as prime minister and finance minister during
the first two years of Garcia's five-year term but resigned in a
power struggle stemming over differences with Garcia on economic
policy, analysts say.
   Alva Castro defeated Luis Negreiros, incumbent secretary general
and Garcia ally, for the post in voting that concluded around dawn
today.
   Since resigning from the Cabinet, Alva Castro has been
campaigning for secretary-general, considered a springboard to the
party candidacy for the nation's presidency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
