<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 1227EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Movie     12-20 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Movie,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China, U.S. Companies to Make Movie of First Emperor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese and U.S. filmmakers will try to show that
China's first emperor can be just as big a movie star as its last.
   China International Television Corp., a division of the state-run
China Central Television, and Lumina Productions of Los Angeles on
Tuesday signed an agreement on production of ``China the First
Emperor,'' a feature-length film of the man who united China more
than 2,000 years ago.
   ``It will be a gigantic project,'' said Lumina Vice Chairman
Sonny Luu. The film will cost between $20 million and $30 million,
and will include a cast of 30,000 to 50,000 extras, including two
divisions of the People's Liberation Army, he said.
   Filming is to begin next fall, with a release date of late 1990,
Luu said. ``Perhaps we'll be up for an Oscar in 1990,'' he said.
   ``The Last Emperor,'' the Bernardo Bertolucci-directed film of
the life of Henry Pu Yi, the child emperor when the Qing Dynasty
crumbled in 1911, won nine Oscars and was one of the most celebrated
films about China ever made.
   Luu said Lumina, an independent company making its first major
production, began working on the project four years ago, and was not
influenced by the success of the Bertolucci film.
   The U.S. side will put up 90 percent of the investment and the
Chinese partner will put up 10 percent, he said. China will receive
10 percent of profits and all earnings from the market in China.
   Richard Attenborough, director of ``Gandhi,'' has been approached
about directing the film, and the main actors will be Americans of
Oriental descent, Luu said.
   Ruan Ruolin, vice minister of the Ministry of Radio,
Broadcasting, Movie and Television, said Emperor Chin _ also known
as Qin Shi Huang _ ``was a great man in Chinese history. However, he
made many mistakes also, and making a proper assessment of this
historic figure on the screen is a very difficult but interesting
project.''
   Emperor Chin unified the country in 221 B.C., and is known for
standardizing writing and weights, starting construction of the
Great Wall to keep out northern invaders, and having the famed
terracotta warriors built near his tomb in the ancient capital of
Xian.
   He also has been criticized for brutal oppression of his subjects
that led to a peasant uprising in 209 B.C., a year after his death.
   ``He is comparable to George Washington or Alexander the Great in
the West,'' said Nick Lecong, president of Lumina. ``This film will
allow the outside world to see how China was formed.''
   Lecong, a Vietnamese-American who emigrated to the United States
in 1968, heads a food supply company in Los Angeles. Luu, also a
Vietnamese-American, arrived in the United States as a refugee in
1975.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
