<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Obit-Robinson 1stLd-Writethru a0560 12-20 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Robinson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0560,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Max Robinson, First Black Network Television Anchor, Is Dead at 49</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0570 to designate as 1st Ld-Writethru</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Max Robinson, the nation's first black network
television news anchor, died today at 49.
   Robinson died at 9:30 a.m. EST at Howard University Hospital in
the nation's capital from complications resulting from AIDS,
according to hospital spokeswoman Tonya Swanson.
   It had been three years since Robinson worked regularly in
television.
   He earned his spot in broadcasting history in 1978 when he began
co-anchoring the ABC Evening News from Chicago with Peter Jennings
in London and Frank Reynolds in Washington.
   In 1969, he had become the first black to anchor newscasts on a
major Washington station. He appeared on the 6 and 11 p.m. news on
WTOP, now WUSA, with co-anchor Gordon Peterson.
   ``He had great presence on the air,'' said James Snyder, vice
president for news for Post Newsweek Stations, who worked with
Robinson at WTOP. ``He was a very meticulous dresser. He was a very
proud man. He was very meticulous about his on-air performance. He
rarely made a mistake. He was very conscious that he was a role
model.''
   But Snyder and others said Robinson was haunted by private
demons. Friends said he labored under enormous pressure to be a role
model for others of his race.
   He was never as successful at the network as he was in local
television, where WTOP's news earned top ratings.
   Snyder said Robinson experienced extreme mood swings. Two
marriages failed.
   Over the past couple of years, Robinson had been ill, wasting
away and reduced to walking with a cane, while refusing to reveal
what his illness was.
   Survivors included four children, Mark, Maureen, Michael and
Malik.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881220-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 1316EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BeachWaste     12-20 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Beach Waste,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Points To Sewers And Landfills As Source Of Beach Waste</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH EDWARDSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The washed-up medical waste and other debris
that spoiled New York City-area beaches last summer came from
several sources, including a landfill, sewer overflows, garbage
transfer stations and storm water outlets, state officials say.
   ``We have not found any evidence of a single culprit discharging
the medical waste,'' Environmental Conservation Commissioner Thomas
Jorling said as he released a report on an investigation into the
waste.
   Several of the state's most popular beaches had to be closed
temporarily during the area's hottest summer in decades when debris
_ including syringes and blood vials _ came ashore. Waste washups
also resulted in beach closings in other Eastern states, including
New Jersey and Rhode Island, as well as along Lake Erie and Lake
Michigan.
   The report blamed the washups primarily on inadequate garbage
handling in New York City and on the weather.
   Medical waste accounted for only 1 percent to 10 percent of the
washed up debris. Jorling said Monday the highly publicized beach
closings pointed to the need for more stringent controls on all
garbage, including medical waste.
   The report highlights the need for change in New York City's
sewage and landfill systems, said a spokesman for a national
environmental organization.
   ``While an army of state, federal and local people have been
looking for midnight dumpers, the real villain here may actually be
the city sewer system and the city's landfills,'' said Mark Izeman
of the Natural Resources Defense Council.
   While much of the beach waste probably was disposed of legally,
environmental officials still believe the vials of blood that washed
ashore could have been the result of illegal dumping, said Jorling.
The vials, at least one of which contained blood contaminated by the
AIDS virus, are the subject of a criminal investigation, he said.
   The state and New York City have strengthened garbage policies
and improved facilities since the beach closings, said Jorling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881220-0104 </DOCNO>
