<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 1325EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Steinberg     12-20 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steinberg,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecution Rests Its Case in Steinberg Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecution in the trial of a former lawyer
accused of fatally beating his 6-year-old adopted daughter rested
its case today after an expert on child abuse testified that Lisa
Steinberg was a battered child.
   Besides the medical expert, the prosecution called a neighbor who
told jurors she heard sounds of violence coming from the Steinberg
apartment the night before the child was found dead.
   The defense was to begin its case later today in the 9-week-old
trial.
   Steinberg, 47, a disbarred lawyer, is charged with murder in the
November 1987 death of Lisa, who he illegally obtained at birth from
an unwed teen-ager and raised as his own.
   Lisa was removed unconscious from Steinberg's apartment the
morning of Nov. 2, and taken to St. Vincent's Hospital, where she
died of a head injury three days later.
   Steinberg denies that he hit the child, but his longtime
companion, Hedda Nussbaum, has testified that he told her the night
the child was injured that he had ``knocked Lisa down and she didn't
want to get up.''
   Steinberg contends Lisa died after choking on vegetables and her
own vomit.
   Lisa's death in an affluent, well-educated household shocked many
New Yorkers and led to a re-examination of the duty and ability of
neighbors, teachers and social workers to recognize and report
evidence of child abuse.
   Dr. Margaret McHugh testified today that Lisa was a battered
child based on medical, pediatric and autopsy reports and color
photographs taken at the hospital and at Steinberg's Greenwich
Village apartment.
   She said that multiple bruises, the child's poor hygiene and the
brain hemorrhage Lisa suffered were consistent with child abuse.
   Neighbor Joan Bonano testified Monday that she heard slaps and
screams from the apartment before the night Steinberg is accused of
beating Lisa to death.
   Ms. Bonano said she called police three or four times after
hearing the sounds from the Steinberg apartment, two floors above
her.
   Ms. Bonano also testified that Ms. Nussbaum appeared increasingly
``battered'' in the years before the child died, and that by
November 1987, Ms. Nussbaum was limping.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
