<1ST_LINE>u a PM-SweetheartShooting     12-20 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sweetheart Shooting,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Reaches Verdict In Ackerman Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper executive's stepson was found
guilty today of attempted, willful, premeditated, first-degree
murder by a jury that also found he inflicted great bodily harm on
the girlfriend he tried to kill.
   Bradley Ackerman, 24, sat stone still as the jury's verdict was
announced in a packed courtroom.
   His stepfather, Daniel Ridder, sat in a front row of the
courtroom and remained grim-faced as the jury read the verdict.
   The jury, which reached its decision late Monday and kept it
sealed overnight, issued three separate verdicts _ one finding
Ackerman guilty of attempted murder, the second finding that he used
a firearm illegally and the third saying he intentionally inflicted
great bodily injury.
   Ackerman faces a maximum sentence of life in prison with the
possibility for parole.
   Neither the victim, Julie Alban, nor her family was in court when
the verdict was read.
   Ackerman pleaded innocent to attempted first-degree murder,
saying he was in a Valium-induced stupor June 8 when he shot Miss
Alban with a single bullet to the back, paralyzing her below the
waist.
   Ackerman, who had taken more than 20 pills, then shot himself in
the chest, inflicting a wound from which he later recovered.
   Prosecutors alleged that Ackerman, stepson of the chairman of the
Press-Telegram in Long Beach, fabricated the blackout defense to
avoid taking responsibility for shooting Miss Alban, 23, in her
parents' home.
   The defense urged the jury to return a verdict, at most, of
assault with a deadly weapon, which carries a maximum sentence of
six years in prison.
   Deputy District Attorney Ken Lamb portrayed Ackerman as a
selfish, irresponsible man who fired the .38-caliber revolver with
too much precision to be suffering from a drug-induced blackout.
   But defense attorney Anthony Murray blamed Ackerman's actions on
the diazepam that he purportedly took to kill himself. Ackerman was
in a state of depression partly caused by a $30,000 gambling debt
and his failure to fulfill his early promise as a tennis player.
   Ackerman testified that on the night of the shootings he only
remembered going to Miss Alban's home and laying out the contents of
his wallet on a bed. He said he didn't remember bringing the gun.
   Miss Alban, who attended the trial in her wheelchair, testified
that she awoke as the bullet pierced her spine, then dragged herself
to the telephone to call for help.
</TEXT>
