<2ND_LINE>PM-Democratic Chairman, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0573,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Congressman Joins Race For Top Democratic Party Job</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to delete extraneous material.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Rep. James Stanton of Ohio entered the
race for chairman of the National Democratic Party today, saying he
could ``revitalize the party structure and bring all Democrats under
the same roof.''
   Stanton became the fifth Democrat to announce for the top party
post to be filled in February by a vote of some 400 members of the
Democratic National Committee.
   Stanton said he recognized that he was not the frontrunner in the
race and said Michigan State Chairman Rick Wiener was ``obviously
the insider'' for the job being vacated by Paul Kirk.
   Stanton said he could unite the party ``because I am not the
candidate of the South or the candidate of the Northeast or the
candidate of the right or the left. I am simply the candidate of the
Democratic party, the whole party.''
   Stanton said he expected to compete with Ron Brown, former top
aide to Jesse Jackson, for organized labor's support. The other two
candidates are former Rep. James Jones of Oklahoma and former Rep.
Michael Barnes of Maryland.
   Ohio Sens. John Glenn and Howard Metzenbaum have endorsed Stanton
for the post, but Ohio Democratic Chairman James Ruvulo and Vice
Chair Thea Boyd on Monday lined up behind Wiener.
   Wiener on Monday announced the support of 13 other state party
leaders from the Midwest. They include the state party chairs from
North Dakota, Minnesota, Kansas, South Dakota, Illinois, Wisconsin,
Nebraska and Indiana as well as vice chairs from several states.
   Stanton said he's confident Democratic National Committee members
who examine his background will be convinced he's right for the job.
   ``I've built a ward organization; I've run a city council; I've
run an $800 million business,'' Stanton said Monday. ``I have the
communications skills to talk to the people who are going to
financially energize any political party in this country.''
   ``I believe I have a very viable chance to win,'' Stanton said.
   Stanton's decision followed a lengthy testing-the-waters period.
   Stanton is a former congressman and Cleveland City Council
president who dropped out of public life after a 1976 Democratic
Primary loss to Metzenbaum.
   Metzenbaum, Glenn, Ohio Reps. Mary Rose Oakar and Louis Stoes and
former House Speaker Tip O'Neill of Massachusetts last week signed a
mailgram urging union leaders to back Stanton.
   The party's new leader is to be chosen at a meeting in Washington
Feb. 9 and 10.
</TEXT>
