<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--EmployeeThievery     12-20 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Employee Thievery,0172</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transit System Money Handlers Can't Pocket Cash in Overalls Without
Pockets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City transit officials have decided the best
solution to employees who pocket fare money is to get rid of the
pockets.
   ``Opportunity makes the thief,'' said Gordana Swanson, president
of the Southern California Rapid Transit District board. She
endorsed a plan Monday to immediately distribute pocketless uniforms
to all workers who handle bus fares.
   Money counters for the regional public bus system handle about
$130 million in cash per year, and officials hope that overalls
without pockets and other security measures will put the brakes on
fare box thievery.
   An audit completed in May showed the Southern California Rapid
Transit District could be losing millions of dollars each year to
casual pilferage or organized theft.
   ``In the counting rooms, workers have had uniforms without
pockets for years,'' said Steve Sibilsky, a Transit District
spokesman. ``The personnel who are going to be getting uniforms are
the maintenance people who handle the vaults.''
</TEXT>
