<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDSReports     12-20 0732</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Reports,2nd Ld-Writethru, a0539,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS On Track To Become Fifth-Leading Killer Among Youth</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS pvs 7th, 8th, 10th grafs to correct numbers mentioned
with corresponding lists of major causes of death among various age
groups</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AIDS in a few years is likely to become the
fifth leading killer of Americans from birth to age 24 if present
trends continue, say federal health officials.
   Meanwhile, a General Accounting Office report says President
Reagan's Domestic Policy Council got in the way of Public Health
Service officials' attempts at launching an anti-AIDS education
program in the spring of 1987.
   The report is also critical of television networks for declining
to run many anti-AIDS public service spots when they did become
available, particularly those dealing with condoms as a way to
prevent spread of the deadly virus.
   The report, issued last week, said further that ther were
problems with getting a national AIDS hotline operating at full
speed, although it said those lapses had been mostly corrected by
last summer.
   Meanwhile, Dr. Antonia Novello, deputy director of the National
Institute of Child Health and Human Development, told Health and
Human Services Secretary Otis R. Bowen on Monday that AIDS is
already the ninth leading cause of death among children 1 to 4 years
old and the seventh leading cause of deaths among young people age
15 to 24.
   If present trends continue, she said, the disease soon will move
up to No. 5.
   The five leading causes of death among people age 15 to 24 in
1985, the last year for which figures are available, were accidents,
suicide, homicide, cancer and heart disease.
   For people age 5 to 14, the top five in 1985 were accidents,
cancer, birth defects, homicide and heart disease.
   For children from 1 to 4, the top four were accidents, birth
defects, cancer, and heart disease.
   For infants under 1, the leading causes were complications at
birth, birth defects, ``ill-defined conditions,'' accidents and
pneumonia and flu.
   As of Dec. 12, 1,291 cases of AIDS had been reported among
infants and children under age 13 and an additional 325 cases in the
13-to-19-year group. Of those, 717 who were under 13 at the time of
their diagnosis have already died, along with 174 who were
adolescents when diagnosed.
   ``The official figures include only those children whose
condition was reported to the Centers for Disease Control,'' said a
report from a task force headed by Novello. ``Probably for every
child who meets the CDC definition of AIDS, another two to 10 are
infected with HIV. It is estimated that by 1991 there will be at
least 10,000 to 20,000 HIV-infected children in the United States.''
   HIV is the virus that causes AIDS, and health officials are
growing increasingly concerned that a large majority of those
infected eventually will develop AIDS and die.
   The GAO report, requested by Rep. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., said
that even though the Centers For Disease Control's AIDS education
budget increased from about $17 million in fiscal 1985 to nearly
$210 million in 1988, ``its efforts to focus national attention on
AIDS prevention were impaired by the slow implementation of key
activities aimed at the general public.''
   GAO said CDC decided in May 1987 to designate the following
October as ``AIDS Awareness and Prevention Month,'' but was unable
to get clearance from the White House Domestic Policy Council _ a
Cabinet group _ for its plans to conduct a national AIDS information
mailing to all households.
   Congress had made clear it thought such a mailing should be done,
but had not explicitly required it. Congress made a mailing
mandatory the following year and the pamphlet ``Understanding AIDS''
went out to more than 100 million households last June.
   In conjunction with ``AIDS Awareness and Prevention Month'' in
1987, CDC contracted for production of 38 public service
announcements on AIDS and distributed them to the major television
networks on Sept. 30, 1987, the report said.
   However, it said there was only one airing by a network during
the following month and only six the following months.
   When ads did air, they were not likely to be seen by many people.
Between December 1987 and February 1988, GAO reported, nearly 90
percent of all network-aired AIDS public service announcements were
shown during non-primetime viewing hours. Nearly 60 percent were
shown between 11 p.m. and 7 a.m., GAO said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881220-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 1452EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-GNP     12-20 0767</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GNP,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GNP Rises Moderately, But Fed Still Expected To Hike Interest Rates</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The economy expanded at a moderate 2.5 percent
pace during the July-September quarter, the government reported
Tuesday, but analysts said growth was rebounding and the Federal
Reserve Board probably will nudge interest rates higher as a result.
   The Commerce Department said growth of the gross national
product, the broadest measure of economic health, slowed during the
third quarter from 3.0 percent in the 2nd quarter and 3.4 percent in
the first three months of the year.
   The GNP, after adjusting for inflation, rose $24.2 billion to an
annual rate of $4.01 trillion in the third quarter.
   The GNP figure for the third quarter, the slowest expansion pace
since the final quarter of 1986, was a slight downward revision from
a preliminary estimate of 2.6 percent issued a month ago. Most
economists had been looking for a slight upward adjustment.
   The trend should be good news for Federal Reserve policy makers
who want to curb economic growth to a range of 2 percent to 2.5
percent, which they believe is sustainable without increasing
inflation.
   However, the government said the temporary effects of the summer
drought, which shriveled crops and seared pastures, are masking the
true strength of the economy in the final nine months of the year.
   Drought losses of $12.3 billion reduced the GNP growth rate by
0.9 percentage points in the second quarter, 0.5 percentage points
in the third and will knock more than 1.0 percent off of fourth
quarter rate.
   The growth rate in the final three months of this year, excluding
the effects of the drought, will top 3 percent, most economists
believe. In the first half of next year, assuming a return to normal
farm production, the economy will be expanding at a rate between 3
percent and 4 percent, they say.
   ``What you're left with is an economy that is growing too fast to
be acceptable to the Federal Reserve,'' said Robert G. Dederick, an
economist with Northern Trust Co. in Chicago.
   Fed members fear that a GNP growth rate higher than the target
range will strain factory capacity, leading to shortages and
resulting price increases. Also, by boosting employment, the growth
encourages employers to bid up wages. The Fed's ``cure'' is higher
interest rates designed to make it more expensive for consumers and
businesses to spend.
   The Fed began nudging interest rates higher in late March,
capping a series of tightening moves in August with a rise in the
discount rate, the interest it charges on loans to member banks.
   When economic statistics for October and November made it clear
that growth remained robust, the Fed responded last week by bumping
up the federal funds rate, the rate banks charge each other for
overnight loans, by a quarter of a percentage point to a range of 8|
percent to 8~ percent.
   David Jones, an economist with Aubrey G. Lanston & Co., a
government securities dealer in New York, said the next tightening
move likely will come in the first two weeks of next month, with
another quarter point rise in the federal funds rate.
   ``I think the Fed will have to lean somewhat against those
(strong growth) winds with a series of modest tightening steps,''
but it will delay raising the discount rate. ``If anything, the Fed
is in danger of underreacting.''
   However, other economists, noting that consumer prices are rising
at a 4.4 percent annual rate in 1988, the same as last year, say
inflation fears are overstated.
   ``What we're afraid of is the Federal Reserve will get carried
away next year and raise interest rates too high and keep them too
high too long,'' said David Wyss, an economist with Data Resources
Inc., a forecasting firm in Lexington, Mass. ``We might end up with
a recession in late 1989 or early 1990.''
   But Dederick and Jones noted that a GNP price index, which
measures price increases in what Americans are producing as opposed
to what they are buying, shot up at an annual rate of 5.3 percent in
the third quarter, the biggest jump in six years. That was up from a
5.0 percent rate in the second quarter.
   In an accompanying report, the Commerce Department said corporate
profits after taxes advanced 3.9 percent in the third quarter after
soaring 8.9 percent in the second quarter. An earlier estimate,
which did not take into account profits by overseas subsidiaries of
U.S. corporations, had said third quarter profits rose only a slight
0.2 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
