<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SriLanka 1stLd-Writethru a0595 12-20 0792</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0595,0812</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premadasa Declared Winner, Appeals For End to Violence</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to CORRECT typo in Sri Lanka.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto COL4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Ranasinghe Premadasa was
declared winner Tuesday of Sri Lanka's presidential election, and he
appealed for an end to the killing that has crippled this tropical
island nation.
   ``The ballots of the people have triumphed over the bullets of
brutality,'' Premadasa said.
   ``The politics of terror has no place in the temple of
democracy,'' he said. ``I will eradicate fear and suppression. I
will restore law and order.''
   Premadasa's victory with slightly more than half of the votes
ended a campaign marked by hundreds of slayings, which the
government blames on the People's Liberation Front, a Sinhalese
extremist group that opposed the balloting.
   Police said members of the group hacked and shot to death nine
supporters of Premadasa's party Tuesday in Bandarawela, 76 miles
east of Colombo.
   A 9 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew was imposed on the nation of 16 million
to prevent violence after the results were announced.
   ``I have an appeal to make to those who have still to join the
democratic process,'' Premadasa said in a nationally televised
address. ``Your participation will enable us to eradicate fear and
poverty with greater speed.''
   He also stretched a conciliatory hand to the two losing
candidates, although an adviser to the runner-up, former Prime
Minister Sirimavo Bandaranaike, said she was not accepting the final
results.
   The intimidation campaign by the Sinhalese extremists kept many
people from the polls Monday. Only 55 percent of 9.3 million
eligible voters turned out to vote compared with 80 percent in the
last presidential election six years ago.
   Premadasa received 50.4 percent of the vote, followed by Mrs.
Bandaranaike of the opposition Sri Lanka Freedom Party with 44.9
percent, according to election Commissioner Chandrananda de Silva.
   He said no balloting took place in parts of eastern Moneragala
district because no polling officers had arrived, but he added that
the three candidates agreed not to make an issue out of it.
   Mrs. Bandaranaike had no immediate comment. But Kumar
Ponnambalam, a spokesman for the five-party Democratic Peoples'
Alliance that backed her, said the candidate sent a letter to the
Elections Commissioner ``requesting him not to announce results
since she is not accepting the final count.''
   When Premadasa takes over Sri Lanka's most powerful government
post Jan. 2, he will be working with a new Parliament, which was
dissolved Tuesday by outgoing President Junius R. Jayewardene.
   Jayewardene has ruled for 11 years and was barred by the
constitution from seeking a third term. Parliamentary elections are
scheduled for Feb. 15.
   The president serves for six years and appoints the prime
minister and other ministers.
   In Washington, the State Department said ``we look forward to
working closely with President-elect Premadasa to strengthen further
the warm relationship we have enjoyed with Sri Lanka under President
Jayewardene.''
   ``The people and the leadership of Sri Lanka have displayed
laudable courage and determination in holding presidential elections
in defiance of terrorist threats,'' the department said in a brief
statement.
   The current cycle of violence in Sri Lanka, an island once famed
as an idyllic tourist resort, dates from 1983, when the Tamil ethnic
minority began its uprising against the majority Sinalhese. Nearly
10,000 people have been killed since then.
   With the help of neighboring India, the subcontinent's superpower
and home to 60 million Tamils, Jayewardene signed a peace accord in
July 1987 aimed at ending the Tamil insurgency.
   Premadasa opposed the plan despite being a top government
official and boycotted the signing ceremony.
   The pact guaranteed some autonomy to the Tamils, who comprise 18
percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people, and invited India to help
end the uprising by sending troops, which now total 47,000.
   The People's Liberation Front vehemently opposes the pact, saying
the government should not compromise with the Tamils.
   The Tamil Tiger rebels seeking an independent state also oppose
the accord, and are fighting Indian soldiers in the northeast.
   Premadasa has called for the phased or immediate withdrawal of
Indian troops, but dealing with the huge neighbor could prove
difficult.
   Indian High Commissioner J.N. Dixit has indicated his country
won't accept unilateral action.
   ``The peace pact was a bilateral one and the unilateral
abrogation by one side will create an unprecedented situation,'' he
said recently. ``As far as India is concerned, we are firmly
committed to the accord.''
   Premadasa also stressed his determination to fight poverty in Sri
Lanka, where the annual per capital income is $360. He has proposed
giving $75 a month to the poorest families, but has not explained
how to pay for the program.
</TEXT>
