<1ST_LINE>u w PM-AlaskaCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0586 12-20 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Alaska Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0586,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Safety Board Blames Alaska Crash on Poorly Loaded Cargo</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS penultimate graf, The crash, to clarify</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Transportation Safety Board today
blamed improperly loaded cargo for the crash of a commuter plane in
Alaska last year that killed 18 people.
   The board said the Ryan Air Service flight crew failed to
properly oversee the loading of the craft and that so much of the
cargo was loaded in the rear that the pilot lost control of the
plane.
   ``The real responsibility rested with the crew, which is
responsible for supervising the loading of the aircraft,'' said
James L. Kolstad, acting chairman of the NTSB. ``For reasons I guess
we'll never know, they failed in that function.''
   The twin-engine turboprop crashed on approach to Homer Airport in
Homer, Alaska, on Nov. 23, 1987. Eighteen of the 21 people on board
were killed.
   Investigators had believed that ice on the aircraft might have
contributed to the accident, but the board said the ice ``did not
cause but may have exacerbated the loss of control.''
   The crash was Ryan Air's 10th in eight years, and the company had
been fined 10 months before the crash for record-keeping violations.
While the board did not explicitly clear Ryan Air for any blame in
the accident, it adopted no conclusions that the commuter airline
was at fault.
   The staff report was adopted on a 4-1 vote, with board member Jim
Burnett voting no because he first wanted to see changes in wording
that were agreed to in the board's meeting.
</TEXT>
