<1ST_LINE>r w AM-EarthquakeDonations     12-20 0151</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earthquake Donations,140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Urges Americans to Send Money, Not Goods, for Quake Relief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citing a lack of storage facilities and other
problems, the State Department is urging Americans to send money
instead of relief supplies to earthquake victims in Soviet Armenia.
   ``The relief lines are clogged up,'' said Rene Bafalis, a
spokeswoman for the Office of Foreign Disaster Assistance who
returned Sunday from the scene of the earthquake.
   In addition to inadequate storage space, she said sorting out the
clothing, blankets and other items being donated from abroad
presents problems for local authorities because of the large
quantities involved.
   She said Soviet authorities turned back at least one flight
carrying relief supplies because of the backlog.
   ``The system is really overwhelmed,'' she said.
   Ms. Bafalis recommended that Americans make cash donations
through either the American Red Cross or to local Armenian
organizations involved in earthquake relief.
</TEXT>
