<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 1505EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DesperatePriest     12-20 0702</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Desperate Priest,0725</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jobs Center Director Has Questionable Past</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tale of a priest who was forced to sell two
prized lithographs to pay overdue bills at his jobs center generated
sympathy and money, but questions have arisen about the man's past.
   One potential donor said he canceled plans to raise at least
$10,000 for the Rev. John DaeCheck's New Times Service Center in
Glassport.
   And the bank handling contributions, Union National Bank in
Glassport, decided to close the account Tuesday because of
skepticism about DaeCheck, said manager Jack Katona. DaeCheck opened
the account Monday with $500.
   DaeCheck acknowledged he has had some brushes with authorities,
including an investigation by the U.S. Postal Service regarding a
publishing company he owned that filed for bankruptcy.
   But Glassport Police Chief Edward Mihoces defends DaeCheck.
   ``What he has done outside isn't important,'' the chief said.
``He does help people.''
   Some of the center's clients, workers displaced by the decline of
the Monongahela Valley's steel industry, said last week that
DaeCheck had helped them obtain retraining and submit resumes.
   DaeCheck said he founded the non-profit jobs center seven months
ago in part to make up for past mistakes and has only the center's
welfare at heart.
   ``We've been here for seven months doing good work. Hopefully
I'll be here another seven months doing good work or until it's
needed,'' he said.
   To get money for the center's phone bill, DaeCheck last week sold
two 19th-century French lithographs, one a Daumier, for $500 to a
Pittsburgh businessman, who also donated an additional $800 to the
center.
   Bell of Pennsylvania agreed to continue phone service because of
assurances the bill of more than $300 would be paid.
   DaeCheck's advertisements offering the bargain-priced lithos
attracted attention, and he told The Associated Press last week that
he was pastor of an independent Russian Orthodox Church called St.
Paul's in Washington, Pa. He said the jobs center was a mission of
the church.
   But after questions arose, DaeCheck said he does not have a
congregation or conduct services. He explained Monday that St.
Paul's Church is actually St. Paul's Mission, part of All-Faith
Church Mission Inc. in Washington, founded by the Revs. Harry and
Helen Harrington.
   The Harringtons said they ordained DaeCheck and hundreds of
people based on the applicant's knowledge of the Bible and belief in
God.
   DaeCheck said he briefly attended but did not graduate from
Savanarolo Theological Seminary in Scranton, operated by the Polish
National Catholic Church, a branch of the Old Catholic Church of
Holland.
   DaeCheck also said he was ordained in Washington, D.C., in 1981
by Bishop James Miller of the Orthodox Church of America. That
church, he said, was based in Anderson, S.C., and is distinct from
the bettern-known Orthodox Church in America.
   But the rector of the Savanarolo seminary, the Very Rev. Edward
Brzostowski, said Monday he had no records of DaeCheck's attendance.
Brzostowski and Bishop Kyrill of the western Pennsylvania diocese of
the Orthodox Church in America said they never heard of Orthodox
Church of America. Directory assistance in Anderson, S.C., also had
no listing for the church or Miller.
   ``If Bishop Miller isn't around ... there's not much I can do for
you,'' DaeCheck said. ``My orders come from the Orthodox Church of
America.''
   DaeCheck started the publishing company in 1974. He said he went
out of business in 1982 after publishing about 150 books on a
cooperative basis with the authors.
   ``A lot of people are probably very bitter that I went
bankrupt,'' he said. ``I went through a terrible time.''
   Caren Mariani, deputy state attorney general in charge of the
Bureau of Consumer Protection in Pittsburgh, said DaeCheck failed to
publish manuscripts, make refunds on time or register the business
with the state. In June 1985, DaeCheck agreed to reimburse seven
authors a total of $5,354.
   The postal service investigated DaeCheck but never charged him
with any crime, said Postal Inspector Bruce Stutzman.
   DaeCheck's background was enough to make Neal Holmes, owner of
Allied Security of Pittsburgh, cancel plans to organize business
people interested in giving $10,000 to the center.
   ``I think I'm going to back off,'' Holmes said Monday.
</TEXT>
