<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     12-20 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christmas should be a hopping good time for
Quasimodo, who'll make the leap from pet store prodigy to house pet
for some lucky youngster.
   The rare red-eyed, albino bullfrog has lived at Don Sutton's shop
for 18 months, greeting customers and entertaining hundreds of
children. But this Christmas, Quasimodo is being adopted for the
princely price of $59.97.
   At first, viewers may mistake Quasimodo for a plastic toy,
because of his out-of-the-ordinary yellow color and his practice of
sitting motionless for long periods. But underneath, he's all frog.
   Quasimodo's unusual color is due to a lack of sufficient
pigmentation to make him the run-of-the-mill-pond brownish green. He
was a highly unusual find for Sutton, who bought Quasimodo from a
wholesale dealer.
   ``It was unusual that he was found before he was eaten,'' he
said. ``Most albino frogs stand out so much they are gobbled up by
other predators. Somehow he survived long enough to get captured.''
   The nearly 2-year-old frog is still growing, and in the security
of his new family, he can be expected to live eight to 10 years,
Sutton said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iron is discoloring the water in Waterford
Township, and hairdressers say they're not the only ones who know
for sure.
   Residents of the Oakland County community who shampoo with the
rusty public water supply complain that it's turning their hair
yellow, orange and even green, an undesireable shade even in this
holiday season.
   ``What (the iron) is doing is depositing on blond hair or any
type of hair and it builds up,'' said beauty salon owner Cyndi
Edwards. ``I've had cases where the hair turns green.''
   Some of the township's public wells contain iron levels six times
higher than Michigan guidelines, state and county officials said.
The iron doesn't pose any known health threats, but it makes the
water taste bitter, smell bad, stain laundry and clog pipes.
   The township could end the problem by tying into Detroit's water
network, according to a report issued last week by the Waterford
Water Quality Committee.
</TEXT>
