<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SpaceFailures     12-20 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Failures,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Exhibit Highlights Failures Of Space Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUTCHINSON, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The failures of the U.S. space program
over the past 30 years are highlighted in an unusual exhibit.
   The exhibit at the Kansas Cosmosphere and Space Center features
the remains of the Mercury-Atlas I, the ill-fated, unmanned rocket
that exploded less than one minute after liftoff on July 29, 1960.
   The remains were retrieved from the floor of the Atlantic Ocean
more than 20 years ago and previously were housed in a museum in
Orlando, Fla.
   The exhibit, which opened Monday, also includes a backup unit for
Project Vanguard, the U.S. response to the Soviet Sputnik. Vanguard,
launched Dec. 6, 1957, rose six inches and collapsed.
   But the display is not only about failures. ``This shows the
difficulties we faced in getting man, and rockets, into space,''
said Max Ary, executive director of the space museum.
   There is a wall-sized mural of President John F. Kennedy. An old
RCA television sitting in a recreation of a 30-year-old livingroom
plays Kennedy's speech to Congress in which he proposed the Apollo
moon-landing program.
   ``I believe that this nation should commit itself to achieving
the goal before the decade is out of landing a man on the moon and
returning him safely to Earth,'' Kennedy said.
   A brief video called ``39 Percent Success Rate'' provides a light
look at some of the 80 U.S. unmanned satellite launches, 49 of which
ended in failure.
   A block house blast window _ a 250-pound chunk of glass that
shielded the launch crew at Cape Canaveral _ sits in the middle of
the exhibit.
</TEXT>
