<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PirateShip 1stLd-Writethru a0609 12-20 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pirate Ship, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0609,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radio Station Owners Won't Give up the Ship</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 4th, `McNaught rejected...' to include
that ship not presently broadcasting.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pirate rock 'n' roll ship operating off the coast
of New York can't continue broadcasting without a license from the
Federal Communications Commission, a judge has ruled.
   U.S. District Judge John J. McNaught issued a summary judgment
Dec. 13 against Al Weiner, former owner of the Sarah and one of four
defendants, who contended the radio ship had a constitutional right
to broadcast without an FCC license on ``open and unused
frequencies.''
   Weiner's attorney, Jeremiah Gutman, an American Civil Liberties
Union lawyer, had argued that the Sarah was a foreign-registered
ship in international waters and didn't come under the scope of the
FCC. He also maintained that since the station, Radio New York
International, was broadcasting on an unassigned AM frequency, the
FCC was violating First Amendment rights to free speech.
   McNaught rejected those arguments, noting that the government
said numerous stations could be subject to interference if the Sarah
broadcast.
   Weiner has said he launched the pirate station to protest what he
called conformity in New York-area radio programming.
   The Sarah has broadcast only twice. In July 1987, it broadcast of
Long Island, N.Y., for about four days and then agents of the FCC
and the U.S. Coast Guard boarded the ship and stopped broadcasts.
The Sarah was towed to Boston after Weiner promised a federal court
in Brooklyn he would cease operations.
   ``Everybody in the project is absolutely frustrated,'' Weiner
said Tuesday. ``We could go on the air and not harm or create one
single problem. It's just that we've got a hysterical FCC.''
   Weiner maintained that the Sarah is an international ship because
it is registered in Sealand, a self-proclaimed principality in the
North Sea off the coast of the United Kingdom. Prosecutors argued
that Britain does not recognize Sealand and recently extended its
territorial limit to include the unofficial country.
   The judge said the defendants ``could not look to the First
Amendment for authority to broadcast on an unoccupied frequency in
violation of both federal and international law. The First Amendment
does not grant anyone the right to broadcast by radio.''
</TEXT>
