<1ST_LINE>r i AM-WorldCourt     12-20 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World Court,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Wins Jurisdiction Ruling In Dispute With Honduras</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Court on Tuesday ruled it
has the authority to deal with a Nicaraguan complaint that
neighboring Honduras is supporting rebels fighting Managua's
Sandinista government.
   The ruling was the latest step in a dispute between the two
Central American nations that has been before the court since 1986.
A final decision is not expected before 1990.
   Nicaragua has said Honduras is actively supporting the Contra
insurgents and is seeking a court-ordered halt to the alleged
assistance.
   Honduras, however, has been contending the World Court has no
jurisdiction in the case. It says it limited its acceptance of World
Court jurisdiction one month before Nicaragua filed the complaint in
July 1986.
   The Sandinista complaint came one month after Nicaragua won a
World Court condemnation of Reagan administration support for the
Contras.
   Tuesday's ruling means the court, formally known as the
International Court of Justice, can examine the merits of the
Nicaragua-Honduran dispute.
   The 15-judge forum is the judicial arm of the United Nations. It
has no enforcement powers and depends on voluntary adherence to its
rulings.
</TEXT>
