<DOCNO> AP881220-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 1614EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-IsraelLobby     12-20 0823</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel Lobby,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.-PLO Link Hits American Israeli Lobby at Bad Time</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Israel Public Affairs Committee
has been shaken by internal turmoil in recent months, raising
concerns about the powerful pro-Israeli lobby's relations with
Congress and its ability to protect the Jewish state from the
fallout of strained relations with the administration.
   The latest setback to befall AIPAC is last week's resignation of
its legislative director, Douglas Bloomfield, the organization's
respected and popular liaison with Congress. It follows several
unfavorable news reports about the generally low-profile group,
based partly on documents supplied by disgruntled AIPAC employees.
   Included among the allegations were that AIPAC violated its
mandate by supporting candidates in the recent congressional
elections and that it mapped out a campaign to smear the Rev. Jesse
Jackson.
   Observers and insiders differ on whether AIPAC's problems are a
result of personality clashes or a reflection of fundamental policy
differences within the organization, which is viewed as possessing
almost mythical clout in this power-conscious city.
   But all agree it could not have come at a worse time for Israel
and the American Jewish community.
   The paternalistic alliance between Washington and Jerusalem is
being strained by last week's U.S. decision to launch talks with the
Palestine Liberation Organization. The decision, taken after PLO
Chairman Yasser Arafat declared he recognized Israel's right to
exist, is viewed by Israel's leadership as betraying a promise given
13 years ago not to deal with its arch-enemy.
   U.S.-Israel ties will be put to a further test in the months
ahead by requests from Saudi Arabia for millions of dollars worth of
arms sales. There are indications the administration of
President-elect Bush may be more inclined to acquiesce to those
requests, which were turned down under congressional pressure in
recent years.
   Jewish leaders also are concerned that Bush and his chief of
staff, John Sununu, who is of Arab ancestry, may be less committed
to Israel's security than the Reagan administration, and especially
in comparison with outgoing Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
   ``It's now more important than ever that Congress remain
committed to Israel,'' said Rep. Howard L. Berman, D-Calif., who
works closely with AIPAC and strongly supports the $3 billion annual
U.S. foreign aid to Israel.
   Berman and others in Congress who work closely with AIPAC say
they perceive a shift from the organization's emphasis on lobbying
the legislative branch to lobbying the executive branch. Others
charge AIPAC's leadership, especially Chairman Robert Asher and
President Edward Levy, with a pro-Republican bias that damns them in
the eyes of the Democratic majority on Capitol Hill.
   ``The partisanship that is perceived as creeping into AIPAC's
decision-making will hurt them in the long run,'' said Democratic
Rep. Lawrence Smith of Florida, who has been instrumental in
opposing arms sales to the Arabs.
   ``They have to understand that the real bedrock of support for
Israel is the Congress. Administrations come and go. We're pretty
constant and reliable,'' Smith said.
   The perception of AIPAC's partisan leanings appears due in part
to an eight-year Republican administration which has been warmly
supportive of Israel. For example, Jewish leaders say they were
reluctant to criticize Shultz's decision to reverse the ban on talks
with the PLO because of his traditionally staunch support for Israel.
   The perception is further highlighted because it contrasts
sharply with American Jews' traditional support for the Democratic
Party. Jews voted 2-to-1 in favor of Michael Dukakis over Bush in
the November elections.
   Especially disturbing to AIPAC supporters in Congress was its
reaction to the administration's request last summer for 40 F-18 jet
fighters worth $1.8 billion for Kuwait. AIPAC, following Israel's
lead, contended that the sale to the moderate Arab nation did not
threaten Israeli security.
   Smith, who led the fight against the sale and counted on AIPAC's
backing, was angry. ``They lost sight of the fact that in the long
run this will be harmful to Israel and America,'' he said. ``There's
a legitimate debate about whether we're selling weapons to the Arabs
as a bribe or whether we have a coherent policy toward them.''
   Morris Amitay, a Washington lawyer who was AIPAC's executive
director from 1974 to 1980, cautioned the lobby's leadership about
bypassing Congress and trying to influence the administration
directly. ``It's not very sophisticated of them,'' he said. ``Anyone
who knows how this city works knows it's wrong.''
   AIPAC leaders declined to be interviewed, saying the
organization's low profile is essential for its behind-the-scenes
effectiveness.
   But privately officials said the organization wasn't moving away
from Congress, noting that it is adding one congressional lobbyist
to its list of five.
   They also denied any Republican leanings, noting that some of
their senior board members are known Democrats.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Ruth Sinai covered the Middle East for The
Associated Press for four years and now reports on foreign policy
for the AP in Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
