<DOCNO> AP881220-0132 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 1659EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AshleyProfile     12-20 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ashley Profile,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Ohio Congressman Named to Deficit Commission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Rep. Thomas L. Ashley, selected by
George Bush on Tuesday for the high-level commission studying the
deficit problem, is a Democrat who has been friends with the
president-elect since they were classmates at Yale long ago.
   Ashley, 65, was a Democratic congressman from Toledo for 26 years
before his defeat in Ronald Reagan's 1980 landslide.
   Ashley, whose nickname is ``Lud'' from his middle name of Ludlow,
is now president of the Association of Bank Holding Companies, a
lobbying group which represents the country's largest banks.
   He is considered one of Bush's oldest and closest friends. At
Yale, they were members of the secret society, Skull and Bones.
Asked once to describe his friend, Ashley said, ``He has spent a
lifetime thinking in conventional terms, never reaching beyond them,
never even wanting to.''
   In announcing Ashley's appointment to the National Economic
Commission on Tuesday, Bush said he expected to benefit from
Ashley's ``counsel and his candor'' on the commission.
   ``I have had the privilege of knowing Lud Ashley for over 40
years,'' Bush said in a statement. ``He understands the full range
of national issues _ from housing, to energy, to the problems of our
cities.''
   Bush's decision to put his long-time friend on the panel gave
supporters of the commssion hope that Bush may take its
recommendations more seriously. During the campaign, Bush derided
the commission as a stalking horse for tax increases.
   Ashley, considered a liberal Democrat while in Congress, served
as ranking member of the House Banking Committee and was also
considered an expert on energy problems.
   Like Bush, Ashley fought in the Pacific during World War II and
then entered Yale to resume his education. He received his
undergraduate degree in 1948 and then earned a law degree by
attending night classes at the University of Toledo law school.
   He practiced law with his father and brother in Toledo before
joining the staff of Radio Free Europe in 1952, where he served as
assistant director for special projects for two years.
   He was elected to Congress in 1954, serving in the House where
his great-grandfather, James M. Ashley, had served during the Civil
War. The great-grandfather had also been governor of Montana when
the area was a territory.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
