<DOCNO> AP881220-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 1707EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Cambodia     12-20 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Cambodia,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Says It Will Stop Aid To Insurgents If Vietnam Withdraws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China on Tuesday announced it would stop aiding
the Khmer Rouge and other Cambodian resistance forces as soon as
Vietnam withdraws its troops from Cambodia.
   The statement, which appeared in the People's Daily, was a
further indication that Beijing's policy toward Vietnam's occupation
of Cambodia has softened.
   China's premier, Li Peng, made the statement at a news conference
Monday with journalists from China and India covering Prime Minister
Rajiv Gandhi's visit.
   According to the report, Li said ``if Vietnam withdraws from
Cambodia, all parties, including China, should stop aiding elements
in Cambodia.''
   In addition, Li said, ``in order to calm the fears of the
international community, as Vietnam withdraws, we will decrease our
military assistance to the resistance forces.''
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978 and unseated the Khmer
Rouge, who had ruled the country from 1975. More than a million
people are believed to have died during their bloody reign.
   China, the capitalist countries of Southeast Asia and the West
support a three-party resitance coalition comprised of forces loyal
to Prince Norodom Sihanouk, the Khmer Rouge and Son Sann, a
Western-leanding politician.
   Vietnam has said it will leave Cambodia by 1990 and will turn the
war over to the government of Heng Samrin, which it installed in
Phnom Penh in 1979.
   But the Cambodian forces are weak and there are widespread fears
the Khmer Rouge will return to power after Hanoi pulls out its
forces.
   On Monday, Vietnam announced another troop withdrawal. The troops
were among the 50,000 Vietnam says are being sent home this year in
its seventh annual partial pullout. Vietnam says the current
withdrawal will leave 50,000 troops in Cambodia.
   China's position on Vietnam's occupation of Cambodia has been
evolving over the last few months as its relationship with Vietnam's
main backer, the Soviet Union, improves.
   Initially, China demanded Vietnam withdraw completely from
Cambodia before China would even consider ceasing military aid. It
also had expressed close support of the Khmer Rouge.
   Over the summer, China moved noticeably away from the Khmer Rouge
and began backing a Cambodian government headed by Sihanouk.
   In November, Li said once the Vietnamese produced a timetable for
the withdrawal, ``then the military assistance to all the four
parties in Cambodia must and also can be graduwlly reduced and even
totally stopped.''
   Tuesday's announcement marked a further revising of the Chinese
position because it dropped the demand for a timetable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
