<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 1708EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Vietnam     12-20 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Vietnam,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Skeptical on Vietnam's Withdrawal Pledge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department expressed skepticism
Tuesday that Vietnam will fulfill its pledge to withdraw 50,000
troops from Cambodia before the end of the year.
   Vietnam contends that its commitment is being met with the
withdrawal of 18,000 troops this week.
   But State Department officials insisted that even if the
Vietnamese estimate of the size of the ongoing pullback is accurate,
it would only bring the total for the year to between 28,000 and
33,000 troops.
   While welcoming this week's troop withdrawal, State Department
deputy spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said, ``We remain skeptical that
the 50,000 pledge will be met.'' She estimated the current
Vietnamese troop commitment to Cambodia at between 90,000 and
100,000, down from about 120,000 at the start of the year.
   ``Since we believe Vietnam's illegal occupation is the root cause
of the conflict, we continue to urge Hanoi to issue a precise
timetable for the withdrawal of its remaining troops from Cambodia
during 1989 and to allow for the verification of their withdrawal,''
she said.
   Vietnam has indicated all its troops in Cambodia will be
withdrawn by 1990.
   Mrs. Oakley said once all Vietnamese forces are withdrawn and
there is an acceptable political settlement in Cambodia, the United
States would be prepared to normalize relations with Hanoi.
   Some previous administration statements had conditioned the
establishment of normal ties with Vietnam on Hanoi's cooperation in
accounting for the estimated 1,700 American servicemen listed as
missing from the Vietnam War, but there was no such link included in
Mrs. Oakley's statement Tuesday.
   A State Department official said Tuesday the MIA issue was being
dealt with separately, and he cited statements by President Reagan
and other senior officials suggesting there was no explicit link
between the MIA issue and normal relations with Vietnam.
   But last July, Secretary of State George P. Shultz linked
diplomatic ties with Hanoi both to a Cambodian settlement and to ``a
resolution of the POW-MIA issue which, if left unsettled, will
continue to divide our peoples.''
   Asked whether the POW-MIA condition had been dropped, Mrs. Oakley
said, ``We have been stressing that it is the complete withdrawal of
all Vietnamese forces in the context of an acceptable settlement in
Cambodia which will be the determining factor.''
   Cambodia's political future following the Vietnamese withdrawal
is highly uncertain. The pro-Hanoi government in Phnom Penh has been
fighting against three rebel groups, two of which are backed by the
United States. The third is the Khmer Rouge, which is widely accused
of having engaged in mass genocide when it ruled Cambodia between
1975 and 1978.
   An alternate approach to U.S. relations with Vietnam was outlined
in a report released Tuesday by the Aspen Institute, a private
research group.
   The report recommended the United States take ``graduated''
diplomatic steps toward Vietnam if its troops are withdrawn from
Cambodia prior to a Cambodia settlement.
   These steps should include the establishment of small diplomatic
missions in each other's capital and adjustments in the U.S. trade
embargo against Vietnam, the report said.
   Vietnam is one of a handful of countries with which the United
States does not maintain diplomatic relations.
</TEXT>
