<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Ouster     12-20 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Ouster,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Fires Lone Non-White Member of Cabinet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha on Tuesday
fired the lone non-white member of his Cabinet following completion
of an inquiry into corruption in the Indian chamber of Parliament.
   Amichand Rajbansi was ousted by Botha from his seat on the
Cabinet, where he served without a portfolio, and also from his post
as leader of the House of Delegates.
   The only other non-white ever to serve on the Cabinet, the Rev.
Allan Hendrickse, was forced to resign last year after a dispute
with Botha over the future of residential segregation laws.
Hendrickse is leader of the mixed-race house of Parliament, which is
dominated by the white chamber and excludes the country's black
majority.
   Rajbansi's ouster came a week after Botha received the official
report on a two-month inquiry into alleged irregularities and
corruption in the House of Delegates. Rajbansi had been suspended
from the Cabinet pending the outcome of the hearings, which were
conducted in Durban by a former Supreme Court judge.
   The report has not been made public, and it is not known whether
any criminal charges might be filed as a result of the investigation.
   Botha did not specify his reasons for firing Rajbansi, saying
merely that the action was taken ``in view of the findings'' of the
inquiry commission.
   Among the allegations made during the inquiry were that contracts
for providing school textbooks went to booksellers who donated money
to Rajbansi's party, that Rajbansi was involved in improper
allocations of business permits, and that he improperly interfered
in civil service appointments.
   Rajbansi, 46, became a fulltime politician in 1980. He worked
previously as a sports administrator, soccer referee, teacher, and
spokesman for the dairy industry.
   He was elected to Parliament in 1984 from a district near Durban
after adoption of a new constitution which created the Indian and
mixed-race parliamentary chambers. Anti-apartheid activists of all
races opposed the constitution because it excluded blacks, and there
was a widespread boycott of the elections.
</TEXT>
