<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea-Protests     12-20 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Protests,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>120 People Storm National Assembly Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 120 people stormed the parliament
building Tuesday during a hearing on a 1980 civil uprising that was
put down by the military, and they demanded the truth be told about
the bloody incident.
   The protesters, identifying themselves as relatives of victims of
the uprising, clashed with scores of guards in the National Assembly
building as they tried to enter the hearing room.
   The uprising in the southern city of Kwangju was the worst in
modern South Korean history. By official count, about 200 people
were killed and more than 800 others injured or wounded when the
army moved in.
   The opposition charges the incident was set up as part of a plot
by army generals to seize power in the chaotic days that followed
the assassination of the late president Park Chung-hee in late 1979.
   ``Reveal the truth of Kwangju,'' the protesters shouted today as
they moved up and down a corridor of the assembly building, breaking
two porcelain decorations. Opposition lawmakers persuaded the
protesters into a room, where they staged a sit-down for four hours.
   After the sit-down, the protesters drove in three buses to the
presidential mansion, but were stopped 700 yards away. Police took
them to nearby police stations.
   Chun Kye-ryang, a spokesman for the group, told police the group
was protesting what he called a lackluster effort by the assembly to
get at the facts of the Kwangju incident.
   Chun rejected a government offer of financial compensation before
all the facts of the incident are fully divulged. He demanded that
he and other protesters be allowed to testify at the hearing.
</TEXT>
