<HEAD>Police Seize Explosives Intended for Bombs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASSIUT, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police seized 286 pounds of explosives
Tuesday on a passenger bus leaving Cairo and arrested a passenger,
security sources said.
   The passenger, Mikki Mahmoud Mikki, acknowledged he owned the
explosives and wanted to used them make bombs intended for sale,
said the police sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Mikki, 23, was among 50 passengers on the bus when it stopped in
Assiut, about 235 miles south of Cairo. The bus was en route to
Isna, in the southern province of Qena.
   Police found six boxes containing TNT and 400 fuses in Mikki's
luggage, the sources said.
   Assiut, a provincial capital and university city, is a center of
violence by Moslem fundamentalists demanding implementation of the
strict Islamic religious and ethical code, known as Sharia.
   The sources said Mikki told police he planned to sell the bombs
in southern Egypt, but he did not say to whom.
