<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MortgageDelinquencies     12-20 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mortgage Delinquencies,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delinquent Mortgages Declining</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of Americans behind in their
mortgage payments fell in the July-September quarter to the lowest
levels in a year, an organization of lenders said Tuesday.
   The Mortgage Bankers Association of America said 4.73 percent of
the payments on the 10.8 million mortgages surveyed in the third
quarter were at least 30 days late.
   It was the lowest rate since the third quarter of 1987, when 4.71
percent of the mortgage payers were behind. The rate a year ago was
the lowest in eight years. In the second quarter, the delinquency
rate was 4.90 percent.
   The foreclosure rate edged down to 0.26 percent in the third
quarter, compared with 0.27 percent in the second quarter.
   Warren Lasko, executive vice president of the association, said
he was ``very heartened'' by the decline, but the report noted a
mixed pattern regionally.
   In North Central states, the delinquency rate was 4.88 percent,
down from 5.30 percent a year ago. The rate in the Northeast was
unchanged from a year ago at 4.12 percent, the lowest of four
regions.
   However, the rate in the South rose from 5.25 percent last year
to 5.29 percent. The rate in the West was 4.28 percent in the third
quarter, up from 4.10 percent a year ago.
   A high employment level in the United States generally has helped
keep delinquencies low. The South has had a relatively high rate
because Texas and other Southwestern states are struggling with a
depressed oil industry.
   Two offsetting trends will affect delinquencies next year.
Interest rates are rising, increasing the monthly payments on
adjustable-rate mortgages. However, the economy is expected to
remain strong, at least through mid-year, keeping the unemployment
rate low.
</TEXT>
