<1ST_LINE>r a AM-InstructorsDisciplined     12-20 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Instructors Disciplined,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Instructors Disciplined For Socializing With Female Students</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT BENNING, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven instructors at Fort Benning's
airborne school were fined and demoted for socializing with students
at the base in violation of the Army's fraternization policy.
   Lt. Col. Mark Lewis, battalion commander, said several female
students alleged that they had sex with instructors, but Lewis only
found evidence that instructors were dating students and of
``improper senior-subordinate relationships.''
   Airborne instructors in three of the four companies in the 1st
Battalion of the 507th Parachute Infantry Regiment have been or are
being investigated for socializing, dating or sexually harassing
female airborne students, post officials told the Columbus
Ledger-Enquirer.
   Seven were punished, appealed and had their appeals denied. All
were demoted in rank and fined the equivalent of one month's pay.
The demotions of four were suspended for six months, which means
their ranks will be restored if no further infractions are charged
against them during that time.
   The students were not punished, Lewis said, because he wanted
them to continue to give information about the instructors' conduct.
   They also were not punished, he said, because instructors are in
supervisory positions and know the fraternization policy, but
students _ even though they are given briefings on it _ are not as
familiar with the policy.
   The investigations began when a student was questioned about an
unrelated incident and told brigade officers that instructors were
dating students, a violation of the Army's fraternization policy.
   The instructors are non-commissioned officers who teach and
supervise students in a three-week airborne course. The course is
one of the few at the post with students of both sexes.
   Col. Kenneth Teel, the School Brigade commander, said the
incidents were not that significant considering 25,000 students go
through the course each year. The School Brigade oversees the
airborne school.
   ``I'm really rather surprised we don't get more (sexual
harassment) allegations than we do,'' he said. ``The investigation
found that it was not very widespread at all.''
   In an attempt to help solve the problem, Teel has hired a female
instructor and is asking for other qualified women to volunteer for
instructors' positions.
</TEXT>
