<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     12-20 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premier Ryzhkov Attacks Nationalists, Calls for Compromise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov on Tuesday asked for
compromise in the ethnic dispute between the republics of Armenia
and Azerbaijan and accused nationalists of using Armenia's
devastating earthquake to sow strife in the region.
   In a report that kept up a media attack on activists on both
sides of the ethnic dispute, the Communist Party newspaper Pravda
said officials arrested nine people on suspicion of inciting unrest
in Azerbaijan.
   Ryzhkov met with members of Armenian artists' unions in the
capital Yerevan before returning to Moscow. He had been in Armenia
almost two weeks to oversee relief efforts following the Dec. 7
earthquake that killed an estimated 55,000 people and left more than
500,000 people homeless.
   The quake came after three weeks of unrest between Armenians and
Azerbaijanis in which at least 31 people were killed and more than
180,000 fled to escape the violence.
   The official Tass news agency said Ryzhkov attacked
``adventurists who jointly with corrupt and hooligan elements hamper
the effort to overcome the aftermath of the natural disaster even
when the resources of the people are taxed to the utmost, try to sow
ethnic strife, provoke illegal actions, and in the long run,
undermine the spiritual health of the nation.''
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and other officials have expressed
frustration that the earthquake has not eased strains between the
two southern Soviet republics.
   Armenia wants to annex the predominantly Armenian region of
Nagorno-Karabakh from Azerbaijan. Azerbaijan and central authorities
have rejected annexation.
   Ryzhkov and the Armenian Communist Party leader, Suren Arutunyan,
called for a compromise solution. They spoke at a televised news
conference.
   Ryzhkov said a Kremlin directive in July rejecting Armenia's
annexation demand had not solved the problem.
   Gorbachev gathered Armenian and Azerbaijani leaders in Moscow
following a session of the Supreme Soviet parliament at the end of
last month. On the basis of that meeting, Arutunyan said, local
officials were working to meet a deadline for a compromise solution
within 12 days. However, he said the earthquake interrupted the work
on the seventh day.
   In a report from Kirovabad, Azerbaijan, where some of the worst
ethnic violence took place last month, Pravda said three Armenians _
I. Muradyan, B. Sisyan, and F. Gulgazaryan _ were held for
investigation for allegedly inciting ethnic unrest among Armenians
living in Azerbaijan.
   It said the three flew to the Kirovabad region several times in a
helicopter to organize meetings. Pravda said a fourth person, former
Soviet Interior Ministry worker L.G. Mirzoyan, was arrested for
interference in agricultural work.
   The report said in a report from the Azerbaijani capital, Baku,
that five people were arrested on suspicion of taking bribes
totaling about $160,000.
   It accused the five, workers in the Ministry of Auto Transport,
of helping organize unsanctioned meetings and demonstrations and of
causing Armenians, Russians and Jews to be fired from their jobs.
   It identified the five by the last names of Ibragimov, Aslanov,
Yusufov, Nabizade, and Ismailov.
</TEXT>
