<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Irish     12-20 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Irish,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Orders New Inquest into IRA Shootings; Journalists Challenge
IRA Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northern Ireland's highest court
on Tuesday ordered a new inquest into the deaths of three unarmed
guerrillas, refueling the controversy over whether police shoot IRA
suspects on sight.
   The Court of Appeals also overturned rulings by a coroner and a
lower court, announcing that three policemen who fired the fatal
shots at the disputed 1982 ambush can be compelled to testify.
   The High Court had upheld coroner James Elliott's ruling that the
officers could not be forced to give evidence.
   But Lord Chief Justice Sir Brian Hutton said, ``The fact that
they are suspected of causing the deaths of the three deceased is
not a reason in law why they should not be compelled to go into the
witness box.''
   But he added that the unidentified lawmen can refuse to give
self-incriminating testimony. The policemen already have been
acquitted of murdering one of the members of the outlawed Irish
Republican Army.
   They were among five officers who ambushed IRA members Gervase
McKerr, Eugene Toman and Sean Burns. The three allegedly failed to
stop their car at a police checkpoint in County Armagh.
   The original inquest was adjourned in late November while Eleanor
McKerr, widow of Gervase McKerr, fought to have the courts order the
policemen to testify and be cross-examined rather than submit
written statements.
   The original inquest has been scrapped.
   Inquests still are pending into the deaths of three more unarmed
Roman Catholics _ two guerrillas and a civilian teen-ager _ who died
in two police ambushes in the same region.
   Police said the deaths, which occurred over a three-week period,
came in the normal course of anti-terrorist activity. But subsequent
evidence suggested the killings were deliberate and avoidable.
   They have opened a fresh chapter in a 6-year-old controversy over
whether police conduct illegal campaigns to shoot IRA suspects on
sight instead of arresting them.
   The Roman Catholic IRA is trying to oust British rule from
Northern Ireland and unite the predominantly Protestant province
with the mainly Catholic Irish Republic.
   In a separate development, six British journalists announced a
court challenge to the government's Oct. 18 ban on radio and
television interviews with members of the IRA, its legal political
wing Sinn Fein, and its sympathizers.
   Financed by the National Union of Journalists, their High Court
appeal argues the order is illegal, contravenes the European
Convention of Human Rights and conflicts with the principle of
editorial independence.
   The measure aimed at silencing IRA propaganda applies to radio
and TV interviews with the publicly funded British Broadcasting
Corp. and independent commercial networks, but not to newspapers or
foreign media.
</TEXT>
