<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Tank     12-20 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Tank,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Opts For Homemade Tank Over U.S. Rival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced Tuesday it has picked a
domestic company over a U.S. firm to develop a new generation of
battle tanks for the British army.
   But Officials said the new British tank would be required to meet
stringent standards over a 21-month development period. If it fails,
they reserved the right to choose the U.S. model or even a West
German tank.
   Announcing the decision in Parliament, Defense Secretary George
Younger said the government would give the British company, Vickers
PLC, a $164 million grant to develop prototypes of its Challenger 2
Mark II tank by September 1990.
   In the final weeks, the choice appeared to have narrowed to the
Challenger and the Abrams M1-A1, a tank made by the U.S.-based
General Dynamics Corp. The U.S. military has used the Abrams M1-A1
for years.
   British government officials said they would stay in contact with
the foreign companies in case the domestic tank fell short of
expectations.
   ``They (Vickers) will have to hit these (development) targets and
hit them well and proper if we are to proceed,'' Younger told
Parliament.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government agonized over the
decision, fearful of repeating the fiasco that ended in 1986 when it
wrote off a dud British spy plane called the Nimrod. The Nimrod cost
nearly $2 billion, but the government instead purchased the Airborne
Warning and Control System planes from the Seattle-based Boeing Co.
   The final contract for the new piece of hardware will call for
about 500 tanks to replace aging Chieftain tanks. The contract will
be worth about $2.5 billion.
   Vickers Chairman David Plastow discounted any similarities
between the new tank and the Nimrod. ``There is no real parallel
with Nimrod, no new state of the art hardware is involved,'' he said.
   General Dynamics Land Systems Division, based in Sterling
Heights, Mich., said it was disappointed but would wait on the
sidelines in case the British tank falters.
   ``Should their development efforts not meet those standards, we
would be prepared to re-enter discussions with British officials
concerning purchase of the Abrams tank to meet their NATO
requirements,'' company officials said in a statement read Tuesday
by spokesman Karl Oskoian.
   Younger denied published reports that British army chiefs had
pushed for the Abrams M1-A1: ``While it is nice to feel that the
best possible tank will be British, it is not the driving force.''
   Plastow had argued if the British government turned down its
model, no other country would buy it. He said potential export
orders to Saudi Arabia and other Middle and Far East countries
totaling about $22 billion would be lost.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
