<1ST_LINE>r w AM-LaxaltProfile     12-20 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Laxalt Profile,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Laxalt: Bush Appointee, Reagan Confidant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul D. Laxalt, named by President-elect Bush
to the commission looking for a solution to the deficit, is a
longtime confidant of President Reagan and one whose own
presidential hopes fell short for want of money.
   Laxalt retired from the U.S. Senate in 1986, giving up a likely
safe seat from Nevada. But more than a senator, he was a close
friend and ally of the president, a man Laxalt described as like a
brother. Their friendship dates to their days as governors of their
adjoining states.
   Laxalt was also general chairman of the Republican National
Committee and managed three Reagan presidential campaigns.
   After giving up his Senate seat, Laxalt sought to become heir to
Reagan's conservative legacy and win the presidential nomination.
   But he found the going difficult, and he ended his presidential
bid in mid-1987, more than a year before the election. He said it
was the lack of money _ he had raised about $1 million, while Bush
was over the $9 million mark at that point.
   ``Washington is a fast-moving town,'' he once remarked. ``You are
a memory very quickly.''
   His appointment by Bush may move him back into the spotlight a
bit.
   Bush named Laxalt and a Democrat, former Ohio Rep. Thomas L.
Ashley, as his representatives on the 14-member National Economic
Commission.
   The bipartisan commission is to recommend ways to close the
federal budget deficit to Bush, whose ``read my lips'' campaign vow
of no tax increases would seem to foreclose one option before the
panel. The panel was created by Congress last year after the stock
market plunge.
   Laxalt is the son of a Basque immigrant sheepherder, and still
enjoys spending time at his family's remote, 120-acre camp in the
Sierra Nevadas east of Lake Tahoe.
   He ran a casino in Carson City, Nev., where he grew up and served
as governor. More recently, Laxalt was embroiled in a $250 million
libel suit against McClatchy Newspapers, over a story that said the
Internal Revenue Service had evidence of skimming at his family's
casino. Both sides claimed victory in the suit's dismissal.
   He held no official position in the Senate leadership, no
committee chairmanship, and he rarely debated issues on the Senate
floor. Yet he had a hand in virtually every major decision of the
first six years of the Reagan presidency, his power deriving from
his closeness to the president.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
