<DOCNO> AP881220-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 1739EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Asylum-Justice 2ndLd-Writethru a0624 12-20 0740</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Asylum-Justice, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0624,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Immigration Official Would Disband Unit Aiding Central Americans</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 7th graf ``This office'' with comment from head of
unit under fire; SUBs 11th graf pvs ``Last week'' with new grafs
12-13 explaining change in work permits</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Immigration Commissioner Alan Nelson has asked
Attorney General Dick Thornburgh to wipe out a Justice Department
unit that has supported Central Americans and others seeking asylum
in the United States, an internal memo shows.
   At issue is the Asylum Policy and Review Unit, which has prodded
the department to override a number of Immigration and
Naturalization Service denials of asylum.
   One point ``we would like to raise with you is the validity of
the Asylum Policy and Review Unit,'' said Nelson's Dec. 13 memo to
Thornburgh, which was obtained by The Associated Press. ``APRU has
cost INS appropriations $750,000 since inception. ... The entire
purpose of APRU and its continued existence should now be reviewed
by your staff.''
   APRU reviews of asylum rejections by INS are ``just plain
financially wasteful,'' said the memo. APRU has persuaded INS to
reconsider denials in 35 cases and has referred another 35 cases to
Justice Department officials who then directed reversals, said
department sources, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   APRU was established in 1987 to monitor INS asylum operations
following a 1985 incident in which a Soviet seaman who jumped ship
on the Mississippi River was returned to his Soviet vessel on orders
of the U.S. Border Patrol. The border patrol is part of INS.
   ``The establishment of the Justice Department unit was a positive
development in that it recognized that INS was incapable of handling
the asylum function,'' Arthur Helton, an attorney for the Lawyers
Committee for Human Rights, said Tuesday. His group favors removing
INS from the asylum process altogether.
   ``This office serves a vital purpose'' and its staff is dedicated
to ensuring that ``the purposes of United States asylum policy are
carried out,'' said Henry Curry, the unit's director, who declined
to respond directly to Nelson's memo.
   Nelson is urging the change in connection with proposed
regulations, first discussed three years ago, which would implement
the Refugee Act of 1980. That law established the standard of
granting U.S. haven to refugees with a well-founded fear of
persecution in their homelands.
   The proposed regulations are finally being shaped at a time when
Nicaraguans and other Central Americans are pouring across the
border illegally and then seeking asylum, saying they have been
persecuted in their home country.
   Nelson's memo asks Thornburgh to review the regulatory proposals
and to issue a final regulation by the end of the year. Thornburgh
is in Europe until later this week and has not yet conducted
discussions on the proposed regulations.
   INS spokesman Greg Leo declined to comment on the memo, saying
that ``we don't want to set a precedent'' in which ``each memo gets
publicly discussed before it gets decided.''
   Last week, the AP obtained internal INS documents outlining a
program under which Nicaraguans and other Central Americans seeking
asylum would no longer be granted work permits while their
applications are pending. INS is assigning additional personnel to
handle the applications in an attempt to shorten the decision time
on the applications to 30 days or less, a process which could
ultimately result in deportations for those whose claims are
rejected.
   Nelson's memo also asked Thornburgh to modify a regulatory
proposal that would set up a centralized system of skilled officers
who consider asylum applications and who would receive training from
APRU.
   The commissioner instead wants the asylum officers placed under
the control of district immigration directors around the country.
   Under that decentralized approach, INS examiners last year
granted asylum requests from 110 Salvadorans and rejected 3,822
other Salvadoran requests for asylum; granted asylum requests from
2,786 Nicaraguans and denied 2,455 others; and granted requests from
24 Guatamalans while denying 447 others.
   ``Asylum applications have almost tripled in the past year due
primarily to the more permissive approach to work authorization,''
said Nelson's memo. ``We need to take the necessary steps to prevent
the existing situation and avoid the proliferation of this
situation.''
   Nelson was referring to a July 1987 statement by then-Attorney
General Edwin Meese III which directed INS to encourage applications
for work authorizations from Nicaraguans seeking asylum.
   Some 60,700 people applied for asylum in fiscal 1988, up from
26,100 the previous year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881220-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 1925EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Steinberg     12-20 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steinberg,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Opens By Attacking Ms. Nussbaum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for Joel Steinberg, accused of murdering
his illegally adopted daughter, opened their defense Tuesday with an
assault on the credibility and character of Steinberg's chief
accuser and former live-in companion.
   Police Officer Thomas Andry testified he had found a woman who
looked just like Hedda Nussbaum drinking a beer and smoking in a
stranger's car while Lisa Steinberg, the 6-year-old girl the couple
raised, was unconscious in the family apartment nearby. He said he
was convinced it was, indeed, Ms. Nussbaum.
   In seven days of graphic testimony, Ms. Nussbaum testified that
she never left the house after Lisa fell unconscious, sometime
around 7 p.m. on Nov. 1, 1987. The prosecution maintains Lisa was
unconscious because Steinberg had struck her before going out to
dinner with a friend.
   ``The focus of this trial has shifted from Joel to Hedda,''
Steinberg's lawyer, Ira London, said outside the courtroom.
   He said there were unexplained bruises on Lisa's body, and
implied that the defense will suggest Ms. Nussbaum was responsible.
   Steinberg, 47, a disbarred lawyer, is charged with second-degree
murder in the child's death. He denies that he hit the child, but
Ms. Nussbaum testified that he told her he had struck Lisa.
   Andry said that he found Ms. Nussbaum sitting, slumped down, in a
car near the couple's Greenwich Village apartment around 8:40 p.m.
on Nov. 1, 1987.
   He said he asked the woman if the car was hers. She said no, and
he told her to get out. She did.
   ``Her nose was distorted like it was messed up somehow. Her eyes
looked like they were dazed,'' he said.
   The officer's description of the woman fit the description of Ms.
Nussbaum, a former children's book author and editor, at the time of
her arrest Nov. 2, 1987. Charges against her were later dropped
after prosecutors concluded she was too severely battered by
Steinberg to have prevented Lisa's death.
   ``Is there any question as you sit here today that the woman you
saw sitting in the car on West 10th Street was Hedda Nussbaum?''
London asked.
   ``There's no question about it,'' the officer replied.
   Earlier in the day, the prosecution rested after presenting 39
witnesses since the trial began more than eight weeks ago.
   State Supreme Court Justice Harold Rothwax denied a defense
request to throw out all charges against Steinberg. He did say he
was inclined to drop one charge against Steinberg, endangering the
welfare of the 16-month-old boy police found in Steinberg's
apartment the morning they took the unconscious Lisa to a hospital.
   The boy was illegally adopted, just as Lisa was. He has since
been returned to his biological mother.
   Rothwax also said he would also instruct the jury to consider two
lesser homicide counts not included in the indictment against
Steinberg. They are second-degree manslaughter and criminally
negligent homicide.
   Steinberg is also charged with second-degree murder, first-degree
manslaughter and endangering the welfare of a minor with respect to
Lisa.
   The prosecution's last witness, Dr. Margaret McHugh, said Lisa
was a victim of child abuse. She based her opinion on medical and
autopsy reports and color photographs taken of the child.
   She said that findings of multiple bruises, the child's poor
hygiene and the brain hemorrhage Lisa suffered were consistent with
child abuse.
</TEXT>
