<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Quayle-Chief     12-20 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle-Chief,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Chooses His Senate Counsel as Chief of Staff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President-elect Dan Quayle on Tuesday
picked Robert M. Guttman, his chief Senate counsel, to be his chief
of staff.
   Guttman, 60, also had expressed an interest in returning to the
Labor Department, where in the Nixon administration as associate
solicitor for legislation he helped draft the 1970 Occupational
Health and Safety Act establishing OSHA.
   An 18-year Capitol Hill veteran in various staff positions,
Guttman will oversee a vice presidential staff of 90 once Qualye
assumes office Jan. 20.
   ``This is the first offer I got and it's the best offer I'm going
to get so I took it,'' Guttman said in a telephone interview after
Quayle's announcement. ``It took me between three and seven
seconds.''
   Guttman was named by Quayle as his chief counsel last year after
Democrats assumed control of the Senate following the 1986 election.
   From 1981 through 1984 he was the chief counsel on the Senate
Labor Committee's subcommittee on employment and productivity that
was chaired by Quayle.
   It was in that role that Guttman helped guide the Job Training
Partnership Act sponsored by the freshman Republican senator from
Indiana through Congress despite initial opposition from President
Reagan.
   The law replaced the scandal-ridden Comprehensive Employment
Training Act or CETA progam as the government's main job-training
effort. Administered through $3 billion to $4 billion a year in
federal block grants to states, it basically subsidizes employer
costs in training disadvantaged and retraining dislocated workers.
   A graduate of Harvard with a law degree from George Washington
University, Guttman worked in various staff jobs in the Labor
Department from 1956 to 1970. From 1970 to 1981, he was a specialist
on social legislation for the Congressional Research Service.
   Quayle also formally announced that David C. Beckwith, 46, a
former correspondent for Time magazine, will be his press secretary.
That decision had been reported earlier.
</TEXT>
