<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 1802EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UNICEF     12-20 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UNICEF,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNICEF: Debt Crisis Killing Children in Developing World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A half-million children died last year
because their Third World countries slashed social welfare spending
when faced with unprecedented debt, UNICEF said Tuesday in its
annual report.
   James P. Grant, UNICEF executive director, urged leaders of
industrialized and developing nations to convene a summit to deal
with the crisis.
   He made the appeal in UNICEF's annual report, ``The State of the
World's Children,'' which he formally released at a New Delhi news
conference telecast live to 40 nations.
   The 500,000 children he mentioned represented only a fraction of
the child deaths in 1987 recorded by the U.N. Children's Fund.
   ``Three million children died last year because they didn't have
50 cents worth of vaccine in them,'' Grant said. Half these deaths
occurred in South Asia.
   Among a few bright spots he highlighted were vaccination programs
in two war-torn countries.
   ``In El Salvador and in Lebanon, in the midst of war, they have
been able to stop the war long enough to immunize their children,''
he said.
   Failure to vaccinate children results not only from the debt
crises but from war, ignorance, lack of health workers and rugged
terrains isolating people from medical care.
   Grant said that for children these were the best and worst of
times.
   ``They are the worst of times because after 35 years of progress,
a significant percentage of mankind _ 900 million people _ is now
sliding backward into poverty,'' he said.
   ``It's the best of times, because low-cost ways (of preventing
children's deaths) are becoming increasingly available.''
   These methods include vaccination against diseases such as
measles, tetanus and whooping cough. Others are oral rehydration
programs, using inexpensive salt solutions that combat diarrhea,
chief killer of small children in many impoverished nations.
   One of the most alarming trends he noted was that 16 nations made
less progress against child mortality last year than they were
making a decade ago because their debt-burdened governments have had
to cut back on social spending.
   ``By far the heaviest consequences are being borne by the
children,'' said Grant. ``For these 16 countries alone, the number
of child deaths in the last 12 months is approximately 650,000 more
than would have been the case if the 1970-80 rate of decline in
under-five mortality had continued.''
   The 16 nations cited by UNICEF are Argentina, Brazil, Chile,
Costa Rica, Cuba, Ecuador, Haiti, Jamaica, Mexico, Panama in the
Western Hemisphere and Benin, Botswana, Liberia, Madagascar, Nigeria
and Togo in Africa.
   The UNICEF report said ``the developing world is now transferring
$20 billion a year more to the rich nations than it receives in new
aid and loans.'' Developing nations owe $1.2 trillion to foreign
governments, private banks and development funds.
   ``It's clear that in the '80s, private contributions for
development have doubled while government assistance has declined,''
Grant said. ``The governments should increase their aid, but there
is also the question of public opinion insisting that they do so.''
   Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, in a pre-recorded preface to
Grant's telecast, said: ``Not only are the present needs of children
neglected but in our greedy growth to development, we are threateing
to mortgage their future.''
   Grant, a U.S. citizen whose Canadian forebears served as doctors
and medical missionaries in India and China, called for a world
summit to focus attention and seek solutions to the problems of
children.
   ``Why shouldn't political leaders of both developing and
developed countries have a world summit on children?'' he asked.
``To reach the unreached, our conclusion is that one must first
reach the unreached's leaders.''
</TEXT>
