<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PressFreedom     12-20 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Press Freedom,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Press Freedom Damaged in Democratic Countries</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tabloids, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Press freedom was undermined in 1988 by governments
in the United States, Britain and other democracies, which should
set examples of tolerance, the International Press Institute said in
a report released Tuesday.
   It called the development the ``most worrying aspect'' of its
annual ``World Press Freedom Review,'' which surveyed the press in
82 countries on six continents.
   ``The hopes and encouragement of nations which are on their way
toward more freedom and who rely on an example from countries with a
democratic system, an open society and freedom, must not be crushed
by governments in the free world,'' director Peter Galliner wrote in
an introduction to the report.
   The institute, which has offices in London and Zurich, is an
independent body representing 2,000 publishers and editors in more
than 60 countries.
   Its report cited these examples of official interference:
   _Washington ``continued its efforts to limit public access to
information held by the American government.''
   _The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the conviction of a former
intelligence analyst for giving satellite photographs of a Soviet
ship to a British magazine. Samuel Loring Morison is serving two
years in prison.
   _Under the new Canada-U.S. Free Trade Agreement restricts
Canadian journalists working in the United States to those with
university degrees and three years experience. It was the first time
the rule, already part of U.S. law, was ``enshrined in an
international accord.''
   _Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's British government tried to
ban publication of extracts from the ``Spycatcher'' memoirs of
former intelligence agent Peter Wright. Newspapers defeated the
government in court.
   _Britain barred radio or television interviews with 11 groups
involved in Northern Ireland, including Sinn Fein, the legal
political wing of the outlawed Irish Republican Army, in the ``most
drastic action taken against British broadcasters in peacetime.''
   _Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi of India, the world's most populous
democracy, agreed only at the last minute to withdraw legislation
shifting the onus of proof of defamation from plaintiff to
journalist.
   _A court court in Australia ordered a journalist to reveal his
sources.
   _Israel suspended three Palestinian newspapers for up to 45 days
and shut down the Palestine Press Service, ``a prime source of
information for the foreign press.''
   Elsewhere, the report found, ``the media under dictatorships
remained all too predictably under lock and key.''
   In Chile there were violent assaults on 24 foreign and Chilean
journalists while five journalists in Colombia were forced to leave
the country following passage of an anti-terrorist law, it said.
   Jordan and Malaysia cracked down on their press, Singapore
continued to pressure the media and China reasserted control on open
discussion and suppressed negative news.
   South Africa closed two church newspapers for three months and
the country's most outspoken anti-apartheid paper, the Weekly Mail,
was suspended for four weeks.
   On the other hand, the report said, many visible and invisible
restrictions were lifted on South Korea's press, and in Taiwan
economic and political liberalizations extended to the media.
   In the Soviet Union, the report declared, ``it seems that
anything goes'' these days. ``No cow, it is tempting to believe, is
too sacred to slaughter. In fact, however, matters are not as simple
as that. ... We should never forget that glasnost (openness) began
as, and remains, a policy guided from above.''
</TEXT>
