<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CanadianAmbassador     12-20 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canadian Ambassador,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Diplomats Must `Play the American Game,' Canadian
Ambassador Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign diplomats must forget tradition and
``play the American game'' if they want to be effective in
Washington, the retiring Canadian ambassador said Tuesday.
   Ambassador Allan Gotlieb told a National Press Club audience that
``In Washington, a foreign government is a special interest and not
a very special one at that.''
   ``If you want to be a successful diplomat in Washington, forget
what you have ever learned about traditional diplomacy,'' said
Gotlieb, who arrived in Washington seven years ago. ``Get up, get
out on the field, and play the American game.''
   He likened the political scene to a large magnetic field crowded
with thousands of electrically charged players, ranging from
politicians to lobbyists and reporters, who sometimes form
harmonious patterns but often repel each other.
   ``Political action committees, dressed as trainers, dispense the
steroids of modern politics _ money _ to the players on all sides,''
he said. ``There are no referees.''
   On the Washington political scene, ``every country is famous for
15 minutes,'' he said, adding that Americans mainly were interested
in the recent Canadian election because it affected the U.S. agenda.
   He was asked about an incident several years ago, in which his
wife Sondra slapped the face of the embassy's social secretary at a
Washington dinner for Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney.
   Gotlieb said his effectiveness as a diplomat was not harmed by
what he termed ``a spontaneous and unfortunate incident.''
   Gotlieb, who is retiring from public service after 30 years,
becomes chairman of the Canada Council on Feb. 1 and will be a
visiting professor at Harvard University in Cambridge, Mass., for
the spring term before settling in Toronto.
</TEXT>
