<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FireDeaths     12-20 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fire Deaths,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christmas Tree Sparked Fire That Killed Four Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A short circuit in Christmas tree
ornaments apparently sparked a fire Tuesday that destroyed a
single-story home, killing four young children and critically
burning two other people.
   The dead children ranged in age from 1 to 5 years old. Two, a
4-year-old boy and his 1-year-old sister, were dead at the scene,
said John Keane, spokesman for the Duval County Fire Department. Two
brothers, ages 5 and 1, died at University Hospital, authorities
said.
   ``The preliminary investigation indicates the fire was caused by
a short circuit in the ornaments on the Christmas tree in the living
room,'' Keane said.
   Eric Oliver, 22, the uncle of two of the dead children, said he
was sleeping in that room when the fire began about 3 a.m. He warned
the families and was credited with saving three occupants.
   ``By the time I ran to the rooms to get the children out, the
flames were on me,'' Oliver said. ``I didn't even know I was burned,
I was trying so hard to get everyone else out.''
   Firefighters found the single-story home almost completely
engulfed in flames when they arrived, Keane said..
   He identified the dead youngsters as Dedrick Ealy, 4, and his
sister Marnecia Ealy, 1, and brothers Corey Oliver, 5, and Cedrick
Oliver, 1.
   The boys' older sister, Lekeisha Oliver, 15, was in critical
condition at University Hospital with burns and respiratory
injuries, pending transfer to the Shriners' Hospital in Cincinnati,
said hospital spokeswoman Sue Lamb.
   Their mother, Sheryl Oliver, 32, who had serious burns and
respiratory injuries, was airlifted to the burn unit at Shands
Hospital in Gainesville, said Keane, and was also in critical
condition. The Ealys' mother Belinda Ealy, 26, suffered minor burns.
   The fire destroyed the house in a moderate-income neighborhood in
northwest Jacksonville, doing about $45,000 in damage, Keane said.
   Neighbors were stunned by the fatal fire.
   Garrick Green, 22, said he and his nephews had been playing with
some of the children the day before.
   Now, his nephews ``are like zombies,'' Green said. ``They're
taking it really hard. There won't be any Christmas for me.''
</TEXT>
