<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan-Soviet     12-20 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan-Soviet,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Kabul Communists Reported Angry at Soviet Allies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some members of Afghanistan's ruling
Communist Party have accused the Soviet Union of betraying them in
recent talks with anti-government rebels, Western diplomats said
Tuesday.
   The reports may lend credence to a rebel claim that Moscow is
ready to negotiate the demise of the government it has supported
with more than 100,000 soldiers. About half the troops have been
withdrawn under a U.N.-mediated agreement signed April 14 and the
rest are to be gone by Feb. 15.
   Burhanuddin Rabbani, chairman of the seven-party Afghan insurgent
alliance based in Pakistan, told a news conference over the weekend
he felt Moscow was ready to abandon its allies in Kabul.
   Rabanni led the guerrilla delegation to the Dec. 3-5 talks with
Yuli Vorontsov, the Soviet deputy foreign minister, Dec. 3-5 in
Taif, Saudi Arabia. A second round is to be held in Islamabad later
this month.
   Vorontsov told the guerrillas the Soviets ``don't want the
present regime'' in Kabul, Rabbani said.
   Diplomats in Islamabad said privately some members members of the
ruling party in Kabul accused Vorontsov of a sellout, but one quoted
a deputy minister as saying the ``regime would accept any solution
which did not require all party members to be exiled to the
U.S.S.R.''
   Moslem guerrillas began fighting in Afghanistan after a Communist
coup in April 1978 and Soviet military forces entered the country in
December 1979.
   Diplomats say about 10,000 Communist Party members and their
families have left Kabul since the Soviet withdrawal began May 15.
</TEXT>
