<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSViruses     12-20 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Viruses,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UCSF Scientists Find Both Types of AIDS Virus In One Woman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers in West Africa have isolated the
AIDS virus and its African cousin from the same patient, showing
both can infect the same individual, scientists report.
   Previous studies had suggested the two viruses could infect the
same person, but the new study confirms it by isolating the viruses
themselves, researchers said.
   In a tatement from the University of California at San Francisco,
researchers said the finding indicates that individuals infected
with one strain should continue to take precautions against becoming
infected by the second. The combination of both strains might speed
up damage to the immune system, they said.
   The work appears in the Dec. 17 issue of The Lancet, a British
medical journal.
   Researchers from UCSF and Africa reported isolating HIV-1, the
virus that causes AIDS in the United States, and the African HIV-2
virus from a 37-year-old woman from the Ivory Coast.
   The viruses cause a variety of diseases, including acquired
immune deficiency syndrome. AIDS from HIV-1 has killed about 45,000
people so far in the United States, but HIV-2 has been found here in
only one West African patient visiting the United States. The HIV-2
strain has been primarily limited to West Africa and parts of Europe.
   The study was led by UCSF postdoctoral researcher Louise Evans
and Jay A. Levy, professor of medicine and an investigator at the
UCSF Cancer Research Institute.
</TEXT>
