<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-20 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0673</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy Snow in Michigan; Warm in East and Parts of Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Winter started a day early out West on Tuesday, and snowfall of
up to 10 inches was reported in northern Michigan, but parts of the
Midwest and East basked in record-breaking warmth.
   High winds were a factor in at least three deaths in Indiana and
Illinois. A strong cold front off the coast of the Pacific Northwest
started to spread wintry weather across much of the Pacific Coast
states. Winter arrives at 10:28 a.m. EST Wednesday.
   Light rain fell at midday along the northern and central Pacific
Coast and snow fell in inland portions of the Pacific Northwest. As
the storm system moved farther inland, snow was expected to increase
and become more widespread, especially in mountain areas, the
National Weather Service said.
   A winter storm warning was posted for the northern Sierra Nevada
range of California as well as higher elevations of the western
Nevada mountains and the Lake Tahoe basin. Between 1 and 2 feet of
snow was expected in parts of the region. Another winter storm
warning remained in effect for the Cascade and Siskyou mountains of
Oregon.
   Winter storm watches and snow advisories were posted for other
parts of Nevada, Oregon, Idaho, Washington and northern California.
   In Utah, snow fell overnight and into Tuesday morning in the
northern mountains, with accumulations up to 6 inches reported in
the higher canyon areas.
   Elsewhere, a low pressure area moving through the Great Lakes
spread rain, freezing rain and drizzle over northern Wisconsin as
well as central and eastern Upper Michigan. Heavy snow fell in
western Upper Michigan, with Ironwood receiving 7 inches of new snow
and Ontonagan 8 to 10 inches.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. EST
included 0.48 inch at North Bend, Ore.; 0.38 inch at Toledo, Wash.;
and 0.24 inch at Medford, Ore. During the same six hours, an inch of
snow fell at Salt Lake City.
   Winds gusted to 70 mph in Indianapolis, 60 mph in Ottawa County,
Mich., and 53 mph at South Bend, Ind.
   Wind gusts were so strong in Indianapolis that a wall under
construction collapsed, killing a construction worker. Wind gusts of
35 mph were blamed for fanning a rapidly spreading blaze that killed
a teen-age girl and her 21-year-old brother at their home in
Gifford, Ill.
   Temperatures early Tuesday afternoon were in the single digits
and teens in northern Minnesota and eastern North Dakota. But record
warm weather was reported in parts of the mid-Atlantic states to the
Great Lakes, including 49 at Alpena, Mich.; 63 in Baltimore; 57 in
Detroit; 43 in Sault Ste. Marie, Mich.; and 63 in Wilkes-Barre and
Scranton, Pa.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 8
degrees at International Falls, Minn., to 82 degrees at McAllen,
Texas. The early-morning low for the nation Tuesday was 4 degrees
below zero at Cutbank, Mont.
   The forecast for Wedneday called for a cold front to move across
the Appalachians, producing showers and thunderstorms from Louisiana
all the way to New England. The weather system that moved into the
West on Tuesday was expected to spread rain across all of the
Pacific Coast and snow over much of the Intermountain region between
the Rockies and the Sierra Nevada and the mountains of eastern
Oregon and Washington, as well as the northern and central Rockies.
Lake-effect snow showers were forecast for Upper Michigan.
   High temperatures in the teens and 20s were forecast for the
upper Mississippi Valley, the northern Great Lakes and the extreme
northern Plains; in the 30s and 40s from the northern half of the
Pacific Coast, across to the Rockies, the central Plains, the
southern Great Lakes to northern New England; the 70s in southern
Texas, the Gulf Coast, Florida and the southern Atlantic Coast; and
the 50s and 60s in most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
