<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada 1stLd-Writethru a0673 12-20 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0673,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quebec Decision on Signs Revives Regional, Linguistic Tensions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th `Environment Minister' to include two
other resignations. PICKS up 5th pvs: Bourassa based his ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Regional and linguistic antagonisms that have
threatened unity throughout Canada's history are reviving because
Quebec will not comply with a ruling that it allow the posting of
signs in English.
   The Supreme Court said last week the predominantly
French-speaking province is justified in making sure French
predominates on signs but cannot prevent the use of other languages.
   Robert Bourassa, the provincial premier, angered both English
speakers and militants from the majority with his compromise last
Sunday: French must remain the only language on outdoor signs but
other languages can be used indoors so long as French predominates.
   Environment Minister Clifford Lincoln, one of four English
speakers in Bourassa's Cabinet, resigned Tuesday and said: ``In my
beliefs, rights are rights are rights. There are no partial rights.
There are no indoor-outdoor rights.''
   Two of the other English speakers _ Public Security Minister
Herbert Marx and Communications Minister Richard French _ quit later
Tuesday.
   Bourassa based his decision on a clause put into the constitution
by Western provinces as a protection against federal power, which
allows provinces or the national government to override a court
decision.
   The resumption of divisiveness in Canada followed four years of
general calm that made possible the 1987 Meech Lake constitutional
agreement recognizing Quebec as a ``distinct society.''
   Only eight of the 10 provinces have ratified the accord, named
for the place in Quebec where it was signed. Premier Gary Filmon of
Manitoba said Monday he no longer would push for legislative
approval in his Western province because of Bourassa's action.
   New Brunswick, on the Atlantic coast, is the other province yet
to ratify the agreement.
   Filmon described the Quebec decision as a ``national tragedy''
and called for a national conference of provincial leaders to
persuade the French-speaking province to accept the court decision.
   Which language can be used on signs is a volatile and symbolic
issue Quebec's French speakers _ 81 percent of the population _
consider essential to preserving their linguistic and cultural
heritage.
   Bourassa's plan prohibits languages other than French on signs
both outdoors and in such places as shopping malls and interiors of
public transportation facilities.
   An editorial Tuesday in The Globe and Mail of Toronto said:
   ``What now? Almost certainly a hardening of hearts, a less
generous attitude, an unwillingness to spend precious political
capital on bilingualism and francophones, tougher questioning of the
primordiality granted to Quebec's concerns; in sum, a quiet,
unspectacular but undeniable backlash that will do us all no good.''
   La Presse, a widely read Montreal daily, said Bourassa chose
``the best compromise under the circumstances.'' It said either
continuing the ban on any language other than French or allowing
bilingual signs everywhere ``would have been to scorn Quebec
reality, both historic and present.''
   In 1985, Bourassa campaigned for election on a platform that
included easing language restrictions on signs. Critics say he could
have avoided angering militants if he had acted soon after the
election instead of responding to a court ruling three years later.
   A crowd of 10,000 or more attended a rally Sunday in Montreal
demanding no changes in the language law, which was passed in 1977
by the separatist Parti Quebecois gpverment.
   Power in the province shifted from the English-speaking minority
to the French speakers in the 1970s. Separatist sentiment abated
after the language law was passed and Quebec's voters rejected a
sovereignty in a 1980 referendum.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
