<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     12-20 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Fighting Between Shiite Militias</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite Moslem militias fought in
Beirut's southern slums Tuesday and police said at least one person
was killed. Six people were reported wounded.
   Shopkeepers in the predominantly Shiite slums lowered their
shutters and pedestrians and motorists took cover when the Shiites
began shooting at each other with mortars, rocket-propelled grenades
and heavy machine guns.
   Police said they did not know what started the battle shortly
after 6 p.m. between Amal, a mainstream militia backed by Syria, and
the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   The two militias compete for the leadership of Lebanon's 1.2
million Shiites, the nation's largest sect. Forty people were killed
and 87 wounded, by police count, in six days of fighting last month
that spread through Moslem south and west Beirut.
   On Tuesday, a police spokesman said Hezbollah gunmen ``apparently
(were) trying to overrun the Amal headquarters'' in the Bourj
el-Barajneh district. Each side accused the other of starting the
fight.
   Most of the 15 foreign hostages in Lebanon are believed to be in
the southern suburbs, Hezbollah's stronghold. Held longest is Terry
A. Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The Associated
Press, who was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
