<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 2042EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Honduras-Contras     12-20 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras-Contras,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduras Accuses Contras Of Holding Sandinista Soldiers, Civilians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is taking steps to
free more than 100 Nicaraguan soldiers and civilians held prisoner
in Honduras by Nicaraguan rebels, Foreign Minister Carlos Lopez
Contreras said Tuesday.
   He said the prisoners are being held by the Nicaraguan
Resistance, an umbrella group of forces fighting to overthrow
Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government.
   Lopez Contreras said the prisoners, Sandinista loyalists, are
being detained in camps at Yamales, a small town about 230 miles
east of Tegucigalpa near the Nicaraguan border.
   The government's moves come as its support fades for Nicaraguan
rebels based on Honduran territory. The rebels, known as Contras, in
turn have been weakened by the cutoff of U.S. aid in February. Rebel
military operations have subsided.
   Lopez Contreras said Roman Catholic Church leaders, the Red Cross
and the London-based International Commission on Human Rights have
agreed to help release the prisoners.
   ``The authorities will proceed to rescue 104 of these
prisoners,'' Lopez Contreras told a news conference Tuesday.
   ``The existence of such Nicaraguan Resistance camps violates our
laws and sovereignty. We will continue efforts to release all the
prisoners in Contra hands.''
   Lopez Contreras said he would risk hampering the rescue operation
if he released details of it.
   Thousands of anti-Sandinista Nicaraguan refugees have been living
in squalid camps in southern Honduras since 1979, when the
Sandinistas overthrew pro-American rightist dictator Anastasio
Somoza.
   Honduras has officially denied the existence of the rebel camps.
In recent months, however, some Hondurans complained of rowdiness by
rebels and pressured the government to expel them.
</TEXT>
