<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 2048EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador     12-20 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Attack Salvadoran Air Force Headquarters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels attacked air force
headquarters on Tuesday with truck bombs and explosives lobbed by
catapults, but did not penetrate the base. Two soldiers and two
civilians were reported wounded.
   A fourth mayor in San Miguel province resigned after receiving
death threats from the leftist rebels, who accuse the officials of
participating in a U.S.-backed plans against the guerrilla movement
in their communities.
   The attack on Ilopango air base was the first in nearly seven
years and the second this month on a major military installation in
the capital. Witnesses said it began at about 10:45 a.m. with nearly
simultaneous explosions of two pickup trucks parked outside the wall
150 yards apart.
   Military sources said the rebels lobbed homemade bombs with
makeshift catapults but most exploded against the outer wall of the
base in eastern San Salvador.
   Witnesses said an ice cream vendor and another civilian passer-by
were wounded, and the military sources said two paratroopers were
wounded inside the base. Witnesses and sources spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Military spokesman Col. Galileo Torres said three vehicles laden
with explosives detonated outside the base, but witnesses and
reporters saw the smoking wreckage of only two.
   A pilot at the base said: ``The security is efficient. This is
the only kind of attack they can mount on us.'' A soldier told
reporters: ``The guerrillas don't have the courage to try to
penetrate. They place a bomb, then run.''
   Rebels set off explosives during an attack on the base in January
1982 that killed nine soldiers and destroyed 12 aircraft. An assault
on National Guard headquarters on the capital's northern edge last
Nov. 1 killed four guardsmen and wounded 34 people, including
civilians.
   Homemade bombs flung by catapult are a favorite weapon of the
rebels, who have fought U.S.-supported governments for nine years.
An estimated 65,500 people have been killed.
   Mayor Tomas Erasmo Campos Rosales of Villa el Transito, 75 miles
east of San Salvador, told reporters he received a death threat from
the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, a coalition of five
rebel groups.
   Similar letters to the mayors of San Jorge, San Rafael Oriente
and Chinameca caused them to resign last week. All four belong to
the rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance.
   Eight mayors have been killed since taking office after
nationwide municipal elections in May.
   About 1,000 students rallied outside the Treasury Ministry on
Tuesday to protest the killing of a professor and demand that
December salaries be paid to National University teachers and
workers.
   Imelda Gonzalez Medrano, director of the university law
department, was killed Friday in Santa Ana after leading a similar
protest march in the western city.
   No one was arrested in the killing. Student leaders blame the
government of President Jose Napoleon Duarte and the army's 2nd
Infantry Brigade in Santa Ana.
   El Salvador's treasury is strapped because of the war. Student
leaders claim the government, which administers the university, owes
teachers and workers $1.2 million.
</TEXT>
