<2ND_LINE>AM-Polygamist Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0650,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Deliberates in Murder Trial of Three Polygamist Clan Members</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `The eight-member...', to UPDATE with jurors
breaking off for the night. Picks up 5th graf, `The siege...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COALVILLE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors deliberated for a second day
Tuesday in the murder trial of three members of a polygamist clan
charged in the fatal shooting of a law officer during a raid on the
group's compound.
   The Jan. 28 assault by officers at the rural homestead ended a
13-day standoff between authorities and members of the clan, accused
in the bombing of an empty Mormon chapel.
   Clan patriarch Addam Swapp, 27; his brother Jonathan Swapp, 21,
and brother-in-law John Timothy Singer, 22, are charged with
second-degree murder in the death of Corrections Lt. Fred House,
gunned down as he directed attack dogs toward the Swapp brothers
during the raid. In the ensuing firefight, Addam Swapp also was
seriously wounded.
   The eight-member jury, which is being allowed by the judge to set
its own schedule, spent three hours in deliberations Monday. On
Tuesday, jurors put in 8{ hours more before breaking off for the
night without a verdict.
   The siege by 100 FBI-led police officers began Jan. 16, hours
after Addam Swapp bombed the chapel in nearby Marion.
   Both sides agree that Singer fired the fatal bullet, but Singer
maintains he was firing at the dogs, not House.
   In addition to the second-degree murder charges, jurors were
instructed they could consider convicting the three on lesser
charges including manslaughter and negligent homicide.
   Under Utah law, the maximum penalty for second-degree murder is
five years to life in prison. For manslaughter, the maximum term is
zero to five years, and for negligent homicide one year in jail and
a $2,500 fine.
   In connection with the case, 3rd Circuit Judge Maurice Jones
scheduled a Jan. 10 trial for Carla Foster, described by police as
an acquaintance of the clan. She pleaded innocent to a misdemeanor
charge of carrying a concealed weapon.
   Foster said she was on her way to the trial and asked a court
clerk what to do about the small-caliber handgun she carried in her
purse. The clerk told her to ask courthouse security officers, she
said.
   Foster said when she did, she was detained, arrested and charged.
</TEXT>
