<1ST_LINE>u a AM-UraniumPlant     12-20 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Uranium Plant,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Energy Department to Negotiate Legally Binding Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Energy Department will negotiate
with the state to reach a legally binding agreement to clean up a
federally owned uranium processing plant, a spokesman said Tuesday.
   The decision was made late Tuesday, said Douglas Elmets, a
spokesman for the department in Washington. A day earlier, he had
said federal officials were still considering whether the agreement
should be in the form of a consent decree that would be enforceable
through federal courts.
   News reports indicating that the Energy Department was backing
away from a consent decree had prompted state Attorney General
Anthony Celebrezze to insist that Ohio had a commitment that federal
officials should honor.
   When state officials announced a $50 million federal agreement on
Nov. 22 to clean up the Portsmouth Gaseous Diffusion Plant at
Piketon in southern Ohio they said it could serve as a model for
dealing with contamination at nuclear weapons plants around the
country.
   Elmets said the department reached its decision after discussions
with Ohio officials and consultations with the Justice Department
and the Energy Department's operations office in Oak Ridge, Tenn.
   ``This decision was based on the same factors that influenced our
decision on two earlier consent decrees in regard to Fernald
litigation,'' Elmets read from a prepared statement.
   He was referring to the announcement earlier this month of a
court-approved agreement that gave Ohio authority to regulate the
Energy Department's cleanup of the Feed Materials Production Center,
a weapons-grade uranium processing plant in Fernald, 18 miles
northwest of Cincinnati.
   ``We analyze the specific facts of each case and litigation risks
involved, and the overriding consideration in all these cases was
the attractive settlement proposals which were fair to both sides
and made pursuing litigation unwise,'' Elmets said.
   Gov. Richard Celeste and Celebrezze were not immediately
available Tuesday night to comment on the Energy Department's
decision.
   Earlier, Celebrezze had expressed dissatisfaction with what
seemed to be a federal reversal of its promise to negotiate toward a
legally binding agreement.
   ``This is not atypical of the federal government. But we have a
commitment from them, and we expect them to keep it,'' he said. ``I
will accept nothing less than a consent decree.''
   Elmets said the decision Tuesday does not mean the Energy
Department will pursue similar agreements with other states that
claim its nuclear facilities have polluted the environment.
   He also would not discuss details of any proposals put forth by
the state.
   The Piketon plant processes uranium for fuel for commercial
nuclear power reactors. It generates toxic wastes such as
polychlorinated biphenyls, or PCBs, solvents and metals, as well as
radioactive materials.
   Piketon site manager Eugene Gillespie, an Energy Department
employee, said some of the cleanup work that is included in the
agreement began Dec. 1, and plans for further action have been
submitted to the Ohio Environmental Protection Agency, which is to
supervise the cleanup of about 6 million pounds of waste.
</TEXT>
