<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Politics 2ndLd-Writethru a0633 12-20 0877</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Politics, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0633,0900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coalition Government Narrowly Approved; Guidelines Bar PLO Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 19 grafs UPDATING with narrowly approved coalition
government, details. PICKS up 20th graf pvs: Peres told reporters
...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JRL5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The right-wing Likud bloc's delegates narrowly
approved a coalition agreement with the left-leaning Labor Party
early Wednesday, another step toward formation of the next Israeli
government, Israeli radio said.
   The agreement still needs approval by the Labor Party's
1,200-member central committee, which planned to meet for a vote
Wednesday afternoon. If Labor approves, the national unity
government could be presented to the Knesset, or parliament, on
Thursday.
   Guidelines of the new government ban talks with the PLO, setting
Israel on a collision course with the United States.
   The new government will be remarkably similar to the outgoing
national unity government, except that Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir, the Likud leader, will be prime minister throughout the
four-year term. In the previous term, Labor leader Shimon Peres, the
current foreign minister, was premier for the first two years.
   Likud delegates voted in a secret ballot Tuesday night, after a
stormy meeting in which opponents led by Ariel Sharon, Likud's
former defense minister, fought a last ditch effort to overturn it.
   Israeli radio said 796 delegates, or 55 percent, voted for the
agreement, and 642 delegates, or 44.4 percent, voted against. The
final tally was reported just after 3 a.m. Wednesday (8 p.m. EST
Tuesday).
   Sharon told the delegates who met in Tel Aviv that Labor was an
unfit partner because it favored withdrawal from the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip and some of its members approved of talking to
the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Israel views the PLO as a terrorist group.
   Shamir told the delegates that if the party did not approve the
agreement at the meeting he would go to President Chaim Herzog and
give up the mandate he was given to form a new government. Such a
move would throw Israel's political system into a state of confusion.
   Herzog had given Shamir, whose party slightly edged out Labor in
Nov. 1 elections, until Dec. 26 to form a new government.
   Labor Cabinet ministers, meanwhile, approved the coalition pact
Tuesday. The agreement will be submitted Wednesday to the party's
1,000-member central committee.
   Peres said formation of the new coalition would spell defeat for
the proposed ``Who is a Jew'' legislation that was vehemently
opposed by U.S. Jews.
   That prospect touched off wrangling between Shamir and the four
religious parties, who originally demanded the legislation and now
threaten to stay out of the coalition.
   Shamir hopes to include the religious parties to make it more
difficult for Labor to bring down the government should an impasse
occur.
   Yitzhak Peretz of the Ultra-Orthodox Shas party accused Shamir of
breaking his pledges. ``He promised us and signed an agreement to
help change the Law of Return,'' he said.
   The Law of Return grants automatic Israeli citizenship to all
Jews, and the amendment would require Orthodox approval of all
conversions to Judaism. U.S. Jews feel the legislation will divide
the Jewish community.
   Shamir said Labor and Likud were united in standing up to the
``common danger'' _ Arab demands for creation of an independent
Palestinan state.
   ``There is a common danger to all of us, the establishment of a
Palestinian state. Both Labor and Likud see it as a danger, and the
government will deal with it in a unified effort,'' he said.
   Although fear of too much influence by the religious parties had
already sparked public support for another unity government, the
latest agreement also was spurred by the U.S. decision last week to
open a dialogue with the PLO. Shamir aides said they wanted to
present a unified front against the move by their greatest ally.
   Peres told reporters the new government guidelines mean ``there
will be no negotiations with the PLO.''
   The decision to ban talks with the PLO puts Israel increasingly
out of step with the rest of the international community, and could
strain relations with Washington, which provides $3 billion a year
in economic and military aid to the Jewish state.
   Israeli officials said the new government would give top priority
in the next two months to devising a peace formula that will be an
acceptable alternative to dealing with the PLO.
   One official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
guidelines call for talks based on the 1978 Camp David accords which
envision limited autonomy for Palestinians and the participation of
Jordan in the peace process.
   There will be few new faces in the new government. Labor and
Likud will each control 10 seats in the Cabinet, which will have a
total of 24 or 25 members. Key policy decisions, however, will be
made by Shamir, Peres, Labor's Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin and
Likud's Foreign Minister Moshe Arens, a close Shamir ally and former
ambassador to the United States.
   Peres will become finance minister, a post Labor officials urged
him to take in order to help debt-ridden party institutions such as
the Histradrut trade union federation and the kibbutz movement of
communal farms.
   The institutions form the backbone of the Labor Party and are
crucial to its support.
</TEXT>
