<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ArmoredRobbery     12-20 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Armored Robbery,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Men, One In Santa Claus Suit, Hold Up Armored Car</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK SEAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A robber in a Santa Claus hat and
beard snatched more than $700,000 from two armored car guards
Tuesday in this fashionable suburb's third large heist in a little
more than five years.
   Police and FBI officials said the man, who wielded a
silver-colored revolver, took two sacks of cash from Dunbar Armored
Security Inc. guards outside a United Bank branch shortly after 9
a.m.
   ``This is not a joke. Get up against the wall. Give me the bags
of money,'' the robber told the guards, according to police Capt.
Russell Hughes.
   No shots were fired and neither guard was injured, police said.
The robber hopped into a car with an accomplice and they drove off
on a nearby highway, Hughes said.
   Authorities suspect that the robbers tailed the armored car to
the bank, said Terry Shumard, a spokesman for the FBI. He said the
two bags held more than $700,000 in cash.
   ``Santa'' didn't have a red suit to match his hat and false
beard, officials said: He was dressed in a gray trenchcoat.
   Hughes said the guards were engaged in ``routine'' business at
the bank, but he didn't have any further information. Carla Dunbar,
a receptionist at the armored car company, said officials would have
no comment.
   Employees and the two or three customers inside the bank at the
time were unaware the theft was taking place, said teller Jane E.
Neveu.
   It was the second armored car heist in two years in the Hartford
suburb and the third big theft since 1983.
   On March 4, 1987, three men stole $1 million in cash from a
Loomis Armored Inc. truck parked outside a branch of the Bank of
Boston. No suspects were ever apprehended.
   The town's most notorious heist occurred on Sept. 12, 1983, when
$7.1 million was taken from a Wells Fargo depot. The government
contends that a security guard, Victor Gerena, pulled the robbery to
help finance a Puerto Rican independence movement.
   Sixteen people were charged in connection with that robbery. So
far, two pleaded guilty and five are on trial in U.S. District
Court. Federal authorities say they think that Gerena is in Cuba.
   Carl Rosensweig, a West Hartford police detective, said that
although the number of large heists in the town of 60,000 is
unusual, there is no evidence they are related.
</TEXT>
