<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SweetheartShooting 1stLd-Writethru a0698 12-20 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sweetheart Shooting, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0698,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>News Exec's Stepson Guilty of Murder Attempt on Woman Who Spurned
Him</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10-12th grafs pvs, bgng `It was...', with 4 grafs to
UPDATE with quotation from victim; and to CLARIFY that `little girl'
mentioned by defense lawyer is victim. Picks up 13th graf, `Ackerman
claimed...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stepson of a newspaper executive was found
guilty Tuesday of trying to murder his girlfriend after she rebuffed
his marriage proposal. The shooting left her paralyzed for life.
   Jurors rejected Bradley Ackerman's defense that he was crazed by
drugs and intent only on suicide when he shot 23-year-old Julie
Alban, whom he had dated for nearly 10 months, as she lay sleeping
in her parents' home June 8.
   Ackerman, 24, then turned the gun on himself, but he recovered
from his wounds.
   The tragedy involved families who lived across the street from
each other and youngsters raised in a world of wealth and privilege.
Ackerman is the stepson of Daniel Ridder, chairman of the Long Beach
Press-Telegram. Miss Alban is the daughter of a prominent orthopedic
surgeon.
   Ackerman showed no emotion as the verdict was read in a packed
courtroom. Ridder, who sat in a front-row seat, was grim-faced as it
was announced and rushed from the courtroom without comment.
   Jurors found Ackerman guilty of willful, premeditated attempted
first-degree murder. They further found that he used a gun illegally
and intentionally inflicted great bodily harm on Miss Alban, who
testified from a wheelchair.
   Superior Court Judge J.D. Smith said he considered Ackerman a
suicide risk and ordered him held in the hospital section of the
county jail. Sentencing was set for Feb. 6.
   The prosecutor, Deputy District Attorney Kenneth Lamb, said the
only sentence possible on Ackerman's attempted murder conviction is
life in prison with the possibility of parole. An additional
five-year sentence is possible on the two gun-related charges, he
said.
   Prosecutors said Miss Alban had spurned Ackerman's marriage
proposal just hours before the shooting.
   ``There can never be justice for me,'' Miss Alban told KNBC-TV
after learning of the verdict. ``I'm going to be in a wheelchair the
rest of my life ... battling complications. Brad may be out ... in
10 years.''
   ``It was clearly a justified verdict,'' said Lamb. ``No matter
what happens to Bradley Ackerman, his sentence to Julie was death
and, failing that, he sentenced her to life in a wheelchair.''
   But Ackerman's lawyer, Anthony Murray, said the verdict was
decided emotionally, not on the facts.
   ``This was an extremely emotional jury,'' he said. ``The
courtroom was charged with emotion when the `little girl' (Miss
Alban) came in to testify. They couldn't focus on the facts.''
   Ackerman claimed he was in a Valium-induced stupor when he shot
Miss Alban with a single bullet to the back, paralyzing her below
the waist.
   His lawyer argued that the young man had taken 30 pills in an
attempt to kill himself out of depression over a $30,000 gambling
debt and his failure to fulfill his early promise as a tennis player.
   Ackerman testified he did not remember shooting Miss Alban. She
testified that she was awakened by a bullet ripping into her spine,
then dragged herself to a telephone and called for help.
   Lamb told jurors that Ackerman's precision in firing the
.38-caliber revolver showed he was not suffering from a Valium
blackout.
   He portrayed Ackerman as a rejected suitor, a selfish,
irresponsible man who invented the blackout defense to escape
responsibility for his action.
</TEXT>
