<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HappyBirthday     12-20 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Happy Birthday,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Happy Birthday To You,' The Song, Being Sold</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Happy Birthday To You'' is not just a tune
to warble on the appropriate occasions, it's a solid investment with
good profit potential, says an official of the company that's buying
it.
   Geoffrey Holmes, senior vice president of Warner Communications,
Tuesday confirmed a report that the giant entertainment company was
buying the birthday song and the New Jersey publishing company that
owns it. But he wouldn't confirm the reported price, $25 million.
   ``This is a business deal,'' Holmes said. ``We're approaching
this whole thing in that it's a very attractive deal to them and to
us. If it wasn't economical, we certainly wouldn't do it.''
   The New York Times reported Tuesday that Warner Chappell, a
division of Warner Communications, will pay $25 million for
Birchtree Ltd. of Princeton. The newspaper cited an unidentified
executive familiar with the negotiations. Birchtree spokeswoman Kate
Shen also confirmed that Warner Chappell, which is the world's
largest music publisher, was buying the family-owned Birchtree. But,
like Holmes, she wouldn't confirm the reported price tag.
   ``It's agreed to, but it's not closed,'' Ms. Shen said. ``The
song should be Warner's by the end of the year.''
   Holmes would not say what the return on ``Happy Birthday'' has
been, but it is believed to be about $1 million a year. The company
plans to boost revenues from the song by increasing marketing, he
said.
   Holmes said the company likes the idea of owning a classic, but
he stressed that Warner is not buying the song for prestige or
sentimental reasons.
   ``We think there are a lot of opportunities to further exploit
the song,'' Holmes said. ``We think we can further enhance the
song's royalties.''
   The birthday staple and the company were put on the block in
October because Birchtree lacked the resources to monitor and
protect copyrights, said Birchtree Chairman David Sengstack, whose
family owns the company. A copyright issued on the song in 1935
expires in 2010.
   Warner Chappell has a large operation to protect copyrights _
that is, make sure people who use the songs for profit pay royalties
_ and would be able to reduce costs of protecting ``Happy Birthday''
and other Birchtree songs, Holmes said.
   Warner Chappell already owns the rights to songs by George and
Ira Gershwin, Michael Jackson and Cole Porter, among others.
   Altogether, Birchtree owns 50,000 titles, of which about 1,700
are actively collecting royalty fees. Spokesmen said that, compared
with ``Happy Birthday To You,'' the other titles are obscure.
   The song began as a classroom greeting in 1893 penned by two
schoolteacher sisters from Louisville, Ky., Patty Smith Hill and
Mildred J. Hill. The birthday lyrics were added later.
   Since then, it has become one of the three most frequently sung
songs in the English language, along with ``Auld Lang Syne'' and
``For He's a Jolly Good Fellow,'' according to the Guinness Book of
World Records.
   Birchtree also owns the Suzuki Methods, an instrumental
instruction method for violin, cell and viola.
   ``Happy Birthday'' and Birchtree are to be only the latest of
Warner's expanding music publishing business. Last year it spent
about $275 million to by Chappell & Company, which was privately
owned.
</TEXT>
