<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Sullivan-Abortion 3rdLd-Writethru a0709 12-20 0778</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sullivan-Abortion, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0709,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Abortion Groups Protest Possible HHS Choice</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 14th-15th grafs pvs, bgng: ``Sullivan echoed...'' with
1
graf to add details on letter; picks up 16th graf pvs, bgng:
``Sullivan did...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-abortion groups, many already suspicious
of George Bush's commitment to their cause, have bombarded the Bush
camp with objections to the possible appointment of Louis Sullivan
as secretary of health and human services.
   A report quoting the Atlanta educator's sentiments on abortion
created a furor among conservatives, and anxiety about what one
group called ``a slap in the face to the millions of anti-abortion
voters.''
   Sullivan, president of the Morehouse School of Medicine, told
Bush in an interview last week that if appointed he would support
the president-elect's anti-abortion campaign positions, according to
Bush's press secretary Sheila Tate.
   But concern flared anew, said Jack Fowler, Washington chief of
the Ad Hoc Committee in Defense of Life, when the Atlanta Journal
and Constitution quoted him Sunday as saying he supported a women's
right to abortion though he opposed federal funding.
   Transition sources have said for many days that Sullivan was the
front-runner for the health and human services post but that Bush
had not formally offered him the job. A Bush transition spokesman,
David Prosperi, said Tuesday that Sullivan was still under
consideration.
   ``Our discussions with Dr. Sullivan have been ... very
encouraging,'' transition team leader Craig Fuller told CBS News.
``We feel he is a very strong candidate. I think we'd like to go
forward with him and I think we're pretty close to that.''
   A statement from Fowler's group said Sullivan's appointment would
be a ``slap in the face'' to conservatives and would continue ``the
obstructionist tactics pro-abortion HHS Secretary Otis Bown has
employed against anti-abortionists.''
   ``Generally among the various conservative and right-to-life
groups in town there is confusion and thus concern about his
possible appointment,'' said Gary Bauer, who was former White House
domestic policy adviser to President Reagan and now heads the
private Family Research Council.
   Bauer said such an appointment would be ``politically stupid,''
because it would alienate a constituency that supported Bush in the
campaign.
   He said his group and others have told Bush transition officials
of their ``great discomfort'' at the thought of having Sullivan in
the Cabinet.
   Rep. Bob Dornan, R-Calif., said abortion was the one issue about
which he was ``distrustful'' of Bush before he decided to endorse
the vice president's presidential candidacy.
   Bush satisfied Dornan that his position was in line with the
conservative stance, but Dornan said Tuesday that Bush ``will rue
the day he picks'' Sullivan.
   Bush has said he opposes abortion except in cases of rape, incest
or danger to the mother's life. He supports a constitutional
amendment to make abortion illegal, and opposes federal funding for
abortion.
   Sullivan echoed those positions in a Dec. 18 letter that was
being circulated to conservative groups and was published in
Wednesday's editions of The Atlanta Constitution. The letter said,
``I am writing to clarify my position on abortion. I am opposed to
abortion except in cases of rape, incest and where the life of the
mother is threatened... My position on abortion is entirely
consistent with President-elect George Bush's position.''
   Sullivan did not return reporters' calls.
   Transition officials denied suggestions that the
Sullivan-abortion issue caused the sudden cancellation of Cabinet
announcements Tuesday.
   Transition personnel director Chase Untermeyer told reporters the
abortion issue is important and that ``I am confident that whoever
is the nominee is certain to conform.''
   The conservatives fear another secretary like Reagan appointee
Otis Bowen, who they say has supported Reagan's anti-abortion views
in word only.
   ``We need an advocate for the pre-born, not a yes man who
undermines everything from behind the scenes,'' said Dornan.
   Sullivan's statement lining up with Bush's positions did not
satisfy the National Right to Life Committee, which last week wrote
to Bush objecting to Sullivan.
   The group's president, John Willke, said in a statement that even
though Sullivan may pledge to carry out the Bush agenda, ``only a
person who shares president-elect Bush's pro-life ethic and
convictions can make genuinely pro-life decisions on the hundreds of
day-to-day matters which cannot all be referred to the president.''
   Another aspect of the abortion issue that conservatives consider
anathema is the use of fetal tissue for research. The Atlanta
newspaper quoted Sullivan as supporting that practice and saying,
``We have a number of medical advances that have occurred as a
result of research with fetal tissue that have benefited the lives
of many people.''
   Transition spokesman Prosperi said he did not know Bush's
position on that issue.
</TEXT>
