<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Peru-RebelStrike     12-20 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Rebel Strike,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels' General Strike Paralyzes Peruvian City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUANCAYO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maoist rebels cut transportation to a
trickle Tuesday and shut down nearly all schools and offices in this
important highland city in a general strike which they threatened to
enforce with weapons.
   Scores of police and soldiers patrolled Huancayo's nearly empty
streets, but no reports emerged of violence or other guerrilla
activity.
   It was the second so-called ``armed strike'' declared by the
Shining Path guerrillas in recent weeks. They paralyzed Ayacucho,
their stronghold about 100 miles southeast of Huancayo, for a week
in late November with a similar strike.
   The rebels called the three-day strike in Huancayo, 125 miles
east of Lima, on Monday.
   The state government was quoted as saying Tuesday's strike had no
impact. Abilio Fernandez, the chief administrative officer of Junin
state, said activity was normal throughout the state, according to a
dispatch by the state news agency Andina.
   However, reporters for The Associated Press and other media said
nearly everyone stayed indoors, apparently in fear of guerrilla
reprisals.
   The strike came a day after Favio Llerena, deputy to Fernandez,
said dozens of small-town mayors and farming hamlet officials across
the state resigned after receiving death threats by the rebel group.
   For two years, Huancayo and the surrounding Mantaro River valley,
an important mining and agricultural area, have been targets of the
Shining Path insurgency to topple Peru's elected government and
install a Marxist state.
   Officials say the violence is part of the guerrillas' overall
goal of weakening Peru by fomenting political and economic chaos to
pave the way for the rebels to seize power.
   ``The Mantaro Valley is practically taken over by the Shining
Path, and there seems to be no way to defend it,'' former Industry
Minister Guillermo Arteaga said over the weekend.
   Authorities declared a state of emergency throughout Junin a
month ago as attacks increased dramatically on villages, power
installations, railroads, bridges and large cooperative farms.
   Parts of eight states with more than half the nation's 21 million
people are under emergency measures that give the military
wide-ranging powers to police and govern. The capital, Lima, is
under the regulations.
   The government says the Shining Path insurgency has claimed more
than 12,000 lives and caused damage of more than $10 billion, four
times the amount of the nation's yearly exports.
</TEXT>
