<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PLO     12-20 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO,0658</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat Says Palestinian State May Come Within Two Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat said Tuesday he
believes an independent Palestinian state can be established within
two years in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   In comments on Austrian radio, Arafat expressed caution when
asked about creating a Palestinian government-in-exile.
   ``We have to think what the Israeli reaction will be,'' he said.
``Some of those people (designated members of a government-in-exile)
live in the occupied territories. How would Israel treat these
people? Would they arrest them, would they expel them?''
   Asked when a Palestinian state could be set up, Arafat replied,
``We think within two years ... perhaps something less.''
   At a news conference later, the leader of the Palestine
Liberation Organization reaffirmed his organization's commitment to
Middle East peace but vowed that the year-old Palestinian uprising
against Israel will continue.
   ``We have definite reports that the Israeli leadership is bent on
perpetrating yet more crimes and terrorist operations in order to
torpedo the process of peace,'' Arafat charged.
   He angrily rejected any questioning of the sincerity of the PLO
peace initiative, with leaders of his own organization threatening
sabotage.
   ``Whatever I have said in Geneva was done on the basis of a
resolution passed by the PLO Executive Committee as well as on the
basis of a resolution passed by the Palestine National Council _
which took place in a democratic atmosphere and by majority vote,''
he said.
   But a senior Palestinian source, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said PLO hardliners backed by Syria met in Damascus on
Tuesday to discuss ways to scuttle Arafat's initiative and oust him
from leadership.
   Mustafa el-Zibri, a member of the PLO governing body, on Monday
reflected a possible serious split in top ranks by calling Arafat's
recognition of Israel and renunciation of terrorism ``Arafat's
personal opinion.''
   Over the weekend, Salah Khalaf, second-in-command of Arafat's own
Fatah faction, declared, ``(President) Reagan may stop his
government's dialogue with the PLO now if he thinks he will be able
to stop our attacks against Israeli military targets.''
   The PLO is an umbrella for several Palestinian factions which
often feud among themselves. PLO factions have launched attacks on
Israel without Arafat's approval. Other groups do not belong to the
organization. Arafat has said he cannot guarantee that every
Palestinian group will refrain from terrorism.
   He spoke before leaving Vienna to take his campaign for an
international conference on the Middle East to Yugoslavia,
apparently hoping to win support from a leading ally in the
non-aligned movement.
   His European trip also included visits in the past week to East
Germany and Romania. The PLO says he also plans to go to Greece,
Italy, Spain and France.
   The visits follow Washington's recent reversal of its 13-year
boycott of the PLO.
   AT PLO headquarters in Tunis on Tuesday, executive committee
member Yasser Abd-Rabboo said indirect contacts with the U.S.
government began in March when Washington relayed conditions for the
PLO to meet before it would open formal talks.
   The two traded counterproposals for months, he said.
   They seemed a prelude to the intense diplomatic maneuvering
through Swedish intermediaries that led to the PLO's meeting U.S.
conditions last week and to the first talks with the organization.
   Abd-Rabboo took part in the first meeting Friday with U.S.
Ambassador Robert Pelletreau, Jr.
   He said messages relayed through Americans of Palestinian
heritage followed the failure of Secretary of State George Shultz to
find any notable Palestinians to speak with on a visit to Arab east
Jerusalem early this year.
   ``They gave signals that the American administration, after
Shultz had failed to find an alternative to the PLO ... was thinking
in a new way ... to deal with the PLO directly,'' he said.
</TEXT>
