<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Ouimet     12-20 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Ouimet,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canadian TV Pioneer Dead at 80</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alphonse Ouimet, a former president of the
Canadian Broadcasting Corp. who helped introduce television to
Canada 40 years ago, died on Tuesday. He was 80.
   Ouimet went to work for the CBC as an engineer when it was
founded 52 years ago. In 1958, he became president and held that
post for nine years.
   In the 1940s, Ouimet studied the operation of a new phenomenon _
television _ in the United States and Europe, and played a major
role in introducing it to Canadian audiences.
   In recent years, Ouimet spoke out against government funding cuts
for the CBC. When the corporation celebrated its 50th birthday in
1986, Ouimet said, ``Never has the CBC found itself as limited,
contested and even rejected, not by the public, but in government
circles.''
   After leaving the CBC, Ouimet headed a UNESCO conference on
satellite technology in broadcasting and served as president of
Telesat Canada from 1969 to 1980.
   No cause of death was announced. Funeral services will be held
Friday in Outremont, a Montreal suburb.
</TEXT>
