<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MyersonTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0671 12-20 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Myerson Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0671,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Asks to Re-Hear Sukhreet's Testimony at Myerson Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 2nd with jury ending deliberations for
second day without a verdict. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, `Miss Myerson
...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jury weighing the fate of former Miss America
Bess Myerson asked Tuesday to re-hear testimony by the prosecution's
chief witness at the divorce-fixing conspiracy trial.
   The panel, which got the case Monday, asked to have Sukhreet
Gabel's testimony about a secret June 1986 meeting with Miss Myerson
read back to them as well as U.S. District Judge John Keenan's
instructions on the law governing circumstantial evidence.
   The jurors then continued deliberating until they recessed for
the night at 9:30 p.m. after about 10 hours of work.
   Miss Myerson, once the city's cultural affairs commissioner, is
accused of giving a $19,000-a-year city job to Ms. Gabel to
influence her mother, a judge making interim rulings in the divorce
of Miss Myerson's lover, Carl ``Andy'' Capasso.
   The prosecution's case against Miss Myerson, 64, Capasso, 43, and
former state Supreme Court Justice Hortense Gabel, 76, consisted of
mainly circumstantial evidence because there were no witnesses to
the alleged bribe scheme.
   In instructing the jury, Keenan had said that circumstantial
evidence ``if believed, is of no less value than direct evidence.
But in either case, the essential elements of the crimes charged
must be established by the government beyond a reasonable doubt.''
   All three are charged with conspiracy, mail fraud and promoting
bribery. Miss Myerson also is charged with obstruction of justice
for allegedly trying to influence Ms. Gabel's grand jury testimony.
   According to Ms. Gabel, her former boss came unannounced to her
apartment building in June 1986, while the grand jury was
investigating her hiring.
   Ms. Gabel testified that Miss Myerson told her during a nighttime
walk around the block that ``you could be dangerous'' and that she
should ``keep your mouth shut.''
   Ms. Myerson faces a maximum of 30 years in prison and $513,000 in
fines if convicted on all counts. Her co-defendants face up to 25
years and $263,000 in fines if convicted.
</TEXT>
