<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NewZealand     12-20 0120</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Zealand,0123</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lange Dafeats Rival in Leadership Challenge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister David Lange easily
survived a challenge to his Labor Party leadership on Wednesday,
defeating former Finance Minister Roger Douglas in a 38-15 party
room vote.
   ``This ballot is actually no big deal,'' Lange told reporters
after he won, but Douglas threatened a three-month campaign to
undermine the government.
   ``I am sad about that,'' said Lange, who fired Douglas from his
Cabinet last week following a disagreement over the pace of economic
change in the island nation of 3.5 million people.
   Lange's Labor government, now in its second three-year term,
trails the opposition National Party in public opinion polls.
Elections are due in 1990.
