<DOCNO> AP881220-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 2252EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RefundRap     12-20 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Refund Rap,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Throws Out Man's Conviction For Razor Return</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Indiana Supreme Court on Tuesday threw
out the convictions of a habitual offender who was sentenced to 32
years in prison after he tried to get a refund for an electric razor
without a receipt.
   The court, in a 4-1 decision, struck down the attempted theft and
habitual criminal convictions of Richard Allen Smith of Indianapolis
and ordered Smith discharged from Indiana State Prison.
   Smith, 49, was sentenced to two years in prison in 1985 for
attempting to get a refund for a $42.96 Remington razor at three
Indiana stores. Under the state's habitual offender law, a fixed
term of 30 years was added to the sentence because of Smith's
earlier convictions on auto banditry and drug charges.
   Prosecutors argued at his Circuit Court trial that Smith
attempted ``to exert unauthorized control'' over one store's profit
margin by creating the false impression he had purchased the razor
there.
   However, the Supreme Court concluded that in order to prove Smith
was trying to create a false impression, the state needed to prove
Smith hadn't purchased the razor at the store. There was no evidence
to demonstrate where the razor was purchased, the court said.
   ``Without that crucial element of proof, every citizen engaging
in a simple refund transaction would risk criminal penalties,''
Chief Justice Randall T. Shepard wrote for the court. ``Some
citizens such as those seeking to return gifts simply do not know
where the item was originally purchased.''
   Court records show that in November 1978, Smith took the razor to
a Hook's Drug store in Mooresville and later to a Hook's in
Martinsville to get a refund. The package had a Hook's price tag on
it, but employees refused to give Smith a refund because of a store
policy requiring receipts for returned merchandise.
   He then went to a Danner's store in Martinsville and presented
the razor, without a price tag, for a refund. Hook's employees,
suspicious about Smith's behavior, had alerted Danner's employees of
his earlier attempts to get a refund.
   Employees at the Danner's store called police when Smith showed
up and stalled until police arrived to arrest Smith, court records
show. Danner's also would have denied a refund under its no-receipt,
no-refund policy.
   The long gap between his arrest and final sentencing occurred
because Smith left the courtroom during his trial and remained at
large for four years, according to court records.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881220-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 2246EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0710 12-20 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0710,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviet-Japanese Talks on Territorial Issue Break Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK2</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout with Shevardnadze's departing statement and
departure, NO PICKUP</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By IRENE M. KUNII</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan and the Soviet Union will continue efforts to
negotiate a formal end to their World War II hostilities, Soviet
Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze said Wednesday, a day after
territorial talks broke down.
   Japanese officials indicated that all hope of a compromise
vanished in Tuesday's negotiations about the Kuril Islands north of
Japan, which Japan claims. Soviet troops occupied them in the last
days of World War II, and they have remained the major roadblock to
an official end to hostilities.
   However, Shevardnadze said Wednesday the two sides will pick up
where they left off in 1973 to negotiate a peace treaty officially
ending the war.
   Shevardnadze, speaking to a news conference shortly before
departing for the Philippines, said his talks with Japanese leaders
had brought a ``very important'' agreement on a mechanism and rough
schedule of meetings to deal with thorny issues now over four
decades old.
   The Soviet official gave a more positive assessment of his two
days of talks with Japanese Foreign Minister Sousuke Uno than
Japanese officials gave the night before. One Japanese official
described the talks as ``heated'' and said neither side had changed
its position on the territorial dispute.
   Uno was to give a news conference later Wednesday after
Shevardnadze's departure and a joint communique was to be released
then.
   Shevardnadze agreed that no major progress was achieved. But he
cited progress in agreements on further meetings leading to a
possible summit between Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and
Japanese Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita.
   He also said the negotiations had won ``a victory for reason, for
balance of interests, and for a realistic policy.''
   ``We have obtained a degree of mutual understanding that allows
us to speak of a new chapter in Japan-Soviet relations,'' he said,
speaking in Russian that was translated into English.
   The Kiril dispute has also blocked progress in diplomatic and
economic matters between the two countries. On Tuesday, the Japanese
brushed off Soviet overtures for economic cooperation, the Kyodo
News Service reported.
   The talks in Tokyo were the first between foreign ministers in
nearly three years.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Seiichi Kondo said little progress was
achieved in the discussions, which he described as heated. ``Neither
side has shown concessions, so the positions are still far apart,''
he said.
   Also Tuesday, Japan refused to conclude two agreements, one on
bilateral investment guarantees and another on trade and economic
cooperation, the agency said, quoting government sources it did not
name.
   The ministers signed agreements on cultural exchanges and
protection of 287 species of migratory birds.
   Earlier Tuesday, Shevardnadze delivered a letter from Gorbachev
to Takeshita. The newspaper Asahi said Gorbachev invited Takeshita
to Moscow and said he would like to visit Japan.
   Shevardnadze said Wednesday the tentative agenda for a
Japan-Soviet summit would include agreements to protect investment,
principles of economic cooperation and establishment of banking
offices, as well as treaty issues and other matters.
   Shevardnadze said Moscow had established trade and other
unofficial relations with South Korea, but would not establish
governmental relations with Seoul. The Soviets are North Korea's
ally, and Moscow's growing ties with Seoul have tended to further
isolate Pyongyang.
   The Soviet foreign minister left for the Philippines, from where
he is scheduled to travel to North Korea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
