<2ND_LINE>PM-Religion Roundup, Adv 23,0602</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Fri PMs Dec. 23, or thereafter</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christmas services provide an opportunity to draw
alienated Catholics back into regular worship, but priests tend to
``ridicule and demean'' them for attending so infrequently, says the
Rev. Andrew Greeley.
   Writing in U.S. Catholic, published by the Claretian Fathers, the
noted priest-sociologist-novelist says:
   ``One of the more twisted and sick kinks in clerical culture is
the propensity to ridicule and demean the `Christmas Catholics' and,
even when priests are on their best behavior, to patronize them.''
   Greeley says ``Christmas Catholics,'' who show up only on such
holidays, often are alienated from the church, having been hurt or
confused by it, and they ``need to know there's room for them in the
inn, too.''
   He adds, ``Welcoming the alienated and inviting them to come home
and stay home permanently is surely far more in the spirit of
Christmas than brutalizing them again.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the busy shopping days before Christmas,
members of Pax Christi have been handing out flyers warning shoppers
that ``war'' toys and games may be damaging to children.
   Daniel Crews, a member the Roman Catholic organization that seeks
to promote a more just and peaceful world, says sales of war toys
has increased 300 percent in the last six years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American ``Pastors for Peace''
convoy of trucks and humanitarian aid for Nicaraguans was expected
to reach the capital of Managua in time to celebrate Christmas.
   About 46 persons, Protestants and Roman Catholic, most of them
pastors from various parts of the country, driving about 20 trucks,
converged here last week before heading through Mexico.
   The trucks range from a 10-ton, 22-foot rig to pickups, some of
them loaded with medical supplies, rice, typewriters and other
materials for the war-damaged country.
   The project is sponsored by the Interreligious Foundation for
Community Organization. Spokesmen said the trucks are particularly
needed to get crops to market and provide transportation to medical
facilities.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The traditional Christmas celebration in
Bethlehem where Christ was born has been canceled by the town
government because of the yearlong uprising of Palestinians against
Israeli rule.
   ``We don't see any reasons to celebrate Christmas,'' Mayor Hanna
Nasser told U.S. National Catholic News service. Noting that the
usually brightly lit Manger Square will remain dark, Nasser added,
``We have to show concern for our dead and for our detainees.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A survey finds that 36 of nearly 300 social
ministries of the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America have
special programs for people with AIDS.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American churches have mobilized relief efforts
to help the stricken people of Armenia, devastated by an earthquake.
   Catholic Relief Services authorized an immediate grant of
$100,000, while Church World Service, relief arm of the
Protestant-Eastern Orthodox National Council of Churches,
coordinated shipment of $1 million worth of medical supplies,
blankets and winter clothing.
   CWS dispatched a four-member team to the stricken region. Member
denominations chipped into the operation, including an initial
grants of $20,000 by United Methodists and $25,000 by the Christian
Reformed Church.
   Lutheran World Relief sent $25,000, Greek Orthodoxy $10,000 and
the Catholic Medical Mission Board $27,116 worth of medicines.
   The Southern Baptist Foreign Mission Board offered $20,000 for
medicines, warm clothing and housing and sent $10,000 in cash
through Soviet Baptist channels.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Dec. 23.</NOTE>
