<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-DeadSolidPerfect ADV21   12-20 0845</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Dead Solid Perfect, ADV 21,0858</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs, Dec. 21</NOTE>
<HEAD>HBO's `Dead Solid Perfect' a Solid Good Movie</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Your football team punted the playoffs, relatives
are descending for the holidays and network TV is cluttered with
junk.
   'Tis the season to give thanks that you paid your cable bill. For
HBO has a nice little out-of-season movie this month, ``Dead Solid
Perfect,'' an adaptation of Dan Jenkins' novel of the same name
about life on the links. What better time of year to be delivered
from gray winter landscapes to the land of greens, fairways,
sandtraps and perpetual short sleeves?
   ``Dead Solid Perfect'' is dead solid funny and a nice little love
story to boot. It premiered last week, but you can still catch it
tonight, Friday and next Tuesday.
   Kenny Lee (Randy Quaid) is a diamond-in-the-rough golfer,
hustling bets on the side so he can afford to get to the next
tournament.
   Enter Hubert ``Bad Hair'' Wimberly (Jack Warden), a hustler with
more money than he knows what to do with, but a nasty slice he'll
never be able to buy off. So he buys Kenny, becoming his sponsor on
the tour.
   Exit Beverly (Kathryn Harrold), Kenny's intelligent wife, tired
of hanging out with jerks like Bad Hair and dragging herself around
the country to watch Kenny cuss and sling golf clubs in disgust.
   Forget ``Caddyshack.'' This is the definitive golf movie of the
'80s. Director Bobby Roth, who co-wrote the screenplay with Jenkins,
does for the links what Martin Scorsese did for pool in ``The Color
of Money.'' Roth and Jenkins successfully teamed on ``Baja
Oklahoma'' for HBO earlier this year.
   The music is by Tangerine Dream, and the theme song is sung by
Billy Vera.
   Larry Riley co-stars as Spec, Kenny's caddy, a talented golfer
himself who stays in the background rather than challenge the racism
of the sponsorship game. At one point, as Kenny is preparing for a
big tournament, Spec warns Bad Hair, ``Give him one word of advice,
and I'll burn down your mansion and marry your daughter.''
   Brett Cullen plays Kenny's friend, Donny Smithern, a successful
young pro who gets recognized in restaurants, cheats on his good ol'
gal wife (DeLane Matthews) and waxes phony pious in TV interviews.
   Jenkins is one of a handful of male authors around who can write
realistic women. He gives his female characters a sense of humor
without making them just sound like men. ``Good ol' Donny,'' Beverly
sneers at one point, ``he'll always be there when he needs you.''
   After Beverly leaves Kenny, he takes up with Janie (Corinne
Bohrer), a bimbo savant who chucks her job as a bartender to
accompany him on the tour. At first, he plays well, and it's party
time. But Kenny warns Janie during an R-rated romp in their hotel
room. ``It's not always this fun. Sometimes I play bad.'' ``So do
I,'' Janie says.
   Kenny starts playing really badly after he gets shook up by
running into Beverly and a new beau at a restaurant. Janie gamely
tries to trade insults with Beverly and spews a blue streak.
Observes Beverly, ``Why, you didn't tell me she talked like Princess
Di.''
   Eventually, the film veers off into a standard-issue plotline
about a tumor and Kenny's big show-down with Donny on the 18th hole
of the U.S. Open. But if the story is predictable, it's also
satisfying, because Jenkins' characters are immensely likable, and
Roth's direction is, like Kenny's play _ for those brief shining
moments just dead solid perfect.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   BOUNCING `BABY BOOM' _ Just when ``Baby Boom'' started turning
into a pretty decent little show about upscale working women, NBC
announced the series was going on hiatus. ``Baby Boom'' will remain
in production, but is leaving the schedule until further notice. NBC
did like the new shows ``Dear John,'' ``Empty Nest,'' ``Day by
Day,'' ``In the Heat of the Night'' and ``Midnight Caller'' enough,
however, to give them full-season orders. A decision about the fate
of low-rated ``Tattinger's'' is expected soon. The show has had
trouble finding a niche, but it will no doubt get another chance,
since it is made by the producers of NBC's critically acclaimed
ex-series ``St. Elsewhere.'' According to NBC, the network and
producers are considering options that include shortening
``Tattinger's'' from an hour to a half-hour. ...
   RELIEF STILL NEEDED _ Billy Crystal, Whoopi Goldberg and Robin
Williams are teaming up for a third ``Comic Relief'' on HBO next
March. HBO says the two previous ``Comic Relief'' benefits combined
to raise $4.7 million to aid the homeless. Once again, an 800 number
will enable viewers to contribute. ...
   RESETTING THEIR ALARM CLOCKS _ Robb Weller, host of ABC's
``Home'' information show, will fill in for vacationing Charlie
Gibson on ``Good Morning America'' next week. Gibson will also be
out the week of Jan. 9, and sitting in will be ``Today'' veteran Joe
Garagiola.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, Dec. 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
