<1ST_LINE>a i AM-ReawakenedPeronists Adv26   12-20 1181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reawakened Peronists, Adv 26,1215</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs Dec. 26 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Peronists on the Move Again in Argentina</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Peronist Party, implanted in
Argentina as the voice of the workers and the poor by Juan D. Peron
and his wife Eva four decades ago, is in a resurgence it hopes will
bring victory in presidential elections set for May.
   It has been out of power for 12 years.
   Virtually every poll gives Peronist Carlos Saul Menem, a colorful
provincial governor, a commanding lead over the candidate of the
governing Radical Civic Union, Eduardo Angeloz.
   Provincial and congressional elections last year reversed
Peronist setbacks in 1983, when civilian government was restored
after nearly eight years of military dictatorship during which
Peronist politicians, including Menem, were jailed, Peronist
teachers were dismissed from universities and labor leaders were
arrested and executed.
   In September 1987, Peronist candidates swept 17 of the country's
22 provinces, including Buenos Aires, the biggest. The party's
inroads in the House of Deputies eliminated the Radical's majority.
   ``In 1983, it wasn't Alfonsin against Luder, it was the Radicals
against the Peronists,'' losing candidate Italo Argentino Luder said
in an interview, referring to Raul Alfonsin. Alfonsin swamped Luder,
52 percent to 40 in the balloting for president in post-military
Argentina.
   ``Now, it is totally different,'' the 71-year-old Luder said.
``The economy is the biggest theme _ inflation, foreign debt,
growth, employment, purchasing power ... (and) the Radicals have
totally failed in government.''
   Pollster Manuel Mora y Araujo's surveys consistently give Menem
twice as big a share of the vote as Angeloz, though he notes that
undecideds have crept up to 35 percent.
   ``You can't say (Menem's) victory is beyond doubt, but he's
definitely ahead,'' the pollster said.
   Peron founded the party following his victory in the elections of
1946, the most honest and widely attended in two decades.
   An army colonel at the time, Peron later was promoted by Congress
to general. With his wildly popular and politically astute wife Eva
at his side and sometimes acting on her own, Peron won the support
of workers disenfranchised by previous conservative governments.
   Peron industrialized an agricultural economy based on grain and
beef, nationalized industries, promoted such legislation as
collective bargaining and pensions, vastly extended public education
and health services, and gave women the right to vote.
   Peron established a dictatorship that remained popular so long as
Eva _ Evita, as she was affectionately known _ was around. Popular
support began to diminish after her death of cancer in 1952 and with
the economy in trouble in 1955 the military overthrew Peron and sent
him into exile in Spain.
   He made a triumphal return in 1971 and was elected president
again in 1973, with his new wife, Isabel, as his vice president. She
took the presidency upon Peron's death in 1974 only to be ousted by
the military two years later.
   While the Perons themselves have had their ups and downs, the
party has generally maintained its base of organized labor and the
poor.
   The 4-million-member General Workers Confederation, the chief
labor union, ``was born, is and will always be Peronist,'' the
53-year-old Menem told a recent rally.
   But party leaders now are trying to appeal to the middle class,
which they see as key to the 50 percent of the vote required by
Argentine law to win the election outright and avoid a runoff in the
Electoral College.
   Luder, an attorney who is one of Menem's advisers, says appealing
to the middle class is a natural move.
   ``Peronism created this country as we know it today,'' he said.
``The sons and grandsons of the workers of 1946 today are
businessmen, teachers, professionals.''
   Argentines in those stations, however, tend to support the
Radical Civic Union or the conservative Union of the Democratic
Center of Alvaro Alsogaray, a former economy minister and former
U.S. ambassador.
   Today's Peronists are finding their overtures frustrated by the
party's image of violence, demagoguery and administrative
incompetence, a public perception Menem calls his party's ``black
legend.''
   Even triple-digit inflation, rising unemployment, stagnant growth
and three military insurrections under President Alfonsin cannot
shake the recollections of better-off Argentines that some of the
country's economic and political low points occurred under Peronist
governments.
   Peron squandered huge gold reserves built up during World War II,
crowded out private business by expanding the state's role in the
economy, made public employment conditional on party membership,
tolerated corruption and thuggery against his opponents, closed down
newspapers, antagonized the Roman Catholic Church.
   In the final months before Isabel Peron was ousted by the
military in 1976, Argentina was torn by murderous street violence,
out-of-control inflation and paralyzing strikes.
   ``Peronist governments have never understood economics,'' said
Juan Balassoni, a medical products importer. ``It's very possible he
(Menem) would return control to the unions, so the unions would
govern, not the government.''
   A well-dressed, middle-aged woman at a rally for Alsogaray in a
downtown sports stadium said, ``If Menem wins, the country will
slide backwards, despite his best intentions. ... I favor shrinking
the size of the state, selling state companies. The Peronists would
never sell state companies.''
   National elections set for May 14 may hang in the balance of
opinions like theirs. Votes in the Electoral College are tied to the
popular ballot. If Menem fails to win at least 50 percent, Alsogaray
could determine the election by throwing his support to Angeloz.
   Menem at times seems to hurt his own cause by endorsing ideas
that appear contradictory and are never fully explained.
   Although Argentina is a country notorious for tax evasion, Menem
has said he would curtail the fiscal deficit not by cutting back
state employment or selling off money-losing state enterprises, but
by cutting tax rates in the hope that would spur compliance and
generate additional revenue.
   Under his program, workers would receive big wage increases, but
he has not fully explained where the money would come from.
   Menem's allies don't always help.
   While he tries to project an image of moderation and
statesmanship, Mrs. Peron in November dredged up unhappy memories by
endorsing an amnesty for the former military chiefs who directed the
so-called ``dirty war'' against subversives and the leftist
Montonero urban guerrillas in the 1970s.
   At least 8,900 Argentines were arrested and ``disappeared''
during that campaign. Forced to take a position on that sensitive
issue, Menem said he opposed an amnesty.
   In another case, the leader of a leftist Peronist splinter group,
Pablo Unamuno, publicly stated that Menem would pardon Mario
Firmenich, the Montonero leader who is in prison for murder,
extortion and kidnapping. An angry Menem denied he planned any such
pardon and suspended Unamuno from the party.
   The Radicals have seized upon such rifts and gaffes to fan
passions and fears that are never far from the surface in this
politically polarized country.
   ``Violence is part of their history,'' said Angeloz's press
secretary, Oscar Fernandez Soares. ``The Peronist Party still has
violent elements in its structure.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon AMs Dec. 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
