<DOCNO> AP881220-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 1316EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-WorldSymposium Adv01-3Takes   12-20 1170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-World Symposium, Adv 01-3 Takes,1200</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Jan. 1, or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WORLD SYMPOSIUM '89 _ What Lies Ahead Abroad for George Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, an accompanying story is BC-Symposium-Neighbors, b0540</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Almost from the minute he takes the presidential oath Jan. 20,
George Bush will face a raft of fast-developing foreign policy
issues in a world that has changed radically from the one Ronald
Reagan found eight years before.
   Most immediately pressing, perhaps, is the Middle East, where the
United States could be on the verge of its first major involvement
in a peace effort since Henry A. Kissinger's shuttle diplomacy of
the 1970s.
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev's changing Soviet Union and more U.S.-Soviet
arms agreements also are likely items on the agenda for the early
days of the Bush presidency.
   Then there is China and its new contacts with Moscow; Europe,
where the East is at a crossroads, and the West looks with less
trepidation toward the Soviet bloc; Latin America, with its debt and
economic stagnation; Africa, where South African apartheid remains a
troublesome and delicate issue for the White House; and Asia, where
burgeoning economies still pour goods into Main Street, U.S.A.
   Even the South Pacific, the place people dream of for tranquil
escape, has become a piece in the world chess game.
   Each year at this time, The Associated Press asks its
correspondents in strategic areas of the world to look ahead to what
Americans can expect abroad in the new year.
   For 1989, they were asked to look ahead to what President Bush
can expect in his first year in office.
   These are their reports:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MIDDLE EAST</HEAD>
<HEAD>BY ED BLANCHE</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush inherits a rapidly changing
climate in the Middle East, where a U.S. dialogue with the PLO holds
the seeds of a possible breakthrough in settling the Arab-Israeli
conflict.
   The Reagan administration's decision Dec. 14 to talk to the
Palestine Liberation Organization after its chairman, Yasser Arafat,
said the PLO recognized Israel's right to exist and renounced
terrorism, will give Bush the opportunity to make a significant
impact on the long-stalled peace process.
   Whatever the outcome of the U.S.-PLO dialogue, it will put
pressure on Israel, appalled at the U.S. decision, to negotiate with
the PLO on the creation of a Palestinian state declared in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip by the PLO's Parliament-in-exile.
   With Israel increasingly isolated, Bush could be in a position to
encourage Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir to be more flexible. But
there will likely be hard bargaining amid Arab, Soviet and European
pressure for an international peace conference attended by the PLO.
   Bush will also find new possibilities for resuming relations with
Iran under the Islamic republic's developing open-door policy of
improving its ties with the rest of the world, ending nine years of
political isolation.
   That could improve the prospects of freeing Western hostages in
Lebanon. Most of the 16 foreigners, including nine Americans, are
held by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem extremists.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SOVIET UNION</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In less than four years, Mikhail S. Gorbachev has
painted over the image of the Soviet Union as a boastful,
missile-wielding totalitarian state with a portrait of a hopeful
giant struggling to pull itself up by the bootstraps and join the
community of peaceful nations.
   But the Soviet Union still has those missiles, and if President
Bush is to continue a period of easing world tensions, he must find
some way to break the deadlock that prevented his predecessor from
signing an agreement with Gorbachev to slash strategic arsenals in
half.
   The initial roadblock remains President Reagan's ``Star Wars''
program to develop a space-based defense against missile attack.
Gorbachev insists such a program only opens a new, dangerous arena
for the arms race and makes reductions in offensive weapons
impossible. Beyond that lie unresolved questions about how the two
sides can fairly balance reductions in their inherently different
land, sea and air weapons systems.
   Gorbachev is busy not only trying to restructure the economy and
way of thinking in his own country, but he also is trying to break
down East-West barriers and develop new trade relationships
throughout the world. The United States has moved more slowly than
some nations in Asia and Western Europe to encourage an end to
Soviet isolation and support development of a potentially powerful
new Soviet market.
   Some Westerners have suggested the Kremlin's efforts to improve
relations, particularly with West Germany, could weaken U.S. ties to
its NATO partners as Gorbachev works to build what he calls a
``common European home.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>EASTERN EUROPE</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In Eastern Europe, George Bush
faces a delicate balancing act between Communist authorities opening
up to reform and the increasingly vocal and active independent
groups who want the West to insist on more human rights.
   As in the Soviet Union, Communist governments in Hungary, Poland,
Czechoslovakia and Bulgaria are realizing they must open up to
economic and perhaps political reform in order to modernize outmoded
industry and keep consumer demands satisfied.
   East Germany and Romania, for the time being, have rejected any
need for the change their allies have embraced with varying degrees
of enthusiasm.
   But new laws allowing more private and foreign investment in East
bloc economies will not boost output unless the West agrees to make
large loans and import or sell its advanced technology.
   Some West European leaders have talked of a kind of ``Marshall
Plan'' to help out Eastern Europe, where massive investment would be
needed to provide modern housing and industry and clean up the
heavily polluted environment.
   But independent groups encouraged by President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's reforms in the Soviet Union are also placing increasing
demands for genuine democracy.
   U.S. trade with Eastern Europe traditionally has been small. But
Bush will have a voice in determining the stand of allies like West
Germany, with significant business activities in the East, as they
try to juggle the demands of Communists for more money and activists
for a firm stand on human rights.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WESTERN EUROPE</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush will find a Western
Europe preoccupied with contentious arms control talks, efforts to
unify its market and a continuing flirtation with Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Bush will likely meet in the spring with West European leaders at
a summit of the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization to
discuss pressing issues.
   By that time, the NATO allies may well have begun negotiations _
called the Conventional Stability Talks _ with the seven Warsaw Pact
nations on reducing conventional arms in Europe.
   The allies recently unveiled their joint position, which calls
for substantial reductions in the East bloc's tanks, artillery and
other forces, surpassing the unilateral cuts promised by Gorbachev
in a surprise announcement at the United Nations in New York in
early December. NATO contends the Warsaw Pact holds a massive
superiority in such weapons.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
