<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Symposium-Neighbors Adv01   12-20 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Symposium-Neighbors, Adv 01,0576</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sun Jan. 1 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WORLD SYMPOSIUM '89 _ Canada and Mexico: The People Next Door</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-World Symposium, b0537-b0539</HEAD>
<HEAD>NEIGHBOR CANADA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada will be looking for reassurance from
President Bush that it is trusted as an ally and valued as the
United States' No. 1 trading partner.
   A bruising campaign that gave Prime Minister Brian Mulroney his
second consecutive majority government put the spotlight on Canadian
concerns that the country is taken for granted, ignored or
overshadowed in the United States.
   The victory for Mulroney's Progressive Conservative Party cleared
the way for the free trade agreement with the United States to
proceed, but it is a long-term pact that will be phased in over 10
years.
   Canadians will be looking for some signs that their willingness
to cooperate with Washington can produce some tangible results in an
easing of the trade squabbles still likely to occur in aspects
uncovered by the agreement.
   And, with economic growth expected to slow down in both
countries, great attention will be paid here to any plant closings
attributed to the new trade pact.
   In other issues, Canada will be looking to Bush to take promised
steps to cut down sulphur dioxide emissions blamed in large part for
producing the acid rain that devastates Canadian aquatic life in
sensitive lakes and streams.
   The private Canadian Coalition on Acid Rain found Bush's stand on
acid rain an improvement over the Reagan administration's record but
``weaker and vaguer'' than Michael Dukakis'.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NEIGHBOR MEXICO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico and the United States face as many
problems as ever, but under the presidencies of George Bush in
Washington and Carlos Salinas de Gortari in Mexico City their
historically prickly relationship will probably improve.
   Prime among problems in the coming months will be Mexico's
foreign debt, now $102 billion. Salinas says the $13 billion annual
payments should be reduced because they aren't leaving enough money
for economic growth.
   Salinas, inaugurated Dec. 1, is expected to tell bankers in 1989
that stifling growth is counterproductive in the long run.
   Renewing growth is vital for Salinas, because the average
Mexican's standard of living has suffered badly during years of
austerity. Salinas won a disputed election and better conditions
would strengthen his mandate.
   Bush has given Salinas a sympathetic ear, and the two appeared to
hit it off when they met in November. A recent $3.5 billion U.S.
loan offer was seen as a vote of confidence. Salinas is a hard-nosed
negotiator, but he is unlikely to let pride get in the way of
practical solutions.
   Other issues:
   _Trade: Mexico fears protectionist sentiment will cut access to
U.S. markets, restricting growth opportunities. A U.S. recession
would also hurt Mexico if exports went down.
   _Migration: Mexico resents the way migrants looking for jobs in
the United States are treated, since they fill an apparent need.
Salinas argues that growth is a key here too, because more jobs in
Mexico would reduce migration.
   _Drugs: Salinas has promised a harder fight against drug
trafficking, but expects the United States to crack down on demand.
   _Central America: Mexicans are hopeful the new administration
will focus less on an anti-communist crusade in Central America,
which was very unpopular here.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sun Jan. 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881220-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 1323EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-BroadwayTix Adv24-25   12-20 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Broadway Tix, Adv 24-25,0717</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 24</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv 25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Dec 24-25 and thereafter</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are Broadway's new and current shows. Ticket
supply as of Dec. 23 is indicated as Difficult or Available. Credit
card holders can order tickets by phone or by calling Telecharge,
Teletron or Ticketron.
   Telecharge's number is 212-239-6200 unless otherwise indicated.
Teletron's umber is 212-246-0102. Ticketron is 212-399-4444.
   For 24-hour information on theater, dance and music performances,
call the Theater Development Fund's New York City@On
Stage, 212-587-1111.
   When calling theaters directly, use New York area code 212.
Advance inquiries should be made, as ticket availability is subject
to change.
   _ ``A Chorus Line,'' the longest-running musical in Broadway
history, is about the hard life and struggles of chorus-line
members. Shubert, 239-6200, same number as Telecharge. Ticketron.
Available.
   _ ``Ain't Misbehavin','' Patti Austin stars in a revival of the
Fats Waller musical revue. Ambassador, 239-6200, same number as
Telecharge. Ticketron. Available.
   _ ``Anything Goes,'' a revival by the Lincoln Center Theater of
the 1934 Cole Porter musical. Vivian Beaumont, 239-6200, same number
as Telecharge. Ticketron. Difficult.
   _ ``Cats,'' musical based on T.S. Eliot's cat poems, music by
Andrew Lloyd Webber of ``Evita'' fame. Winter Garden, 239-6200, same
number as Telecharge. Ticketron. Available.
   _ ``Checkmates,'' a comedy by Ron Milner about contrasting
couples and starring Paul Winfield, Ruby Dee, Denzel Washington and
Marsha Jackson. 46th Street, 221-1211. Teletron. Available.
   _ ``42nd Street,'' hit remake of the 1930s movie-musical classic.
St. James, 398-0280. Teletron. Ticketron. Closes Jan. 8. Available.
   _ ``Into the Woods,'' a Stephen Sondheim musical about several
fairy tale characters and what takes place after ``happily ever
after.'' Martin Beck, 246-6363. Teletron. Ticketron. Available.
   _ ``Jackie Mason's The World According to Me,'' the popular
comedian in a return engagement of his one-man show. Brooks
Atkinson, 719-4099. Teletron. Closes Dec. 31. Available.
   _ ``Legs Diamond,'' Peter Allen stars in a musical about the
big-time New York gangster. Mark Hellinger, 757-7064. Teletron. Now
in previews, opens Dec. 26. Available.
   _ ``Les Miserables,'' a lavish musical retelling of the epic
Victor Hugo novel. Broadway, 239-6200, same number as Telecharge.
Ticketron. Difficult.
   _ ``M. Butterfly,'' David Dukes stars in a play by David Henry
Hwang about the love affair between a French diplomat and a Chinese
opera star. Winner of the 1988 Tony Award as best play. Eugene
O'Neill, 246-0220. Teletron. Ticketron. Difficult.
   _ ``Me and My Girl,'' Jim Dale stars in the 1930s English musical
hit about a cockney scamp making it big in high society. Marquis,
382-0100. Teletron. Ticketron. Available.
   _ ``Oh! Calcutta!,'' long-running nudie musical that spoofs sex
and swinging and such. Edison, 302-2302. Available.
   _ ``Our Town,'' a revival by the Lincoln Center Theater of the
Thornton Wilder classic. Spalding Gray plays the stage manager.
Lyceum, 239-6200, same number as Telecharge. Limited engagement
through Jan. 15. Available.
   _ ``Romance Romance,'' two one-act musicals about the vagaries of
love. Barry Williams, formerly of ``The Brady Bunch,'' and Alison
Fraser star. Helen Hayes, 944-9450. Teletron. Available.
