<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0564</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 2{ months of just saying ``no,''
Pillsbury Co. finally had no choice but to agree to a sweetened
$5.68 billion takeover bid from Britain's Grand Metropolitan PLC,
securities analysts said.
   Pillsbury, a giant food and restaurant company, agreed to the
takeover Sunday, two days after its takeover defenses suffered major
legal setbacks.
   Grand Met will purchase all outstanding shares of Pillsbury
common stock for $66 a share in cash, $3 higher than Grand Met's
previous best offer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. fits Grand Metropolitan PLC's
international expansion strategy, even though some Grand Met
shareholders have been concerned that Pillsbury was an ailing target
that nobody else apparently wanted, analysts said.
   ``Pillsbury represents a great deal for (Grand Met), even at the
higher price,'' Andrew Buchanan, an analyst with Hoare Govett Ltd.,
said Monday.
   Pillsbury fits in well with Grand Met's strategy of focusing on
foods, liquor and retailing and expanding those businesses
worldwide, the analysts said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friendly acquisitions of U.S. companies by
foreign investors are on the rise, but hostile takeovers by
foreigners still are rare, according to a congressional report.
   The General Accounting Office said Monday that foreign
acquisitions as a share of all takeovers has increased from 6
percent in 1984 to 9 percent last year and 13 percent in the first
half of this year.
   However, of the 1,281 foreign takeovers during the 4{-year
period, only 17 were hostile, or resisted by the target company's
board of directors, the GAO said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British owner-to-be of Burger King is expected
to beef up the chain's standing in the sizzling U.S. fast-food
competition, but rivals aren't conceding anything yet, franchisees
and analysts say.
   ``They've been almost rudderless. I see these guys from England
coming in and ending (Burger King's) state of confusion,'' John P.
Uphoff, an analyst with Raymond James & Associates in St.
Petersburg, Fla., said Monday.
   Grand Met executives have indicated they will move quickly to
improve Burger King, which has been criticized by franchise owners
and other industry figures as the company slipped further behind
kingpin McDonald's.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has approved the sale of
Eastern Airlines' Northeastern shuttle service to real estate
developer Donald Trump, a $365 million deal that labor leaders had
challenged as a union-busting effort.
   The transaction approved Monday still must be reviewed by the
Department of Transportation, which must affirm that Trump can
operate the shuttle safely and manage it properly.
   The flamboyant Trump announced his agreement to purchase the
shuttle for cash on Oct. 12, saying he would turn the shuttle, which
makes hourly flights between Boston, New York and Washington, into
``an absolute diamond.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover strategist Carl Icahn has purchased
another 1 million shares of Texaco Inc., raising his stake to 16.22
percent of the third-largest U.S. oil company, Icahn has disclosed.
   In a routine filing Monday with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, Icahn also included a letter addressed to Texaco
President James Kinnear in which Icahn denied rumors of improperly
acting in concert with an unidentified investor to acquire Texaco
stock.
   Icahn is Texaco's largest single shareholder.
</TEXT>
