<DOCNO> AP881220-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 0035EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TreasuryBills     12-20 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Bills,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>3-Month T-Bills Reach 8.14 Percent in Latest Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities rose in the government's latest auction to the highest
level in more than 3{ years.
   The Treasury Department sold $7.2 billion in three-month bills at
an average discount rate of 8.14 percent on Monday, up from 7.98
percent last week. Another $7.2 billion was sold in six-month bills
at an average discount rate of 8.29 percent, up from 8.21 percent
last week.
   The rates were the highest since three-month bills sold for 8.18
percent on April 1, 1985 and six-month bills averaged 8.56 on April
8, 1985.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 8.43 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for
$9,794.20 and and 8.77 percent for six-month bills selling for
$9,580.90.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yild for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index for
making changes in adjustable rate home mortgages, rose to 9.10
percent last week after averaging 8.89 percent the week before.
</TEXT>
