<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Drexel     12-20 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drexel,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drexel Chief Says Talks Have Reached Difficult Stage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Settlement talks between the government and
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. over as yet unfiled securities fraud
charges have reached a difficult stage, the investment firm's chief
executive has told employees.
   Drexel Chief Executive Frederick Joseph also said Monday the
investment firm couldn't accept the terms presented to it, sources
familiar with the remarks said. The sources, who spoke on condition
they not be identified, said the tone of the statement suggested an
indictment had become more likely.
   Joseph made his remarks over a public-address system, and they
were broadcast to Drexel branches nationwide.
   The sources paraphrased Joseph as saying, ``Not at this point
does a settlement make sense.''
   The nation's fifth-largest securities firm has been the subject
of an intense investigation for more than two years stemming from
its involvement with Ivan F. Boesky, the one-time speculator now
serving a 3-year prison term for the biggest insider trading fraud
in U.S. history.
   Drexel repeatedly has denied any wrongdoing but has been
negotiating with the Manhattan U.S. attorney's office over the past
two months in an effort to avoid an indictment for racketeering and
securities fraud.
   The government reportedly has demanded that Drexel plead guilty
to multiple felony counts and pay a fine as high as $750 million. In
addition, the government has requested Drexel's assistance in
implicating other possible wrongdoers, both within and outside the
firm.
   Steven Anreder, Drexel's chief spokesman, declined comment on
Joseph's reported remarks to employees. Deborah Corley, spokeswoman
for Manhattan U.S. Attorney Rudolph W. Giuliani, also declined
comment.
   There has been heightened speculation in the past few weeks that
Drexel would reach a plea-bargain settlement with the government
before Christmas. Federal prosecutors have intensified the pressure
by exacting cooperation from at least three traders in Drexel's West
Coast high-yield bond department.
   Drexel's problems began after Boesky paid a $100 million fine to
the Securities and Exchange Commission in November 1986 and agreed
to plead guilty to a felony charge as part of his plea-bargain.
Three months ago, the SEC filed a wide-ranging civil lawsuit against
Drexel, its high-yield bond financier Michael Milken and three other
key employees, accusing them of conspiring with Boesky to violate a
range of securities laws.
   Drexel was a pioneer in the $175 billion high-yield bond market.
It is one of the most profitable Wall Street firms and has around
10,000 employees worldwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881220-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 0054EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Pillsbury-Chronology     12-20 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pillsbury-Chronology,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Recap of Major Events in Pillsbury Takeover Struggle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Pillsbury Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   _Oct. 4, 1988: Grand Metropolitan PLC, a British distilling,
gambling and food giant, makes a surprise $60-a-share, $5.23 billion
offer for Pillsbury Co., the Minneapolis-based food and restaurant
chain subjected to repeated takeover rumors in preceding months
because of its depressed stock price. The offer is 53 percent more
than Pillsbury's closing stock price of Oct. 3.
   _Oct. 6: Pillsbury Chairman Philip L. Smith tells the company's
100,000 employees the Grand Met offer is illegal and he refuses to
meet with the suitor. Besides asserting its ``poison pill''
shareholder-rights anti-takeover bylaw, Pillsbury plans a complex
defense that reportedly includes an effort to overturn Grand Met's
U.S. liquor-distribution licenses. It also creates an ad depicting
the famed Pillsbury ``doughboy'' strutting boxing gloves.
   _Oct. 17: Pillsbury board formally declares the Grand Met order
inadequate and orders advisers to explore alternatives.
   _Nov. 7: Faced with increased pressure to capitulate by dissident
shareholders, Pillsbury proposes spinoff of Burger King fast-food
subsidiary as part of defensive restructuring to thwart Grand Met,
but the proposal is widely criticized as a feeble effort to remain
independent. Meanwhile, Grand Met says nearly 75 percent of
Pillsbury's shares have been tendered, but acquisition of the
company is delayed by legal haggling over Pillsbury's poison pill
defense.
   _Nov. 13: Reports surface that Pillsbury may attempt a so-called
``Pac-Man'' defense by acquiring Grand Met, which is twice
Pillsbury's size. Grand Met's management expresses concern about it,
but Pillsbury declines comment.
   _Nov. 20: Pillsbury board delays spinoff of Burger King in
response to opposition from the chain's 1,400 franchises.
   _Nov. 30: Pillsbury suggests it would be willing to meet with
Grand Met if a higher offer emerged.
   _Dec. 9-11: Weekend bargaining results in a sweetened Grand Met
offer of $63, but Pillsbury balks at an agreement.
   _Dec. 16: A Delaware judge invalidates Pillsbury's poison pill
defense and further postpones Burger King spinoff. A separate ruling
by a Minnesota judge also blocks the Burger King spinoff. Hours
later, both sides agree to a $66-a-share takeover worth $5.68
billion.
   _Dec. 18: Pillsbury board formally announces approval of the
takeover.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881220-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 0106EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-StockDisputes     12-20 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stock Disputes,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Court Throws Out State Stock Arbitration Regulations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has thrown out controversial
first-in-the-nation state regulations, inspired by the 1987 stock
market crash, that allowed stock traders to sue brokers more easily
in financial disputes.
   In a 36-page ruling issued Monday, U.S. District Court Judge
Douglas P. Woodlock threw out regulations promulgated in September
by Massachusetts Secretary of State Michael Connolly.
   The regulations, set to take effect Jan., prevented stockbrokers
from requiring customers to agree to arbitration in stock disputes
instead of lawsuits. A top aide to Connolly said the state likely
would appeal the ruling.
   A coalition of brokers sued the state in September and Woodlock
heard the case two weeks ago. In his ruling he said the U.S. Supreme
Court in 1987 upheld the use of pre-dispute arbitration clauses to
govern resolution of controversies between brokers and their
customers.
   Typically, the agreements state that in the event of a dispute,
the customer and the broker would go into arbitration before a
mutually acceptable party _ the New York Stock Exchange, for example
_ rather than take the case to court.
   Woodlock ruled in favor of the brokers who argued that
arbitration is a quicker, cheaper way of settling disputes and that
Massachusetts had improperly usurped federal authority in regulating
securities trading.
   ``On the evidence before me, it appears that court litigation
affords customers the opportunity to pay more in legal costs to get
less in recovery,'' Woodlock wrote. ``To the degree that arbitration
constitutes a more economical form of dispute resolution, it may be
anticipated that regulations which discourage arbitration will have
the effect of raising commission rates.''
   The regulations, Woodlock said, ``single out arbitration
agreements for more demanding standards than are imposed by the
general law of contract in Massachusetts.'' Woodlock said the state
regulations would increase the federal caseload at a time when the
court system is already overburdened.
   ``My clients are delighted that the court agreed with our
position that these regulations were invalid,'' said attorney Gerald
Rath of the Boston law firm Bingham, Dana & Gould. Rath represents
the Securities Industry Association and 10 brokerage firms,
including Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., Fidelity Brokerage Services
Inc. and Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Deputy Secretary of State Marty Meehan said officials in
Connolly's securities division still were reviewing the ruling
Monday evening but he said, ``in all likelihood we will request the
attorney general to appeal the decision.''
   Meehan said the regulations stemmed from a flood of complaints
following the stockmarket crash of October 1987 when thousands of
customers alleged that their urgent stock transactions were
misplaced or mishandled. In the disputes that followed, Meehan said,
stock customers found to their surprise that they had signed away
their right to sue.
   The state regulations would have required brokers to fully
disclose the terms of their arbitration agreements and give
customers the option of maintaining their right to sue in court.
   ``Our beef isn't necessarily with the arbitration process,''
Meehan said. ``Our concern is with investors signing away their
rights unknowingly.''
   Woodlock said full disclosure is desirable but is not adequately
defined in the state regulations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881220-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 0743EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Denny'sDoors     12-20 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Denny's Doors,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Always Open' Restaurant Chain Closing For Christmas Day For First
Time</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: In Tuesday AMs report; brief version for Monday PMs.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LA MIRADA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The signs say ``Always Open,'' but for
the first time in 35 years, most of the 1,200 Denny's restaurants
across the United States will close their doors for Christmas Day.
   Locking those doors is a different story.
   Some buildings have been without locks for decades because of the
always-open policy. At others, the locks have never been used and
the keys can't be found. The company is having to install locks at
about 700 restaurants, said Joe Herrera, director of marketing at
the company's southern California headquarters.
   The company decided to close this year so employees could have
the day off.
   ``It will cost us about $5 million in sales,'' Herrera said.
   The chain's 60,000 employees were so grateful for the holiday
that many sent cards and letters of appreciation to the offices,
Herrera said. Employees received normal pay for Christmas Day.
   ``We just feel we spend 364 days a year taking care of other
people's families; for one day a year we want to take care of our
own,'' he said.
   Nobody wants to work on Christmas, he said, and it has been the
top turnover day of the year, with some managers losing four or five
employees.
   In Hollywood, the companywide closing solved manager Almaz
Legesse's problem of choosing which employees of a Sunset Boulevard
restaurant to give the day off. ``I had a big list. ... I was having
a hard time,'' she said.
   The restaurant, which serves more than 1,700 Christmas customers,
was awaiting a visit from a locksmith. ``We never had locks,'' Ms.
Legesse said.
   ``After so many years of working Christmas every year it's real
nice,'' said Lee Sevene, a manager at a Denny's near a turnpike in
Portland, Me.
   ``People have always thanked us a lot for staying open,'' said
Frances Bushman, manager of a Pismo Beach, Calif., Denny's.
   ``On the other hand they always felt sorry for our waitresses and
cooks,'' she said.
   Ms. Bushman's Denny's has locks but she had to check to see if
the keys fit.
   Christmases in the past have been about twice as busy as average
days at Denny's, Herrera said.
   ``We have up to an hour wait sometimes on Christmas, and that's
all day _ not just at midday,'' Herrera said. ``It actually starts
on Christmas Eve, and just keeps going.''
   The Christmas closing applied to 1,221 restaurants. The operators
of 174 franchise restaurants were allowed to make their own
decisions.
   Winifred Gibson, a manager at two Denny's franchise restaurants
in Fresno, Calif., said they would remain open for the biggest day
of the year.
   But she sympathized with the trouble of locking up a Denny's.
   ``Once I needed to lock the doors on my store. It was a major
fiasco. It took us a day to find the keys,'' Ms. Gibson said.
   Christmas Day used to bring in mostly single people, couples with
no children or elderly people with no family, she said. ``But not
anymore. You have so many one-parent families.''
   The three franchise Denny's in Anchorage, Alaska, and one in
Fairbanks will be open, said Donna Flanagan, manager of an Anchorage
restaurant.
   Ms. Flanagan expects to serve about 1,500 people on Christmas,
which is second only to Mother's Day in bringing in customers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
