<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Obit-Duda     12-20 0146</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Obit-Duda,0153</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Also contained in PM-Deaths</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>John Duda</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OVIEDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Duda, who helped his family build one of
the nation's largest agricultural empires, has died at the age of 84.
   A. Duda & Sons began as a 10-acre farm near here, and mushroomed
into a farming giant from Florida to California and Australia.
Today, the company handles vegetables, citrus, sugar cane, sod,
foliage, cattle and real estate.
   John Duda, who died Saturday, joined the family business in 1926.
He worked behind the scenes to design special farming, irrigation
and packing equipment that is now widely used in farming on organic
soils.
   He retired as corporate vice president in 1976 and served on the
Duda board of directors until January of this year. Last year Forbes
magazine listed the Duda family among the 400 richest people in
America.
</TEXT>
