<1ST_LINE>r f BC-LincolnSavings     12-20 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Lincoln Savings,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Continental Sells Lincoln Savings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Continental Corp. has agreed to sell its
Lincoln Savings and Loan Association subsidiary to a California
investment group.
   Under the deal announced late Monday, the company will recieve
$288.7 million in newly issued preferred stock of Lincoln Savings in
exchange its common stock interest in Lincoln.
   The sale to a group headed by Glendale, Calif., investor Spencer
Scott follows an investigation by the California Department of
Savings and Loans into American Continental's use of Irvine,
Calif.-based Lincoln.
   The agency had ordered American Continental to stop selling
subordinated debentures _ uninsured, long-term debt backed by
corporate earnings _ through Lincoln.
   American Continental spokeswoman Patricia Johonson said the
timing of the sale had nothing to do with the recent decision in
California.
   ``It was just good business sense to make the deal now,'' she
said. ``Frankly, we had received offers from Mr. Scott a couple of
months ago.''
   As part of the deal, American Continental, a financial-services
and real-estate development company, also will gain Lincoln Savings'
interests in a newly opened Phoenician resort and in the Crescent
Hotel in Phoenix, Ms. Johnson said.
   The acquisition is subject to approval by California and federal
regulatory agencies and is expected to be completed in about two
months, Ms. Johnson said.
</TEXT>
