<1ST_LINE>r f BC-China-ExportBan     12-20 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-China-Export Ban,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Bans Exports of Six Commodities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Starting Jan. 1, China will ban exports of copper,
aluminum and four other metal products due to short supplies on the
domestic market, the official Xinhua News Agency reported Tuesday.
   The Ministry of Foreign Economic Relations and Trade also banned
sales of nickel, nickel products, platinum and yellow phosphorus, it
said. Alloys of copper, aluminum and nickel also will go on the
banned list.
   A ministry official said that in 1987 China exported nickel
products worth $47.5 million, aluminum worth $31.2 million, copper
worth $23.3 million and yellow phosphorus worth $9.8 million. There
were no figures for platinum exports.
   Xinhua said government bans on the exports of musk, natural
bezoar, raw polythene materials and monazite remain in effect.
   The new measures also call for limits on the export of 12
commodities, including, metallic magnesium and rubber. Exporters of
these materials must apply for licenses from the Ministry of
Materials and Equipment.
   China is trying to cope with serious raw materials shortages that
have led to sharply higher prices, hoarding and profiteering.
</TEXT>
