<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices advanced broadly this morning,
extending the gains of the past two sessions.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which rose nearly 22
points on Monday, was up another 8.75 to 2,181.43 after 30 minutes
of trading.
   That was near its post-crash closing high of 2,183.50 set Oct. 21.
   Advancing issues led decliners by a margin of more than 2 to 1
among issues listed on the New York Stock Exchange, with 681 issues
up, 286 down and 570 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 30.32 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street, compared with 19.41 million shares at the same
point on Monday.
   The market appeared to take some encouragement this morning from
a pair of economic reports that seemed to signal low inflation and
moderate economic growth.
   The government reported the consumer price index rose 0.3 percent
in November, a slightly slower pace than some analysts expected.
   In another report the government lowered its estimate of economic
growth in the July-through-September period to 2.5 percent from 2.6
percent.
   But while some analysts say the conditions are right for a
year-end stock rally, others said the recent gains may be
short-lived.
   The skeptics note that short-term interest rates near 9 percent
are are making Treasury issues attractive compared with the
uncertain yields on stocks.
   In the credit markets today, however, rates on one-year Treasury
bills were slightly lower.
   International Business Machines was among the active issues in
the early going on the NYSE, rising 1\ to 124.
   Among other widely-held issues, General Electric was up { at 46{,
Exxon was up \ at 46] and American Telephone & Telegraph was
unchanged at 30.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.54 to 156.92. At the American Stock Exchange, the composite market
index was up 0.49 at 299.19.
   On Monday the Dow Jones industrial average rose 21.97 to 2,172.68.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 7 to 5 on the
NYSE, with 839 up, 598 down and 523 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 162.25 million shares, against 196.48
million in the previous session.
