<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Under Pressure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Profit-taking in the wake of Monday's surprisingly strong showing
pressured the market early, and traders said overnight rain in the
soybean growing regions of Brazil helped keep the lid tight.
   Even corn was unable to post gains, despite an announcement the
Soviets had bought 750,000 tons of corn, and are expected back for
another shipment of the same size, possibly later this afternoon.
   On the opening, wheat was 1 cent to 3{ cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.35{ a bushel; corn was 1
cent to 3 cents lower, with December at $2.69 a bushel; oats were 2{
cents to 4 cents lower, with December at $2.28\ a bushel; and
soybeans were 2{ cents to 6 cents lower, with January at $7.89 a
bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures prices were mixed to mostly lower at
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .30 cent lower, with December at
73.62 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .17 cent lower to .10 cent
higher, with January at 83.70 cents a pound; live hogs were .30 cent
lower to .20 cent higher, with December at 44.60 cents a pound; and
frozen pork bellies were .17 cent to .40 cent lower, with February
at 45.00 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
