<2ND_LINE>PM-Pillsbury, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0015,0736</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pillsbury Shareholders Big Winners In Grand Met Takeover, Analysts
Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS New grafs 8-10, Meanwhile today ... last year, to
UPDATE with earnings report. Picks up 8th graf pvs, Pillsbury's
board ...
^By JEFF BAENEN</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. shareholders are the big winners
in Pillsbury's decision to accept a sweetened $5.68 billion takeover
bid from Britain's Grand Metropolitan PLC, securities analysts say.
   ``The shareholders are the first people to profit, from what I
can tell,'' June Page, an analyst at Bear Stearns & Co. in New York,
said Monday. ``The employees of Pillsbury should profit tremendously
and ultimately the consumer.''
   ``They had no other direction to go. We knew that from day one,''
said Craig Carver, an analyst at Dain Bosworth Inc. in Minneapolis.
``I don't know if I can answer the question why they prolonged the
pain for so long.''
   Pillsbury Chairman Philip L. Smith on Monday defended
management's 2{-month battle against the buyout bid, which ended
Sunday when the Minneapolis-based food and restaurant company
accepted Grand Met's latest $66 a share offer.
   ``I think the practical fact of the matter is that we got them to
move off a very firm position,'' Smith told KARE-TV of the Twin
Cities. ``So I don't apologize for our strategy one bit.''
   In a letter Monday to Pillsbury employees, Smith said the company
was pleased with the outcome because it represented a 10 percent
increase from Grand Met's original $60-a-share tender offer and
because the new ownership will allow Burger King franchises a chance
to grow.
   ``It's time to take off the gloves and get on with the next
chapter,'' said Smith. ``We're convinced that Pillsbury's
outstanding brand franchises and products will prosper with the
enthusiastic backing and support of Grand Metropolitan PLC.''
   Meanwhile today, Pillsbury reported its profit fell 38 percent in
the second quarter ended Nov. 30 and 10 percent for the first six
months of fiscal 1989 ``due to a substantial one-time investment in
the Burger King advertising fund and the cost of responding'' to
Grand Met's takeover offer.
   Second-quarter net income totaled $44.8 million, or 52 cents per
share, compared with $72.5 million, or 84 cents per share, in the
same period a year ago. Sales rose to $1.75 billion from $1.69
billion.
   For the six months, net earnings were $116.2 million, or $1.35
per share, vs. $129.3 million, or $1.50 per share, during the
comparable period of fiscal 1988. Sales were $3.23 billion, compared
with $3.14 billion, last year.
   Pillsbury's board of directors approved the takeover Sunday after
a Delaware judge on Friday invalidated its key takeover defenses: a
``poison pill'' plan and the proposed spinoff of its Miami-based
Burger King fast-food chain.
   Pillsbury common stock was trading at about $39 a share the day
before Grand Met launched its takeover bid Oct. 4.
   The stock closed up $3.12{ Monday at $65.37{ a share.
   In addition to benefiting Pillsbury shareholders, shares, the
Grand Met takeover should secure the jobs of most company employees.
But analysts said top Pillsbury executives probably should start
looking elsewhere for work, analysts said.
   Pillsbury spokesman Larry Haeg said he could not comment on
whether top executives or employees would be laid off.
   Top management has been under fire in recent years because of
Pillsbury's lackluster financial performance. Smith, former chairman
of General Foods Corp., earlier this year succeeded William H.
Spoor, who came out of retirement to head Pillsbury on an interim
basis in February after former chairman John Stafford resigned under
pressure.
   Pillsbury's results were depressed again this year. After-tax
profit plummeted 62 percent to $69.3 million on sales of $6.2
billion, largely because of a restructuring charge associated with
the sale of its Godfather's Pizza chain and a number of other
restaurant operations and consolidations.
   Pillsbury, which started as Pillsbury Flour Mills with a single
flour mill in Minneapolis in 1869, makes Pillsbury flour, Green
Giant vegetables, Haagen Dazs ice cream and a variety of other
products.
   In addition to Burger King, Pillsbury owns the Bennigan's and
Steak & Ale restaurant chains, which Grand Met has said it would
sell. Pillsbury employs 100,000 people.
   Grand Met is a British real estate, liquor and gambling
conglomerate. Its U.S. holdings include Alpo dog food and Pearle
Vision Centers.
</TEXT>
