<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0450</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market pushed ahead today for the third
consecutive session, taking some encouragement from a new inflation
report.
   Trading was more active than in the previous session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which rose 21.97 points
on Monday, was up another 8.93 at 2,181.61 at noon on Wall Street.
   That approached its post-crash closing high of 2,183.50 set Oct.
21.
   Advancing issues led decliners by 7 to 6 in nationwide trading of
New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 711 issues up, 578 down
and 578 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 82.05 million shares at noontime
compared with 76.23 million shares at the same point on Monday.
   The market appeared to take some encouragement from a pair of
economic reports that seemed to signal low inflation and moderate
economic growth.
   The government reported the consumer price index rose 0.3 percent
in November, a smaller rise than some analysts expected.
   In another report, the government lowered its estimate of
economic growth in the July-through-September period to 2.5 percent
from 2.6 percent.
   ``The numbers were pleasantly in line with Street expectations,
and gave some confidence to the market,'' said Jack Baker, head of
equity bloick trading at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   The reports contributed to a rally in the credit markets, where
prices of some long-term bonds were up by as much as $9 for every
$1,000 in face value while interest rates pulled back.
   But while some analysts say the conditions are right for a
year-end stock rally, others said the recent gains may be
short-lived.
   The skeptics note that short-term interest rates near 9 percent
are making Treasury issues such as one-year bills attractive
compared with the uncertain yields on stocks.
   International Business Machines was the most active issue in the
early going on the NYSE, rising 1[ to 123~.
   Elsewhere in the technology group, Digital Equipment was up | at
95|, Hewlett Packard was up 1\ at 52} and Honeywell was up \ at 60{.
   Among other active issues, American Telephone & Telegraph was off
\ at 29}, Masco Corp. was off ] at 25\], General Electric was up ]
at 46] and Inco Ltd. was up } at 25|.
   First Fidelity Bancorp was off 2{ at 25]. The company announced
last week it expected to lose $145 million to $190 million in the
current quarter.
   The NYSE's index of all its listed common stocks rose 0.37 to
156.75. At the American Stock Exchange, the composite market index
was up 0.81 at 299.51.
</TEXT>
