<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Testing, 1st Ld-Writethru,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Random Drug Testing Barred for 3 Million Truckers, Bus Drivers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7th graf to add no comment from Transportation
Department officials and to clarify when testing was to begin. Picks
up in 6th graf, `Jeffrey King ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge blocked a federal plan to
require random drug testing of 3 million interstate drivers
nationwide but did allow pre-employment and post-accident testing.
   U.S. District Judge Marilyn Hall Patel issued a temporary
restraining order Monday against random drug testing of truckers and
interstate bus drivers. She told government lawyers she wanted to
review how widespread substance abuse is in the trucking industry
before a future hearing.
   The material published in the Federal Register in support of
testing amounted to nothing more than ``a well-taken diatribe
against drug abuse in American society,'' Patel.
   The program was to start Wednesday, but the Transportation
Department did not require companies to conduct any actual testing
until next December, according to department spokesman Bob Marks.
   More than 1 million other private employees in the rail, airline
and maritime industries are scheduled to begin random testing.
   The order expires Dec. 30, when Patel is scheduled to hear
arguments on a longer-lasting injunction against all testing
programs affecting truckers and interstate bus drivers.
   Marks declined to comment on Patel's ruling, saying the
government would present its side on Dec. 30.
   Jeffrey King, lawyer for the Owner-Operator Independent Drivers
Association of America, which challenged the testing program, said
drug abuse among truck drivers ``is probably below the national
average.''
   ``There's no basis to think there's a severe problem,'' King told
reporters. He said random drug testing would sacrifice ``the rights
of millions of truck drivers ... in hopes of catching a few.''
   King said his organization, which has 9,000 members, sued on
behalf of all 300,000 independent owners of heavy-duty trucks and
small truck fleets. He said Patel's order applies to all interstate
truck and bus drivers, but not to inter-city bus drivers, who have
separate drug testing regulations.
   King said he hoped to reach agreement with government lawyers on
an extension of the ban on random drug testing before the temporary
restraining order expires.
   The Transportation Department testing program was announced Nov.
14. Transportation Secretary James Burnley said at the time that
transportation employees were no more immune from drug abuse than
the rest of society, listing a series of accidents and other
evidence.
</TEXT>
