<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 1342EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-US-EECHormones     12-20 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-EEC Hormones,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Asks GATT Council For Support In Hormones Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community on Tuesday called
for a GATT Council ruling in the dispute over the EEC ban on
hormone-treated meat which is to take effect Jan.1 and threatens to
trigger a trade war with the United States.
   The United States immediately opposed the request, saying the EEC
sought an ``instantanous legal finding'' that had no basis under the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
   The EEC representative, John Beck, told the GATT Council that the
threatened U.S. retaliatory measures, a 100 percent punitive duty on
a range of products, were a ``further affront against the
multilateral trade system'' set up by the GATT.
   He said the case had wide ramifications and urged the council to
rule on the legal issues involved and decide on remedies.
   A top U.S. trade negotiator, Michael Samuels, said the EEC ban
amounted to a ``unilateral decision to simply prohibit $120 million
in U.S. exports per year.'' He said it was a ``wholesale disruption
of traditional trade flows'' on alleged grounds of health but that
the measure was not backed up by scientific evidence.
   Samuels said the EEC had repeatedly rejected proposals to have
the case examined by an impartial scientific body. He said the
United States remained willing to pursue the matter under any
appropriate GATT process as long as the EEC deferred the ban.
   Beck said the EEC was aware that there were different views on
the use of growth hormones in meat but that it had to ``listen to
its consumers'' who did not want such meat.
   Canada supported the United States, saying that it considered the
EEC approach excessive. Robert Wright, the Canadian representative,
said in the brief debate that growth hormones were proven to be safe
if used properly.
   There was no decision on the EEC request and the matter was
expected to come up again at the next GATT Council session in
February.
   In other business, Brazil formally demanded that a GATT panel be
set up to rule in its dispute with the United States over punitive
U.S. duties imposed in response to an alleged lack of Brazilian
patent protection for U.S. pharmaceutical products.
   Brazilian ambassador Rubens Ricupero said the U.S. retaliation
was in clear violation of GATT rules and in breach of commitments
not to impose new unilateral trade restrictions during the current
Uruguay round of world trade liberalization talks.
   Samuels said there had been no alternative left to defending
legitimate U.S. interests but that the measures would be lifted as
soon as Brazil acts upon the U.S. request to ensure full patent
proection.
   The measures cover $39 million worth of Brazil's trade with the
United States, an amount which Samuels said reflects the damage
suffered by the U.S. pharmaceutical industry.
   Twenty-eight countries backed Brazil's position, including the
EEC and Switzerland, which said also that the case argued for action
on patents in the Uruguay round talks.
   As the United States opposed the Brazilian request up a panel,
the council did not take a decision but was expected to discuss the
case again at its February session.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
