<HEAD>London Shares Close Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: updates throughout with close.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London stock exchange finished
a listless session higher Tuesday, as an optimistic start to Wall
Street and better-than-expected British money supply figures helped
fuel a bit of buying interest.
   However, traders cautioned that activity was still light as
players attention focused on the holidays and Friday's release of
British trade figures for November.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index closed 6.9
points, or 0.4 percent, stronger at 1,777.4.
   Equities rose following news that Britain's money supply grew
more slowly than expected, which dealers said is another sign that
the British economy is finally beginning to slow down and that
interest rates might not have to be nudged higher in the near future
to quell an overheating economy.
   Britain's narrow money supply M-0, which consists of notes and
coins in circulation plus banks' operational balances with the Bank
of England, rose an estimated 0.2 percent in November. The markets
had expected a gain of between 0.3 percent and 1.3 percent.
   Volume was a moderate 331.6 million shares, compared with the
403.8 million shares that changed hands Monday.
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 10 points at 2,182.68 by
the close of the London session.
</TEXT>
