<HEAD>Dollar Firmer In Europe, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose in thin European trading
Tuesday as companies made purchases to square their books for the
year's end. Gold prices were mixed.
   The dollar was also helped by market expectations of an increase
in the U.S. discount rate, dealer said.
   Signs of slower economic growth in Britain knocked 1.60 cents off
the British pound, which has been boosted by a high 13 percent base
interest rate for bank loans.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8070 late Tuesday, cheaper
for buyers than Monday's late $1.8230.
   Other late rates in Europe, compared with Monday's late rates,
1.7750 West German marks, up from 1.7625; 1.4995 Swiss francs, up
from 1.4870; 6.0675 French francs, up from 6.0235; 2.0080 Dutch
guilders, up from 1.9895; 1,309.32 Italian lire, up from 1,296.50;
1.2000 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1995.
   Earlier in Tokyo the dollar closed at 124.70 Japanese yen, up
from 124.02. The dollar traded higher in London late in the day at
125.05 yen.
   Gold bullion prices rose in Zurich but were static in London, the
major market.
   Gold closed in Zurich at a bid $413.50 a troy ounce, up from
$412.25 and were unchanged in London at $414.25 bid.
   Hong Kong gold closed at $415.67 bid, up from $415.62.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $6.11 a troy ounce,
up from $6.08.
</TEXT>
