<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 0323EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f AM-BusinessMirror Adv21   12-20 0743</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Business Mirror, Adv 21,0762</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release AMs Wednesday Dec. 21</NOTE>
<HEAD>`To Succeed You Must Eat, Sleep and Dream Your Goals'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Curt Carlson, 74, recently stepped up the pace.
Rather than growing his business at just 15 percent a year, which
would double volume in five years, he publicly announced a goal of
17.5 percent a year.
   At that rate Carlson Cos., a personally owned 75-company
conglomerate based in Minnetonka, Minn., would double its annual
volume to $9 billion in 1992. Already, it is as large as some
Fortune 100 companies.
   Unlike such companies, however, Carlson remains entrepreneurial,
constantly setting sales goals, publicly stating them so that there
is no retreat, then setting new goals. It has never missed a
five-year sales goal.
   Curtis LeRoy Carlson was selling soap to grocery stores in 1938
when he founded Gold Bond Stamp Co. Constantly diversifying into
other businesses, restlessly setting goals, he pushed company sales
to $1 billion in 1978.
   Averaged out over the 40 years, that growth came to 33 percent a
year compounded. The company was huge now, and growth of that sort
doesn't come as easily as in the smaller days. For one thing, you
have to seek public funds.
   So, said Carlson, in 1978 he thought it best to ``settle'' for 15
percent a year for the next five years. In 1982 sales reached $2
billion. Another 15 percent five-year plan began. In 1987 the
company reached $4 billion.
   Ever the entrepreneur, Carlson then looked at his cash flow and
decided there was enough money coming in to step up the pace to 17.5
percent. That's the goal each year through 1992. There's no resting
at Carlson Cos.
   The conglomerate now has four major divisions: hospitality,
incentives, travel and promotion. Among the companies are the highly
rated Radisson hotel chain, TGI Friday's restaurants, Ask Mr. Foster
Travel Service, the oldest and largest in America, E.F. MacDonald's
incentive travel, Carlson Learning Co.
   It is forever in transition, continually evolving. In its
evolution the company follows no rigid plan, says Carlson. ``I hire
top people and they grow the company,'' he says. ``We're pulled
ahead by big horses.''
   Enthusiasm, imagination, innovation and motivation are important
elements in Carlson's type of management, and goal-setting is basic
to all of them. It began with little self-reminders in Curt's
wallet. Now it's institutionalized.
   ``To succeed you must eat, sleep and dream your goals and
quotas,'' he says. ``It's a fact, an absolute fact: You will never
make as much progress without targets as you will with goal
setting.''
   Nevertheless, he calls himself cautious. He seeks to grow in
``bite sizes; I don't shoot the wad.'' That way, if things don't
turn out as expected, ``you get a little blip in the earnings that
can be corrected.''
   Incentives spur achievement, and Carlson officers who achieve are
given such things as first-class, 17-day tours of Hawaii, New
Zealand and Australia. Throughout the year spouses are kept informed
of how well their mates are doing. Not wanting to be left out, they
spur their mates to higher achievement.
   The company remains the very same as it was 50 years ago in at
least one respect: it is sales driven. ``You build as fast as you
can,'' said Carlson the other day. ``As soon as a salesman is making
his pay you put on another.''
   Every month Carlson examines the income statement and balance
sheet for each of the 75 companies. He watches the bottom line, the
pursuit of goals. Should he suspect problems, he asks for backup
information and explanations.
   So successful are the Carlson management techniques that some of
his people would set _ and probably reach _ even higher goals. But,
says Carlson, ``you can only grow as fast as the money comes in.''
   To open a new Friday's, for example, might take $2 million. ``I
cannot open 40 of them without taking money away from others.'' In a
sense, therefore, the big growth goals are probably compromises.
   Perhaps its just as well because the goals are always publicly
stated. As a consequence, they are avidly watched by the media. Fail
to achieve a goal and everyone in town will know about it.
   ``You burn your bridges behind you,'' said Carlson the magic
motivator. ``We give a figure and we had better make it, because
everyone is watching.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tuesday Dec. 20</NOTE>
