<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Slip Across the Board on Correction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices posted
across-the-board losses Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   The markets opened under pressure because of profit-taking in the
wake of Monday's surprisingly strong showing.
   Traders said overnight rain in the soybean growing regions of
Brazil helped keep the lid tight. And even corn was unable to post
gains, despite an announcement the Soviets had bought 750,000 tons
of corn, and were expected back to announce a second purchase of the
same size after Tuesday's close.
   ``We were overdue for a correction,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a
trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``There was no fresh news to
move things and everybody felt the dramatic rises of the last few
sessions had reached their top.''
   On the close, wheat was 3 cents lower to { cent higher, with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.34{ a bushel; corn was 2
cents to 3{ cents lower, with December at $2.67 a bushel; oats were
4 cents to 5 cents lower, with December at $2.21 a bushel; and
soybeans were 3\ cents to 7 cents lower, with January at $7.86 a
bushel.
