<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Fares,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Continental Eliminates Advance Purchase on Popular Holiday Fares</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Continental Airlines announced Tuesday it will
eliminate the advance purchase requirement on a popular excursion
fare for travel during the next two weeks.
   The change will allow more people to obtain a discount ticket for
holiday travel, a spokesman for the airline said.
   Continental is eliminating the seven-day advance purchase
requirement on a category of excursion fares that is discounted up
to 70 percent from full economy-class fares for those traveling
between Dec. 21 and Jan. 4.
   A round-trip purchase and a Saturday night stay are required, and
a 25 percent cancellation charge applies.
   Although the seats available at the fares are limited and may not
remain on every flight, they are widely available for travel on most
U.S. routes throughout the holiday period, said the spokesman for
Continental, a subsidiary of Texas Air Corp.
