<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 1617EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Bush-Deficit 1stLd-Writethru   12-20 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Deficit, 1st Ld-Writethru,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Appoints Laxalt, Ashley to Deficit Commission</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with appointments, Bush quotes</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush, emphasizing his
opposition to tax increases, appointed Republican Paul Laxalt and
Democrat Thomas Ashley on Tuesday to a national commission
struggling to find a formula for reducing the federal budget deficit.
   ``I intend to hold the line on taxes,'' Bush said. ``There are a
lot of people around saying I can't do that.''
   Laxalt, onetime governor of Nevada, served two terms in the U.S.
Senate before joining a Washington law firm. Ashley, a longtime
personal friend of Bush's, spent 26 years in the House of
Representatives and was a top-ranking member of the Banking
Committee. He now is president of the Association of Bank Holding
Companies, a lobbying group which represents the country's largest
banks.
   The appointments put the National Economic Commission at its full
strength of 14 people. The panel was created last year after the
stock market's 508-point plunge.
   Some business leaders said Laxalt's appointment diminished the
possibility that the commission would recommend tax increases to cut
the deficit.
   ``Laxalt is the type of guy who has read George Bush's lips, and
from everything I know about him he would be against taxes and would
want to look on the spending side for deficit reductions,'' said
Richard Rahn, chief economist of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. ``He
has been a good fiscal conservative.''
   Tempering skepticism that he voiced earlier, Bush said, ``Some
have suggested I am something less than enthralled with the National
Economic Commission. That's not right.''
   Bush, who takes office on Jan. 20, made that comment in a meeting
with about 30 business leaders who pledged their support for a
program of reducing the deficit by cutting spending rather than
raising taxes. He issued a written statement later announcing the
appointment of Laxalt and Ashley.
   He noted that his announcement came only one day after the
Electoral College ratified the Nov. 8 vote electing him president.
``The swiftness with which I am making these appointments
underscores the importance I place on the need to reduce the federal
budget deficit,'' he said.
   ``I believe that the experience these two public servants will
bring to the panel will add to the quality of its deliberations,''
he said.
   At the beginning of the meeting with the business leaders, Bush
called the deficit a tough problem.
   ``I'll just do my level best to send signals to the international
markets that we're serious, that we're projecting it downward
firmly, and I really believe that once that happens the adverse
psychology that is forcing interest rates up beyond where in my view
they ought to be will turn around,'' he said.
   ``I think once world markets think that we're definitively on a
track without exception to have the deficit obliterated in whatever
number of years it is, that in itself _ a bipartisan answer _ that
in itself will be enormously beneficial to world markets,'' he said.
   In the past, Bush has appeared suspicious of the National
Economic Commission, warning that it might try to promote a
tax-increase plan to cut the deficit.
   But Bush said Tuesday he was looking forward to hearing from the
group and listening to its suggestions. ``There are some very good
people on there, Democrats and Republicans. They're serious, serious
people. ... So I'm not looking for a battle with the them and there
won't be one because they've been most cooperative since the
election in terms of wanting to at least have from our key economic
appointees their views.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
