   The market appeared to take some early encouragement from a pair
of economic reports that seemed to signal low inflation and moderate
economic growth.
   The government reported the consumer price index rose 0.3 percent
in November, and lowered its estimate of economic growth in the
July-through-September period to 2.5 percent from 2.6 percent.
   The reports contributed to a rally in the credit markets, where
prices of some long-term bonds were up by as much as $9 for every
$1,000 in face value while interest rates pulled back.
   But analysts said profit-taking eroded some of the stock market's
early gains, and some observers warned the recent rally had not been
broad-based enough to be sustained.
   The skeptics note that short-term interest rates near 9 percent
are making Treasury issues such as one-year bills attractive
compared with the uncertain yields on stocks.
