<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Inflation-Markets Bjt   12-20 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Inflation-Markets, Bjt,0726</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inflation Report Boosts Financial Markets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for AM-Economy Rdp</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An encouraging report on inflation Tuesday added
a spark of life to some financial markets and eased concerns about
higher interest rates, but most analysts remained wary about the
economy's direction.
   The dollar rallied against most major currencies in foreign
exchange trading here and abroad, while bond prices headed sharply
higher.
   The Treasury's bellwether 30-year issue rose nearly $10 per
$1,000 face amount, while its yield, which moves inversely to price,
fell below 9 percent for the first time in a week.
   On Wall Street, however, stocks declined. The Dow Jones average
of 30 industrials, which shot up around 14 points at the opening,
closed down 6.61 to 2,166.07.
   Economists said the markets were encouraged by a Labor Department
report that showed inflation on the consumer level slowed in
November to an annual rate of just 3 percent. A drop in clothing
prices and stabilized prices for food contributed to the decline,
the department said.
   With only December left, another month similar to November could
enable the Reagan administration to finish its last year in office
meeting its inflation target of 4.3 percent for 1988, down slightly
from 1987's 4.4 percent level.
   Also easing inflation worries was a Commerce Department report
that the gross national product _ the broadest measure of economic
health _ expanded at a moderate annual rate of 2.5 percent in the
third quarter due to the summer drought.
   For the same period, the department reported that after-tax
corporate profits rose 3.9 percent, down from a robust 8.9 percent
increase the previous quarter.
   ``Low inflation is good for all the markets. It means the
(economic) recovery was sustainable and long-lived,'' said Maury
Harris, chief economist for PaineWebber Inc.
   It eases the pressure on interest rates, which have risen sharply
in recent weeks partly on inflationary fears.
   Inflation is considered the nemesis of the financial markets,
particularly the credit markets, because it erodes the value of
fixed-income securities, sending yields higher to compensate for the
loss.
   That depresses the stock market, which competes for investor
money. And it often hurts the dollar because as prices of stocks and
bonds slip, foreigners become less willing to exchange their
currencies for dollars to buy those U.S. securities.
   Talk around Wall Street lately had centered around whether the
Federal Reserve will raise its discount rate, a key short-term rate,
to prevent the economy from overheating and inflation from heading
up.
   The discount rate is the interest the Fed charges on loans to
member banks and savings institutions, and it's considered the most
direct vehicle for the central bank to make its credit policies
known. Most economists had predicted the rate would be raised 0.5
percentage point to 7 percent.
   However, Tuesday's inflation and GNP reports put some of those
discussions to rest, at least temporarily.
   ``Some people who jumped on the interest-rates-going-up,
fed-tightening bandwagon found out they were going on it
prematurely,'' said Robert A. Brusca, chief financial economist for
Nikko Securities Co. International. ``That's what the markets are
telling you.''
   Carol A. Stone, a senior economist for Nomura Securities
International Inc., admits she was part of that majority group.
   ``We had expected that given the strength in some of the other
economic numbers lately that we'd see the Fed raising the discount
rate pretty soon,'' she said. ``Well this (economic data) suggests
that they may not have to do that right away, although there's still
a good possibility after the first of the year that we'd see that
happen.''
   ``There are some people that are ... expecting a rise in the
discount rate and the (bank's) prime rate before year's end,'' added
Kevin Flanagan, a money market economist for Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc.
   Brusca said that while the latest reports point to less inflation
and slightly slower economic growth, ``a laundry list'' of other
factors point in another direction.
   ``The dollar remains weak overall, (business) capacity use rates
are high and rising, and we have a very low unemployment rate,'' he
said. ``Oil prices are also rising.''
</TEXT>
