<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SeawayTolls     12-20 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seaway Tolls,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>St. Lawrence Seaway Boosts Some Tolls, Exempts Humanitarian Aid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most tolls on the St. Lawrence Seaway will
increase by 4.5 percent in each of the next two years, officials of
the binational waterway said Tuesday.
   The higher tolls being levied in 1989 and 1990 are needed to help
the system keep pace with inflation, said U.S. Seaway Administrator
James L. Emery and William A. O'Neil, president of the Seaway
Authority of Canada.
   However, tolls for humanitarian-aid shipments will be eliminated
and lumber shipments will be reclassified as bulk cargo and
therefore have a lower toll, officials said. These moves are
intended to spur increased movement of those two cargos.
   The combined toll for general cargo on the seaway in 1989 is
$2.86 per metric ton, while the rate for bulk cargo is $1.33 per ton.
   To be qualify for the lower rate, the lumber must be timber or
logs, sawed or split and rough or dressed into various sizes for use
as beams, joists, rafters, studs, boards of planks.
   ``There is an abundance of forest land and wood product
industries in the western Great Lakes region,'' O'Neil said. ``The
seaway is a natural transportation route for this virtually untapped
market.''
   However, he said the seaway handled only 9,400 metric tons of
lumber shipments in 1987, and the U.S. and Canadian agencies are
hoping for a significant increase in the amount of lumber shipped
through the system.
</TEXT>
