<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PrimeLayoffs     12-20 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prime Layoffs,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime May Lay Off Hundreds as Part of Integration of Computervision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NATICK, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc. may lay off 200 to 1,000
employees in the next six months as it restructures its sales and
marketing staff following a recent acquisition, it was reported
Wednesday.
   Speculation about layoffs has been fueled by a recent
announcement that the Natick takeover target, which acquired
Computervision in February, intends to organize its sales and
marketing operations into three geographical regions, according to
The Boston Herald and the Middlesex News in Framingham.
   The three regions would be the Americas; Europe, Africa and the
Middle East; and the Asian-Pacific.
   Rickard Eckel, a Prime spokesman, would say only, ``We cannot
rule out the elimination of positions in the future as the
integration continues.''
   Prime is the target of a hostile $970 million takeover bid by MAI
Basic Four Inc. Analysts say Prime's layoffs could help the firm
build up its defenses by cutting costs.
</TEXT>
