<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     12-20 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose Tuesday, strengthened by yearend
corporate demand, speculation of higher U.S. interest rates and a
sharp jump in oil prices.
   Gold prices fell marginally in New York after mostly rising
abroad. Republic National Bank of New York quoted bullion at $413.90
a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, down from $414 late Monday.
   Currency strategists attributed the dollar's rise largely to
orders for the currency from U.S.-based multinationals preparing to
repatriate 1988 earnings.
   ``There is always good corporate demand for dollars in the last
couple of weeks of the year,'' said Stuart Yannalfo, senior foreign
exchange trader at Refco Inc., a New York commodities futures firm.
   Others said persistent speculation that the Federal Reserve would
tighten interest rates in the United States raised demand for
dollars. Higher interest rates make dollar-denominated holdings
worth more.
   In addition, an oil price hike in the energy markets supported
the U.S. currency, since most oil contracts are priced in dollars. A
rise in oil prices theoretically raises demand for dollars to pay
for the oil.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 124.70 Japanese yen, up from
124.02. The dollar traded higher in London at 125.05 yen. By the
time trading ended in New York the dollar fetched 125.33 yen, up
from 124.08 yen late Monday.
   In London the British pound cost $1.8070 late Tuesday, cheaper
for buyers than $1.8230 late Monday. In New York the pound cost
$1.7957, down from $1.8209 late Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York compared with rates late
Monday: 1.7803 West German marks, up from 1.7645; 1.5035 Swiss
francs, up from 1.4891; 1.2025 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1998;
6.0813 French francs, up from 6.0270; and 1,310.75 Italian lire, up
from 1,300.75.
   Other late rates in Europe, compared with late rates Monday:
1.7750 marks, up from 1.7625; 1.4995 Swiss francs, up from 1.4870;
6.0675 French francs, up from 6.0235; 2.0080 Dutch guilders, up from
1.9895; 1,309.32 Italian lire, up from 1,296.50; and 1.2000 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.1995.
   In gold trading, bullion for current delivery fell 40 cents a
troy ounce to $414 on the New York Commodity Exchange. Earlier in
London, prices remained unchanged at $414.25. In Zurich gold rose
$1.25 to $413.50 and in Hong Kong it rose 5 cents to $415.67.
   Silver for current delivery fell 1.7 cents a troy ounce to $6.093
on the New York Commodity Exchange. In London silver rose 3 cents an
ounce to $6.11.
</TEXT>
