<1ST_LINE>r f AM-OECD-Inflation     12-20 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OECD-Inflation,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OECD Says West Should Take Steps to Combat Inflation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western industrialized nations are likely to
experience moderately low inflation rates over the next two years,
but the threat of accelerated inflation and higher interest rates is
just over the horizon, the OECD said Tuesday.
   In the latest issue of its semi-annual Economic Outlook, the
secretariat of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development suggested that some tightening of fiscal policy, as well
as monetary policy, may be necessary in most countries to combat
inflationary pressures.
   The secretariat also predicted that the current-account trade
deficits of the three biggest OECD countries _ the United States,
Japan and West Germany _will remain unacceptably high.
   The Paris-based OECD cautioned that although there appears to be
no imminent problem, ``it would be unwise to conclude that external
(trade) imbalances no longer represent an important threat to
international financial stability.''
   The report says the real, or inflation-adjusted, rate of
expansion of western industrialized economies is likely to slow to
between 2.5 percent and 3 percent in 1990 from 3.25 percent next
year. The expansion rate this year was 4 percent.
   Growth in the United States is expected to slow to 2.5 percent in
1990 from 3 percent in 1989 and 3.75 percent this year.
   The OECD also suggested that the dollar may strengthen against
other currencies in the short term, especially if the U.S. economy
continues to expand at a rapid pace.
   Japan's growth rate is expected to moderate from a robust 5.75
percent in 1988 to 4.5 percent in 1989 and 3.75 percent in 1990. The
outlook is similar in West Germany, where this year's growth rate of
3.75 percent is likely to decline to 2.5 percent in 1989, although
there may be a very slight pickup to 2.75 percent in 1990.
   The organization's chief economist, David Henderson, described
the overall picture for the OECD economies as ``rather encouraging.''
</TEXT>
