<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 1832EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     12-20 0834</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0862</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coffee Overflows Limit as Concerns Rise Over Dockworkers' Strike
in
Brazil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Coffee futures prices made their most dramatic surge in five
consecutive sessions of advances, overrunning the daily trading
limit Tuesday amid growing concerns over a lengthening strike by
dockworkers in Brazil.
   ``The longer the strike remains in place,'' said Arthur Stevenson
of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. ``the more explosive this will
get.''
   On other markets, cocoa moved in sympathy with coffee and
registered sharp gains; platinum came off the floor and posted
moderate gains after three straight days of reverses; and the
January contract for crude oil futures skyrocketed $1.42 when the
brokerage arm of a large commodity trading house got caught selling
the market short on the day the contract expired.
   Coffee prices rocketed 10.35 cents and 10.58 cents for the spot
March and May contracts, respectively, and settled up the 6-cent
daily trading limit for the remaining deferred contracts at the New
York Coffee, Sugar and Cocoa Exchange. March closed at $1.5543 a
pound, a high for the contract.
   Stevenson said the single-biggest development Tuesday was a
report that a regional court near the key Brazilian port of Santos
affirmed the legality of the strike that began Dec. 13.
   But several other factors were underpinning coffee's dramatic
rise in recent days.
   ``There is concern about the production outlook ... insufficient
rain in some parts of Brazil (the world's largest producer) and too
much in Colombia,'' he said.
   ``And when you put those together, and then consider that the
court decision leaves the workers under less pressure to settle
quickly,'' he added, ``you've got the kind of explosive market we
saw today.''
   Cocoa, meanwhile, was up $58 to $82 a ton, with March at $1,524.
   ``It was the biggest day for cocoa in ages,'' said Stevenson.
``There was psychological spillover from the coffee pit and the port
strike has some impact there too.''
   ``And,'' he added, ``there is some indication the Ivory Coast
(the world's leading cocoa producer) is going to tighten supply by
removing some from the market.''
   Platinum climbed as high as $15 an ounce before settling $5 to
$6.50 an ounce higher on the New York Mercantile Exchange. The
December contract closed at $535.80 _ a steep decline from the $600
level the precious metal topped last week before Ford Motor Corp.
announced it had developed an automotive catalytic converter that
did not require the use of platinum.
   ``People are coming back to platinum, but there are no bets how
this will go until we get a complete story,'' said Steve Chronowitz,
vice president and director of futures research for Smith Barney,
Harris Upham & Co. in New York.
   ``How much will this actually cut demand? Will General Motors and
Chrysler and Europe and Japan follow suit? Those are questions we
won't know answers to for a while,'' he added. ``But the worst may
be over.''
   The rest of the precious metals were quiet. Gold settled 40 cents
to 50 cents lower at the Comex, with December at $414 a troy ounce;
silver 1.7 cents to 2.1 cents lower, with December at $6.093 a troy
ounce. Copper was .90 cent lower to 3.15 cents higher, with December
at $1.5890 a pound.
   Crude oil futures at the New York Mercantile Exchange rose only
by 10 cents to 38 cents _ except for the spot contract in January,
which jumped $1.42 to $17.73 a barrel jump,
   The spot-month aberration resulted because a brokerage firm,
rumored to be part of grain giant Cargill Inc., had sold the market
short _ expecting a drop in prices _ and was forced to buy contracts
to fulfill obligations on delivery day.
   ``Somebody got caught between tornadoes,'' said energy analyst
who declined to be identified, ``and had to buy like crazy. It seems
to happen every time delivery day comes along.''
   Heating oil settled 0.47 cent to 0.72 cent higher, with January
at 51.47 cents a gallon, and unleaded gasoline was up 0.13 cent to
0.35 cent, with January at 45.55 cents a gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures prices posted across-the-board losses
on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat settled { cent to 2{ cents lower, with December at $4.34{ a
bushel; corn was 2{ cents to 3{ cents lower, with December at $2.67
a bushel; oats were 4\ cents to 5 cents lower, with December at
$2.21 a bushel; and soybeans were 3} cents to 7 cents lower, with
January at $7.86{ a bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures prices were mixed at the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle settled .25 cent lower to .08 cent higher, with
December at 73.65 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .03 cent lower
to .10 cent higher, with January at 83.82 cents a pound; live hogs
were .30 cent lower to 1.10 cents higher, with December at 45.74
cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .10 cent lower to .37
cent higher, with February at 45.52 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
