<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Pillsbury     12-20 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pillsbury,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pillsbury Reports Second Quarter Earnings Decline; Smith To Leave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. said Tuesday its profit fell 38
percent in its second quarter and 10 percent for the first half of
its fiscal year due to the costs of its unsuccessful battle against
hostile suitor Grand Metropolitan PLC.
   Pillsbury said its net income in the three months ended Nov. 30
totaled $44.8 million, or 52 cents per share, compared with $72.5
million, or 84 cents per share, in the same period a year ago. Sales
rose to $1.75 billion from $1.69 billion.
   The food and restaurant company agreed Sunday to accept a
sweetened $5.68 billion takeover bid from the British conglomerate,
which had made its first offer on Oct. 4.
   Pillsbury said the profit decline was ``due to a substantial
one-time investment in the Burger King advertising fund and the cost
of responding'' to Grand Met's takeover bid.
   The Burger King investment reduced net earnings by $14.4 million,
or 17 cents per share, in the quarter, while after-tax costs related
to the tender offer totaled $13.2 million, or 15 cents per share,
the company said.
   Operating profit for restaurants fell to $4.2 million in the
quarter from $47.6 million a year ago. Included in the latest
quarter's results was a one-time investment of $23.4 million to
reduce the deficit in Burger King's advertising fund.
   Pillsbury's foods businesses reported operating profit of $132.8
million for the quarter, a 16 percent gain from the year-earlier
period.
   For the six months, the company's net earnings were $116.2
million, or $1.35 per share, vs. $129.3 million, or $1.50 per share,
during the comparable period last year. Sales rose to $3.23 billion
from $3.14 billion last year.
   For the six months, foods operating profit increased 25 percent
to $211 million, while restaurants operating profit fell by 56.3
percent to $52.9 million.
   Separately, Pillsbury Chairman Philip L. Smith said he would
leave the company after Grand Met completes the buyout sometime this
winter.
   Smith, 54, former chairman of General Foods Corp., became
Pillsbury's president, chairman, and chief executive officer Aug. 1.
   ``There isn't a CEO (chief executive officer) I know that
wouldn't rather be running an independent company,'' Smith told the
Minneapolis Star Tribune. ``I felt there were significant
opportunities in Pillsbury, and my regret is that I won't be able to
bring those about.''
   After months of resistance, Pillsbury's board of directors
approved the buyout on Sunday after a judge in Delaware on Friday
blocked its two key takeover defenses, a ``poison pill'' stock issue
plan and the proposed spinoff of Miami-based Burger King.
   Grand Met will purchase all outstanding shares of Pillsbury
common stock for $66 per share in cash under an offer that expires
Jan. 3.
   Grand Met is a British real estate, liquor and gambling
conglomerate. Its U.S. holdings include Alpo dog food and Pearle
Vision Centers.
</TEXT>
