<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ZZZZBest     12-20 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ZZZZ Best,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Say Probe Continues, Victims Unlikely to Get Money Back</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal investigation of fraud at the ZZZZ
Best rug shampooing company continues despite the conviction of
owner Barry Minkow and his accountant, the U.S. attorney said
Tuesday.
   Investors in the company and other victims of its scams are
unlikely to get back any of the $65 million to $70 million that
disappeared into the firm, U.S. Attorney Robert Bonner told a news
conference.
   ``It's a sad fact that in many of these fraud cases, there isn't
much left when it is all over,'' Bonner said. ``Certainly much of it
was dissipated on the lifestyle that Mr. Minkow led.''
   Minkow, 22, became familiar to millions of people through
appearances in television ads and talk shows, portraying himself to
the public and the investment community as a teen-age supersalesman
whose thriving company began in his parents' garage in the San
Fernando Valley.
   He was convicted last week of 57 counts of conspiracy, securities
fraud, mail fraud and credit card fraud.
   Jurors rejected his defense that Mafia figures had forced him to
swindle investors by falsely claiming his company was making a
fortune restoring fire- and water-damaged buildings.
   Minkow's accountant, Norman Rothberg, 52, was convicted Monday of
taking a bribe from Minkow to cover up the fraud. Ten others
connected with ZZZZ Best have pleaded guilty to various charges
since the firm collapsed in July 1987.
   Bonner said his office, the FBI and the Internal Revenue Service
were following leads that surfaced at the trial, including Minkow's
claims that he was forced into crime by mobsters who had interests
in his company.
   ``The full range of individuals who may have participated ... is
going to be looked into,'' Bonner said. ``We're not ruling out _ I
can't say that none of these figures have ties to organized crime.''
   Bonner and other officials at the news conference refused to say
who was under investigation, when charges might be forthcoming or
even if they were sure they would amass enough evidence for further
charges.
   Possible crimes connected with ZZZZ Best include tax fraud, bank
fraud and securities fraud through manipulation of the company's
stock price, Bonner said.
   The officials refused to comment on whether Minkow had discussed
helping in the investigation in return for a reduction in his
sentence, which could be a maximum of 403 years.
   Asked to comment on accusations by Los Angeles Police Chief Daryl
Gates that ZZZZ Best may have laundered money for East Coast
mobsters, the U.S. attorney said that aspect of the case was in the
hands of local authorities.
   ``There's certainly some smoke there,'' he said.
   The Police Department's top spokesman, Cmdr. William Booth, said
this week that investigation continues.
   One of the prosecutors, Assistant U.S. Attorney James Asperger,
said that of the $65 million to $70 million believed invested in or
paid to ZZZZ Best, most seems to have been spent by the high-living
Minkow and other defendants. Virtually none appears to be available
for restitution to investors, bankers, brokers and other victims,
whom Minkow numbered in the thousands, Asperger said.
</TEXT>
