<HEAD>Holly Farms Reports Increased Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holly Farms Corp. said Tuesday its
second-quarter earnings more than tripled while sales rose nearly 25
percent.
   Holly said that for the period ending Nov. 30, its earnings
totaled $22.2 million, or $1.22 a share, compared with $8.5 million,
or 49 cents a share, during the second quarter of 1987.
   The poultry and food processor said its sales totaled $479.4
million, up from $384.9 million.
   Profits for the six-month period ending Nov. 30 rose to $52
million, or $2.87 per share, compared with net income of $19.3
million, or $1.10 per share, in the first six months of fiscal 1987.
   First-half sales totaled $983.6 million, compared with $768.4
million.
   Holly Farms announced Nov. 17 it would accept a stock-swap offer
from ConAgra of Omaha, Neb., to avoid a $1.1 billion takeover bid by
Tyson Foods Inc. of Springdale, Ark.
   Tyson has challenged the proposed merger, saying it cannot take
place as a planned pooling of interests, which occurs when companies
combine balance sheets after a merger leaving the original firm's
assets, liabilities and owners' equity relatively unchanged.
   Holly Farms has rejected cash offers of $52 and $54 a share from
Tyson.
   Holly Farms is the nation's second largest poultry processor,
while Tyson is the largest.
</TEXT>
