<HEAD>Investors Make Merger Offer for Fairchild Industries</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Fthenakis is cq in 5th graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Carlyle Group, a Washington investment and
banking firm, said Tuesday it had offered some $200 million cash for
the stock of aerospace manufacturer Fairchild Industries Inc. it
does not already own.
   Carlyle described the proposal as friendly and said its $15.50 a
share offer represented a premium of 53 percent of the closing
market price per share on July 25, 1988, when its general partner,
Carlyle Investors VI, began accumulating Fairchild shares.
   Carlyle Investors VI owns 9.9 percent of the outstanding shares
of Fairchild and is the second largest shareholder of record,
Carlyle said. Based on Fairchild's roughly 14.3 million common
shares outstanding, the offer is worth about $198.4 million for the
stock Carlyle does not already own.
   Fairchild stock closed unchanged at $13.37{ a share Tuesday on
the New York Stock Exchange.
   Fairchild, which is based in Chantilly, Va., is a designer and
maker of aerospace systems, components, plastics tooling and
communications equipment. The company posted a profit of $21.7
million, or $1.11 a share, on sales of $399.3 million in the first
nine months of this year.
   Carlyle said it made the offer Tuesday in a letter to Emanuel
Fthenakis, Fairchild's chairman.
   The Carlyle Group is a private investment and merchant banking
firm located in Washington. The Carlyle Group is the general partner
of Carlyle Investors VI, also a Delaware limited partnership.
   Two of the principal partners of the Carlyle Group are T. Rowe
Price and Associates, the Baltimore-based investment company, and
the Richard King Mellon family.
