<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 2035EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-TexacoSettlement     12-20 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Texaco Settlement,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texaco Unit To Pay $8.95 Million To Settle California Waste Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Texaco Inc. subsidiary has agreed to
pay $8.95 million to settle a state complaint that it improperly
stored hazardous wastes at its Bakersfield facility, state officials
said Tuesday.
   Attorney General John Van de Kamp and state Health Director
Kenneth Kizer called the settlement the largest ever reached under
California's hazardous waste law and possibly the biggest of its
kind in the country.
   ``The severity of the penalties imposed in this case are matched
by the seriousness of the violations and by the potential threat to
public health and safety,'' Van de Kamp said at a Capitol news
conference.
   He said state investigators found about 5,000 steel drums
containing hazardous waste at the Texaco Refining and Marketing Inc.
facility in northwest Bakersfield. About 2,000 of the drums were
leaking, corroded or open and more than 3,000 of them were not
labeled, he said.
   Van de Kamp and Kizer said they had no indication that the waste
had leaked into groundwater, but Van de Kamp said the situation at
the refinery could have been disasterous if there was a fire.
   Texaco spokesmen said the waste posed ``no significant risk to
either our employees, the environment or the community.'' They said
the company agreed to the settlement to avoid the costs of fighting
the case in court.
   ``While technically hazardous waste, the vast majority of the
materials were relatively inert and would not be considered to be
hazardous outside California,'' said Robert Hammond, a spokesman for
Texaco USA.
   ``Furthermore, procedures exist in the California regulations
under which Texaco could have sought and, we are confident, obtained
approvals from the Department of Health Services to treat most of
the material involved as non-hazardous.''
   Hammond and Bill Bresnick, an attorney for Texaco, said most of
the material stored in the drums already was there when Texaco
purchased property next to its facility from Tosco Corp. in 1986.
   Most of the drums have been removed, Texaco officials said. The
company is required to remove the remaining drums within 90 days,
state officials said.
   Under the settlement, Texaco Refining and Marketing will pay $4.5
million in civil penalties, $500,000 to cover administrative and
investigative costs and at least $3.95 million to reduce waste
production and improve waste handling procedures at its facilities.
   Kizer said the violations found by state inspectors included
storing waste for longer than allowed without a permit, storing
incompatible wastes next to each other, storing waste in unlabeled
containers, and storing waste in open and unsafe conditions.
   According to the complaint, the department first found improper
storage of waste at the site during a partial inspection in
September 1986. The complaint was filed last week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
