<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Economy-Glance 1stLd-Writethru f0157 12-20 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0157,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inflation, Economic Growth Both Slow</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, bgng: ``Inflation slowed...'' to make CPI
gain 0.25 percent sted 0.3 percent, which had been a rounded-off
figure used by the federal government; picks up 3rd graf pvs, bgng:
``The new...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are Tuesday's economic reports from the
federal government.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Inflation:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Inflation slowed in November to an annual rate of 3 percent as
clothing prices fell and food stabilized. The Consumer Price Index,
after seasonal adjustment, rose 0.25 percent. That followed a 0.4
percent gain in October.
   The new figures slowed the annual inflation rate from 4.6 percent
for the first 10 months of the year to 4.4 percent for the first 11
months.
   Another month similar to November could enable the Reagan
administration to leave office on target for inflation of 4.3
percent for 1988.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Gross National Product:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The summer's drought held the gross national product to a
moderate 2.5 percent annual growth in the July-September quarter.
Growth in the GNP, the broadest measure of economic health, slowed
from 3.0 percent in the second quarter and 3.4 percent in the first
quarter.
   The drought knocked $12.3 billion off the GNP, which was $4.01
trillion on an annual basis, adjusted for inflation and season.
Excluding the drought, the GNP grew 3.9 percent in the second
quarter and 3.0 percent in the third.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Corporate Profits:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   U.S. corporations reported that third-quarter profits rose $6.4
billion or 3.9 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual $169.1
billion. That was down from a robust 8.9 percent increase in the
second quarter.
   Dividend payments to stockholders rose 2.5 percent to $105.7
billion in the third quarter, compared with a 1.8 percent gain in
the second quarter.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Weekly Earnings:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Americans' average weekly earnings, after adjusting for
inflation, plunged 0.8 percent in November after jumping 0.7 percent
in October.
   The November decline stemmed from a 0.6 percent drop in the
number of hours worked and a 0.1 percent decline in average earnings
per hour, the first drop since February. Together, the drops more
than offset a 0.2 percent increase in prices as measured by a
special index for urban wage earners.
   Average weekly earnings in November, before adjusting for
inflation, were $327.92, only 3.2 percent higher than a year ago.
Taking the 4.1 percent inflation rate for urban workers into account
over the 12 months, real weekly earnings are 1 percent lower than a
year ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
